{"title_page": "Nawaraj Parajuli", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=March 2019}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Nawaraj Parajuli\n| image              = \n| birth_date         = <!-- {{birth date and age|df=y|1987|2|11}} -->\n| birth_place        = Nepal\n| nationality        = Nepalese\n| education          = M.ED in English Education\n| alma_mater         = [[Tribhuvan University]]\n| occupation         = Poet, lecturer Artist\n| employer           = \n| known_for          = Poetry\n}}\n'''Nawaraj Parajuli''' is a [[Nepalis|Nepalese]] poet, best known for starting the trend of \"Kabita concerts\" where a poet recites poems to music.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.977mag.net/poet-nawawaj-parajuli-explores-his-journey-towards-poetry/|title=Poet Nawawaj Parajuli Explores His Journey Towards Poetry|date=5 April 2018|work=Nepali Film News|access-date=2018-04-13|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 a collection of his poems was published by Fineprint Inc., titled \"Sagarmatha Ko Gahirai\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nepalibytes.com/nawaraj-parajuli-announces-australia-tour-for-poetry-concert/|title=Nawaraj Parajuli announces Australia Tour For Poetry Concert|date=17 June 2017|work=nepali bytes|access-date=2018-04-13|language=en-US}}</ref> His anthology of poetry ''Sagarmatha ko Gahirahi'' was awarded the 2017 Padmashree Award by the Khemkala-Harikala Lamichhane Foundation.<ref name=\"padmashree\">{{Cite news|url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/news/2017-09-01/parajulis-sagarmatha-ko-gahirahi-bags-padmashree-award.html|title=Parajuli's Sagarmatha ko Gahirahi bags Padmashree award|access-date=2018-04-13|language=en}}</ref>''Sagarmatha ko Gahirahi'' was also nominated for the [[Madan Puraskar]] award.{{citation needed|date=April 2018}} His poem ''Hebbi Badde'' (\"Happy Birthday\")  is for the son who is gone abroad.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://neostuffs.com/2017/01/poem-mothers-love-will-hit-right-feels/|title=This Poem About A Mother's Love Will Hit You Right in the Feels|date=10 January 2017|work=NeoStuffs|access-date=2018-04-13|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ecanadanepal.com/2018/03/poet-nawaraj-parajuli-speaks-about-love.html|title=Poet Nawaraj Parajuli Speaks About Love|website=www.ecanadanepal.com|access-date=2018-04-13}}</ref>\n\n==Concert tours==\nParajauli went on a six-city tour of Australia in 2017, accompanied by flutist Samyak Maharjan, guitarist Chet Pun and poet Shuvechchhya Pradhan. At the event in [[Sydney]], the organisers also honoured his contributions to Nepali language and literature.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/printedition/news/2017-07-26/poet-parajuli-serenades-sydney.html|title=Poet Parajuli serenades Sydney|access-date=2018-04-13|language=en}}</ref> He went on a poetry tour of the United Kingdom in 2018, to support children who were affected during the [[Nepalese Civil War]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nepalexpress.live/nepali-poem-concert-inuk|title=Nepali Poem Concert in UK with Nabaraj Parajuli|website=Nepal Express Live|language=en-US|access-date=2018-04-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nepalconsulate.net.au/hon-consul-general-attends-kabita-concert-celebrating-depth/|title=Hon. Consul General Attends 'Kabita Concert: Celebrating Depth' \u2013 Consulate General of Nepal in Victoria|date=10 August 2017|work=Consulate General of Nepal in Victoria|access-date=2018-04-13|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== Acting ==\nHe acted in the play ''Malini'' when it toured Europe in 2017, along with Rajendra Shrestha, Sujan Oli, Dipesh Rai, Jeni Subedi, Dilip Ranabhat and Bipul Pandey .<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/printedition/news/2017-06-20/theatre-villages-malini-to-travel-to-europe.html|title=Theatre Village's Malini to travel to Europe|access-date=2018-04-13|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and recognition==\n* Winner, Nepal Slam Poetry 2014<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/news/2014-07-15/winners-of-the-first-all-nepali-slam-poetry-declared.html|title=Winners of the First All Nepali Slam Poetry declared|access-date=2018-04-13|language=en}}</ref>\n* His book Nominated for Madan Puraskar.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.myrepublica.com/news/26425/?categoryId=81|title='Dhritarastra' wins Madan Puraskar ; Batsayan awarded with Jagadamba Shree|work=My Republica|access-date=2018-04-13|language=en}}</ref>\n* His book won Padmashree<ref name=\"padmashree\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Parajuli, Nawaraj}}\n[[Category:Nepalese male poets]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Nepalese poets]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=March 2019}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Nawaraj Parajuli\n| image              = \n| birth_date         = <!-- {{birth date and age|df=y|2045|04|23}} -->\n| birth_place        = Nepal\n| nationality        = Nepalese\n| education          = MA\n| alma_mater         = [[Tribhuvan University]]\n| occupation         = Poet, lecturer Artist\n| employer           = \n| known_for          = Poetry\n}}\n'''Nawaraj Parajuli''' is a [[Nepalis|Nepalese]] poet, best known for starting the trend of \"Kabita concerts\" where a poet recites poems to music.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.977mag.net/poet-nawawaj-parajuli-explores-his-journey-towards-poetry/|title=Poet Nawawaj Parajuli Explores His Journey Towards Poetry|date=5 April 2018|work=Nepali Film News|access-date=2018-04-13|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 a collection of his poems was published by Fineprint Inc., titled \"Sagarmatha Ko Gahirai\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nepalibytes.com/nawaraj-parajuli-announces-australia-tour-for-poetry-concert/|title=Nawaraj Parajuli announces Australia Tour For Poetry Concert|date=17 June 2017|work=nepali bytes|access-date=2018-04-13|language=en-US}}</ref> His anthology of poetry ''Sagarmatha ko Gahirahi'' was awarded the 2017 Padmashree Award by the Khemkala-Harikala Lamichhane Foundation.<ref name=\"padmashree\">{{Cite news|url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/news/2017-09-01/parajulis-sagarmatha-ko-gahirahi-bags-padmashree-award.html|title=Parajuli's Sagarmatha ko Gahirahi bags Padmashree award|access-date=2018-04-13|language=en}}</ref>''Sagarmatha ko Gahirahi'' was also nominated for the [[Madan Puraskar]] award.{{citation needed|date=April 2018}} His poem ''Hebbi Badde'' (\"Happy Birthday\")  is for the son who is gone abroad.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://neostuffs.com/2017/01/poem-mothers-love-will-hit-right-feels/|title=This Poem About A Mother's Love Will Hit You Right in the Feels|date=10 January 2017|work=NeoStuffs|access-date=2018-04-13|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ecanadanepal.com/2018/03/poet-nawaraj-parajuli-speaks-about-love.html|title=Poet Nawaraj Parajuli Speaks About Love|website=www.ecanadanepal.com|access-date=2018-04-13}}</ref>\n\n==Concert tours==\nParajauli went on a six-city tour of Australia in 2017, accompanied by flutist Samyak Maharjan, guitarist Chet Pun and poet Shuvechchhya Pradhan. At the event in [[Sydney]], the organisers also honoured his contributions to Nepali language and literature.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/printedition/news/2017-07-26/poet-parajuli-serenades-sydney.html|title=Poet Parajuli serenades Sydney|access-date=2018-04-13|language=en}}</ref> He went on a poetry tour of the United Kingdom in 2018, to support children who were affected during the [[Nepalese Civil War]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nepalexpress.live/nepali-poem-concert-inuk|title=Nepali Poem Concert in UK with Nabaraj Parajuli|website=Nepal Express Live|language=en-US|access-date=2018-04-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nepalconsulate.net.au/hon-consul-general-attends-kabita-concert-celebrating-depth/|title=Hon. Consul General Attends 'Kabita Concert: Celebrating Depth' \u2013 Consulate General of Nepal in Victoria|date=10 August 2017|work=Consulate General of Nepal in Victoria|access-date=2018-04-13|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== Acting ==\nHe acted in the play ''Malini'' when it toured Europe in 2017, along with Rajendra Shrestha, Sujan Oli, Dipesh Rai, Jeni Subedi, Dilip Ranabhat and Bipul Pandey .<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/printedition/news/2017-06-20/theatre-villages-malini-to-travel-to-europe.html|title=Theatre Village's Malini to travel to Europe|access-date=2018-04-13|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and recognition==\n* Winner, Nepal Slam Poetry 2014<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/news/2014-07-15/winners-of-the-first-all-nepali-slam-poetry-declared.html|title=Winners of the First All Nepali Slam Poetry declared|access-date=2018-04-13|language=en}}</ref>\n* His book Nominated for Madan Puraskar.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.myrepublica.com/news/26425/?categoryId=81|title='Dhritarastra' wins Madan Puraskar ; Batsayan awarded with Jagadamba Shree|work=My Republica|access-date=2018-04-13|language=en}}</ref>\n* His book won Padmashree<ref name=\"padmashree\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Parajuli, Nawaraj}}\n[[Category:Nepalese male poets]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Nepalese poets]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Tkafle.123", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nawaraj_Parajuli"}
{"title_page": "Mary (2019 film)", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Mary\n| image          = Mary poster.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Michael Goi]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* Scott Lambert\n* D. Scott Lumpkin\n* Mason McGowin\n* Alexandra Milchan\n* [[Tucker Tooley]]\n}}\n| writer         = Anthony Jaswinski\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Gary Oldman]]\n* [[Emily Mortimer]]\n* [[Manuel Garcia-Rulfo]]\n* [[Stefanie Scott]]\n* Chloe Perrin\n* [[Douglas Urbanski]]\n* [[Jennifer Esposito]]\n* [[Owen Teague]]\n}}<!--PER POSTER BILLING BLOCK-->\n| music          = [[The Newton Brothers]]\n| cinematography = Michael Goi\n| editing        = [[Jeff Betancourt]]\n| production companies = {{Plainlist|\n* Tooley Entertainment\n* [[Entertainment One]]\n}}\n| distributor    = [[RLJE Films]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2019|08|24|FrightFest|ref1=<ref>http://www.frightfest.co.uk/2019films/index.html</ref>|2019|10|11}}\n| runtime        = 84 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n}}\n'''''Mary''''' is a 2019 American [[horror film|horror]] film, directed by [[Michael Goi]], from a screenplay by Anthony Jaswinski. It stars [[Gary Oldman]], [[Emily Mortimer]], [[Manuel Garcia-Rulfo]], [[Stefanie Scott]], Chloe Perrin, [[Douglas Urbanski]], [[Jennifer Esposito]], [[Owen Teague]]\n\n==Plot==\nAfter being found drifting on the wreckage of a sailing boat and rescued by the [[Coast Guard]], Sarah and her two daughters are taken into police custody. Sarah is interrogated by Detective Clarkson, who Sarah claims will not believe what happened onboard the boat. Clarkson asks to hear anyway and Sarah tells her what occurred:\n\nSarah's husband David, a helmsman on a tourist ferry, impulsively buys a salvaged sailing boat that had been discovered abandoned by the Coast Guard. David intends to take Sarah and their two daughters, teenager Lindsay and ten-year old Mary, on a trip to [[Bermuda]], as a way to strengthen the family\u2019s bond after Sarah had an affair. The family restores the ship, and David names it Mary after his daughter. While David christens the boat, Lindsay's boyfriend and David's protege Tommy sees a bright flash of light emanate from the note while taking a photo.\n\nDavid, Sarah, Mary, Lindsay, Tommy, and David's friend and Sarah's one-time lover Mike set sail for Bermuda. Mary gains an imaginary friend, a woman she claims lives on the boat, and begins making sinister crayon drawings of her friend. On the first night out, David hears a noise from above deck and investigates. He finds Tommy, who has non-fatally stabbed himself with a knife. Tommy attacks David with the knife and is promptly subdued. David has Tommy confined to a mental institution on the [[Abaco Islands]], and he and Sarah resolve to keep this a secret from the others, which strains Sarah and David's relationship with Lindsay. David later receives word that Tommy hanged himself, much to his horror. Sarah later discovers Mary had drawn a picture of a hangman earlier. Numerous supernatural activity occurs, such as footprints mysteriously appearing, Sarah experiencing vivid nightmares, and Sarah being locked inside the cabin and seeing the apparition of a woman.\n\nTension grows between the crew. Mary smashes a glass on Lindsay's face, and David and Sarah begin to fight constantly, as Sarah wants to turn back while David wants to continue the trip. Sarah and David separately research the history of the boat, and discover that its previous owners had disappeared in similar trips, and all sailed to the same destination; it is implied the boat is possessed by the spirit of a witch who is attempting to replace her children after being drowned.\n\nDavid and Sarah agree to turn back, and David orders Mike to change course. David heads mysterious noises topside, and discovers Mike, now under the control of the witch, has destroyed the sails, drains the ship of gas, and thrown the satellite phone overboard, and that the boat is caught in a torrential storm. Mike attacks David, but is knocked unconscious and trapped inside one of the cabins. Lindsay sees Tommy's ghost, and is convinced to commit suicide by jumping overboard, though she is saved at the last minute by Sarah. Mike is released from the cabin, and stabs David and knocks Sarah unconscious. Sarah awakens, tied up, and watches as Mike tosses David overboard. Mike does the same to Sarah, but she is able to climb back onboard. She attacks Mike, but he gains the upper hand. David, still alive, appears and shoots Mike with a harpoon gun. Mike falls overboard, and Sarah rescues Lindsay and Mary from the cabin she had been locked in. Sarah sends Lindsay and Mary overboard in life jackets while David steers the boat. Before Sarah can leave, David is killed by the witch, who attacks Sarah. Sarah fires a flare gun at the witch, and causes the boat to explode.\n\nAt the police station, Detective Clarkson concludes Sarah is a murderer and delusional, and has her escorted away by a police officer. Clarkson intends to make sure Sarah never gets custody of her daughters. As she checks footage of the interrogation, Clarkson discovers video distortions, and that Sarah is possessed by a witch. Clarkson heads a noise from the room where Sarah had been taken, and discovers the officer who escorted her dead and Sarah gone, having escaped through the window. The final shot reveals that the area surrounding the police station is going through a torrential storm like the one that happened around the boat.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Gary Oldman]] as David\n* [[Emily Mortimer]] as Sarah\n* [[Owen Teague]] as Tommy\n* [[Manuel Garcia-Rulfo]] as Mike \u00c1lvarez\n* [[Jennifer Esposito]] as Detective Clarkson\n* [[Stefanie Scott]] as Lindsay\n* Chloe Perrin as Mary\n* [[Douglas Urbanski]] as Jay\n\n==Production==\nIn June 2016, Anthony Jaswinski was announced to write the script for the film, with [[Tucker Tooley]] producing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/06/the-shallows-anthony-jaswinski-mary-haunted-ship-tooley-productions-spec-script-1201778924/|title=Haunted Ship Spec By \u2018Shallows\u2019 Scribe Anthony Jaswinski Anchors At Tooley Productions|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Mike|last=Fleming Jr|date=June 24, 2016|accessdate=July 12, 2019}}</ref> In September 2017, it was announced [[Gary Oldman]], [[Emily Mortimer]], [[Owen Teague]], [[Manuel Garcia-Rulfo]], [[Stefanie Scott]] and Chloe Perrin had joined the cast of the film, with [[Michael Goi]], directing from a screenplay by Anthony Jaswinski.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/gary-oldman-star-supernatural-thriller-mary-1035239|title=Gary Oldman to Star in Supernatural Thriller 'Mary' (Exclusive)|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|first=Borys|last=Kit|date=September 5, 2017|accessdate=July 12, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/09/stefanie-scott-manuel-garcia-rulfo-chloe-perrin-supernatural-thriller-movie-mary-1202178374/|title=Stefanie Scott, Manuel Garcia-Rulfo & Chloe Perrin Join Thriller \u2018Mary\u2019|website=Deadline Hollywood|first=Anita|last=Busch|date=September 28, 2017|accessdate=July 12, 2019}}</ref> In August 2018, [[Jennifer Esposito]] joined the cast of the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/jennifer-esposito-gary-oldman-film/|title=Jennifer Esposito to Appear in Gary Oldman Supernatural Thriller \u2018Mary\u2019|website=[[The Wrap]]|first=Umberto|last=Gonzalez|date=August 24, 2018|accessdate=July 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nIn July 2019, [[RLJE Films]] acquired distribution rights to the film and set it for release on October 11, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/07/mary-movie-gary-oldman-emily-mortimer-release-date-rlje-films-1202644201/|title=Gary Oldman-Emily Mortimer Thriller \u2018Mary\u2019 Docks At RLJE Films For Fall Release|website=Deadline Hollywood|first=Patrick|last=Hipes|date=July 10, 2019|accessdate=July 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Expand section|date=October 2019}}\nThe film received largely negative reviews from critics. On the [[review aggregator]] [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 4%, based on 23 reviews, with an average rating of 3.36/10. The consensus reads, \"Misguided from stem to stern, ''Mary'' wastes the talents of an outstanding cast -- and makes a soggy mess of its supernatural horror story.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/mary_2019|title=Mary (2019)|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango Media]]|url-status=live|accessdate=October 17, 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 31 out of 100, based on 12 critics, indicating \"generally unfavorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/mary-2019|title=Mary (2019)|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=October 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|5834854}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|Mary_2019}}\n* {{Metacritic film|mary-2019}}\n\n[[Category:2019 films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American drama films]]\n[[Category:American supernatural horror films]]\n[[Category:Entertainment One films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Mary\n| image          = Mary poster.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Michael Goi]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* Scott Lambert\n* D. Scott Lumpkin\n* Mason McGowin\n* Alexandra Milchan\n* [[Tucker Tooley]]\n}}\n| writer         = Anthony Jaswinski\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Gary Oldman]]\n* [[Emily Mortimer]]\n* [[Manuel Garcia-Rulfo]]\n* [[Stefanie Scott]]\n* Chloe Perrin\n* [[Douglas Urbanski]]\n* [[Jennifer Esposito]]\n* [[Owen Teague]]\n}}<!--PER POSTER BILLING BLOCK-->\n| music          = [[The Newton Brothers]]\n| cinematography = Michael Goi\n| editing        = [[Jeff Betancourt]]\n| production companies = {{Plainlist|\n* Tooley Entertainment\n* [[Entertainment One]]\n}}\n| distributor    = [[RLJE Films]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2019|08|24|FrightFest|ref1=<ref>http://www.frightfest.co.uk/2019films/index.html</ref>|2019|10|11}}\n| runtime        = 84 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n}}\n'''''Mary''''' is a 2019 American [[horror film|horror]] film, directed by [[Michael Goi]], from a screenplay by Anthony Jaswinski. It stars [[Gary Oldman]], [[Emily Mortimer]], [[Manuel Garcia-Rulfo]], [[Stefanie Scott]], Chloe Perrin, [[Douglas Urbanski]], [[Jennifer Esposito]], [[Owen Teague]]\n\n==Plot==\nAfter being found drifting on the wreckage of a sailing boat and rescued by the [[Coast Guard]], Sarah and her two daughters are taken into police custody. Sarah is interrogated by Detective Clarkson, who Sarah claims will not believe what happened onboard the boat. Clarkson asks to hear anyway and Sarah tells her what occured:\n\nSarah's husband David, a helmsman on a tourist ferry, impulsively buys a salvaged sailing boat that had been discovered abandoned by the Coast Guard. David intends to take Sarah and their two daughters, teenager Lindsay and ten-year old Mary, on a trip to [[Bermuda]], as a way to strengthen the family\u2019s bond after Sarah had an affair. The family restores the ship, and David names it Mary after his daughter. While David christens the boat, Lindsay's boyfriend and David's protege Tommy sees a bright flash of light emanate from the note while taking a photo.\n\nDavid, Sarah, Mary, Lindsay, Tommy, and David's friend and Sarah's one-time lover Mike set sail for Bermuda. Mary gains an imaginary friend, a woman she claims lives on the boat, and begins making sinister crayon drawings of her friend. On the first night out, David hears a noise from above deck and investigates. He finds Tommy, who has non-fatally stabbed himself with a knife. Tommy attacks David with the knife and is promptly subdued. David has Tommy confined to a mental institution on the [[Abaco Islands]], and he and Sarah resolve to keep this a secret from the others, which strains Sarah and David's relationship with Lindsay. David later receives word that Tommy hanged himself, much to his horror. Sarah later discovers Mary had drawn a picture of a hangman earlier. Numerous supernatural activity occurs, such as footprints mysteriously appearing, Sarah experiencing vivid nightmares, and Sarah being locked inside the cabin and seeing the apparition of a woman.\n\nTension grows between the crew. Mary smashes a glass on Lindsay's face, and David and Sarah begin to fight constantly, as Sarah wants to turn back while David wants to continue the trip. Sarah and David separately research the history of the boat, and discover that its previous owners had disappeared in similar trips, and all sailed to the same destination; it is implied the boat is possessed by the spirit of a witch who is attempting to replace her children after being drowned.\n\nDavid and Sarah agree to turn back, and David orders Mike to change course. David heads mysterious noises topside, and discovers Mike, now under the control of the witch, has destroyed the sails, drains the ship of gas, and thrown the satellite phone overboard, and that the boat is caught in a torrential storm. Mike attacks David, but is knocked unconscious and trapped inside one of the cabins. Lindsay sees Tommy's ghost, and is convinced to commit suicide by jumping overboard, though she is saved at the last minute by Sarah. Mike is released from the cabin, and stabs David and knocks Sarah unconscious. Sarah awakens, tied up, and watches as Mike tosses David overboard. Mike does the same to Sarah, but she is able to climb back onboard. She attacks Mike, but he gains the upper hand. David, still alive, appears and shoots Mike with a harpoon gun. Mike falls overboard, and Sarah rescues Lindsay and Mary from the cabin she had been locked in. Sarah sends Lindsay and Mary overboard in life jackets while David steers the boat. Before Sarah can leave, David is killed by the witch, who attacks Sarah. Sarah fires a flare gun at the witch, and causes the boat to explode.\n\nAt the police station, Detective Clarkson concludes Sarah is a murderer and delusional, and has her escorted away by a police officer. Clarkson intends to make sure Sarah never gets custody of her daughters. As she checks footage of the interrogation, Clarkson discovers video distortions, and that Sarah is possessed by a witch. Clarkson heads a noise from the room where Sarah had been taken, and discovers the officer who escorted her dead and Sarah gone, having escaped through the window. The final shot reveals that the area surrounding the police station is going through a torrential storm like the one that happened around the boat.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Gary Oldman]] as David\n* [[Emily Mortimer]] as Sarah\n* [[Owen Teague]] as Tommy\n* [[Manuel Garcia-Rulfo]] as Mike \u00c1lvarez\n* [[Jennifer Esposito]] as Detective Clarkson\n* [[Stefanie Scott]] as Lindsay\n* Chloe Perrin as Mary\n* [[Douglas Urbanski]] as Jay\n\n==Production==\nIn June 2016, Anthony Jaswinski was announced to write the script for the film, with [[Tucker Tooley]] producing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/06/the-shallows-anthony-jaswinski-mary-haunted-ship-tooley-productions-spec-script-1201778924/|title=Haunted Ship Spec By \u2018Shallows\u2019 Scribe Anthony Jaswinski Anchors At Tooley Productions|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Mike|last=Fleming Jr|date=June 24, 2016|accessdate=July 12, 2019}}</ref> In September 2017, it was announced [[Gary Oldman]], [[Emily Mortimer]], [[Owen Teague]], [[Manuel Garcia-Rulfo]], [[Stefanie Scott]] and Chloe Perrin had joined the cast of the film, with [[Michael Goi]], directing from a screenplay by Anthony Jaswinski.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/gary-oldman-star-supernatural-thriller-mary-1035239|title=Gary Oldman to Star in Supernatural Thriller 'Mary' (Exclusive)|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|first=Borys|last=Kit|date=September 5, 2017|accessdate=July 12, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/09/stefanie-scott-manuel-garcia-rulfo-chloe-perrin-supernatural-thriller-movie-mary-1202178374/|title=Stefanie Scott, Manuel Garcia-Rulfo & Chloe Perrin Join Thriller \u2018Mary\u2019|website=Deadline Hollywood|first=Anita|last=Busch|date=September 28, 2017|accessdate=July 12, 2019}}</ref> In August 2018, [[Jennifer Esposito]] joined the cast of the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/jennifer-esposito-gary-oldman-film/|title=Jennifer Esposito to Appear in Gary Oldman Supernatural Thriller \u2018Mary\u2019|website=[[The Wrap]]|first=Umberto|last=Gonzalez|date=August 24, 2018|accessdate=July 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nIn July 2019, [[RLJE Films]] acquired distribution rights to the film and set it for release on October 11, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/07/mary-movie-gary-oldman-emily-mortimer-release-date-rlje-films-1202644201/|title=Gary Oldman-Emily Mortimer Thriller \u2018Mary\u2019 Docks At RLJE Films For Fall Release|website=Deadline Hollywood|first=Patrick|last=Hipes|date=July 10, 2019|accessdate=July 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Expand section|date=October 2019}}\nThe film received largely negative reviews from critics. On the [[review aggregator]] [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 4%, based on 23 reviews, with an average rating of 3.36/10. The consensus reads, \"Misguided from stem to stern, ''Mary'' wastes the talents of an outstanding cast -- and makes a soggy mess of its supernatural horror story.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/mary_2019|title=Mary (2019)|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango Media]]|url-status=live|accessdate=October 17, 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 31 out of 100, based on 12 critics, indicating \"generally unfavorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/mary-2019|title=Mary (2019)|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=October 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|5834854}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|Mary_2019}}\n* {{Metacritic film|mary-2019}}\n\n[[Category:2019 films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American drama films]]\n[[Category:American supernatural horror films]]\n[[Category:Entertainment One films]]\n", "name_user": "Orenburg1", "label": "safe", "comment": "sp", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mary_(2019_film)"}
{"title_page": "The International Pharmacopoeia", "text_new": "{{italic title}}\n'''''The International Pharmacopoeia''''' ('''''Pharmacopoeia Internationalis''''', '''''Ph. Int.''''') is a [[pharmacopoeia]] issued by the [[World Health Organization]]<ref name=\"apps_who_int_PhInt\">{{Citation |author=WHO |authorlink=World Health Organization |year=2018 |title=The International Pharmacopoeia |edition=8th |url=http://apps.who.int/phint/ |postscript=.}}</ref> as a recommendation, with the aim to provide international quality specifications for pharmaceutical substances (active ingredients and [[excipient]]s) and [[dosage form]]s, together with supporting general methods of analysis, for global use. Its texts can be used or adapted by any WHO member state wishing to establish legal pharmaceutical requirements.\n\nThe ''Ph.Int.'' is based primarily on medicines included in the current WHO Model List of Essential Medicines (EML) and medicines included in the current invitations to manufacturers to submit an expression of interest (EOI) to the WHO Prequalification Team \u2013 Medicines (PQT) and those of interest to other UN Organizations. In recent years, priority has been given to medicines of importance in low and middle income countries, which may not appear in any other pharmacopoeias, including child-friendly dosage forms.\n\nThe ''Ph.Int.'' is designed to serve all Member States, especially their national and regional regulatory authorities, organizations in the United Nations system, and regional and interregional harmonization efforts, and they underpin important public health initiatives, including the prequalification and procurement of quality medicines through major international entities, such as the Global Fund to Fight AIDS, Tuberculosis and Malaria, and UNICEF.\n\nThe monographs published in the ''Ph.Int.'' are established in an independent manner via a consultative procedure and based on international experience. <ref>[http://www.who.int/medicines/publications/pharmacopoeia/Annex1-TRS992.pdf?ua=1 Procedure for the development of monographs and other texts for The International Pharmacopoeia]</ref>\nMonographs on radiopharmaceuticals developed with the International Atomic Energy Agency.\n\n== Editions ==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" border=\"1\"\n|-\n! Sort !! Edition number !! Year !! Medium !! Notes\n|-\n| 1 || First Edition || 1951 || Print || 2 volumes plus supplement\n|-\n| 2 || Second Edition || 1967 || Print || \n|-\n| 3 || Third Edition || 1979 || Print || 5 volumes\n|-\n| 4 || Fourth Edition || 2006|| Print or CD-ROM || 2 volumes\n|-\n| 5 || Fifth Edition || 2015 || online || \n|-\n| 6 || Sixth Edition || 2016 || online ||\n|-\n| 7 || Seventh Edition || 2017 || online ||\n|-\n| 8 || Eighth Edition || 2018 <ref name=\"apps_who_int_PhInt\"/> || online<ref name=\"apps_who_int_PhInt\"/> ||\n|-\n| 9 || Ninth Edition || 2019 || Online ||\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[European Pharmacopoeia]]'', another supranational pharmacopoeia\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official site|http://apps.who.int/phint/}}\n* [http://www.who.int/medicines/publications/pharmacopoeia/Annex1-TRS992.pdf?ua=1 Procedure for the development of monographs and other texts for The International Pharmacopoeia]. WHO Technical Report Series No. 992, 2015, Annex 1.\n* [http://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/handle/10665/42613/WHO_TRS_908.pdf?sequence=1#page=32 The International Pharmacopoeia: revised concepts and future perspectives]. WHO Technical Report Series, No. 908, 2003, Annex 2.\n* [http://www.who.int/medicines/areas/quality_safety/quality_assurance/projects/en/ Current projects: Monographs and general tests under review/revision for inclusion in the International Pharmacopoeia]\n* [http://www.who.int/medicines/publications/pharmacopoeia/radiopharm/en/ Radiopharmaceuticals]\n* [http://www.who.int/medicines/publications/pharmacopoeia/Annex2-TRS992.pdf?ua=1 Updating mechanism for the section on radiopharmaceuticals in The International Pharmacopoeia]. WHO Technical Report Series, No. 992, 2015, Annex 2.\n* [http://www.who.int/medicines/publications/pharmacopoeia/2015-08-26trade-names_stationary_phases-QAS15-640_04092015N.pdf?ua=1 Trade names of stationary phases found suitable in performing chromatographic tests described in The International Pharmacopoeia].\n* [http://www.who.int/medicines/publications/pharmacopoeia/pharm_int-omissions/en/ Omitted Monographs]\n* [http://www.who.int/medicines/services/expertcommittees/pharmprep/en/ WHO Expert Committee on Specifications for Pharmaceutical Preparations]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:International Pharmacopoeia, The}}\n[[Category:Pharmacopoeias]]\n", "text_old": "{{italic title}}\n'''''The International Pharmacopoeia''''' ('''''Pharmacopoeia Internationalis''''', '''''Ph. Int.''''') is a [[pharmacopoeia]] issued by the [[World Health Organization]]<ref name=\"apps_who_int_PhInt\">{{Citation |author=WHO |authorlink=World Health Organization |year=2018 |title=The International Pharmacopoeia |edition=8th |url=http://apps.who.int/phint/ |postscript=.}}</ref> as a recommendation, with the aim to provide international quality specifications for pharmaceutical substances (active ingredients and [[excipient]]s) and [[dosage form]]s, together with supporting general methods of analysis, for global use. Its texts can be used or adapted by any WHO member state wishing to establish legal pharmaceutical requirements.\n\nThe ''Ph.Int.'' is based primarily on medicines included in the current WHO Model List of Essential Medicines (EML) and medicines included in the current invitations to manufacturers to submit an expression of interest (EOI) to the WHO Prequalification Team \u2013 Medicines (PQT) and those of interest to other UN Organizations. In recent years, priority has been given to medicines of importance in low and middle income countries, which may not appear in any other pharmacopoeias, including child-friendly dosage forms.\n\nThe ''Ph.Int.'' is designed to serve all Member States, especially their national and regional regulatory authorities, organizations in the United Nations system, and regional and interregional harmonization efforts, and they underpin important public health initiatives, including the prequalification and procurement of quality medicines through major international entities, such as the Global Fund to Fight AIDS, Tuberculosis and Malaria, and UNICEF.\n\nThe monographs published in the ''Ph.Int.'' are established in an independent manner via a consultative procedure and based on international experience. <ref>[http://www.who.int/medicines/publications/pharmacopoeia/Annex1-TRS992.pdf?ua=1 Procedure for the development of monographs and other texts for The International Pharmacopoeia]</ref>\nMonographs on radiopharmaceuticals developed with the International Atomic Energy Agency.\n\n EDITIONS\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" border=\"1\"\n|-\n! Sort !! Edition number !! Year !! Medium !! Notes\n|-\n| 1 || First Edition || 1951 || Print || 2 volumes plus supplement\n|-\n| 2 || Second Edition || 1967 || Print || \n|-\n| 3 || Third Edition || 1979 || Print || 5 volumes\n|-\n| 4 || Fourth Edition || 2006|| Print or CD-ROM || 2 volumes\n|-\n| 5 || Fifth Edition || 2015 || online || \n|-\n| 6 || Sixth Edition || 2016 || online ||\n|-\n| 7 || Seventh Edition || 2017 || online ||\n|-\n| 8 || Eighth Edition || 2018 <ref name=\"apps_who_int_PhInt\"/> || online<ref name=\"apps_who_int_PhInt\"/> ||\n|-\n| 9 || Ninth Edition || 2019 || Online\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[European Pharmacopoeia]]'', another supranational pharmacopoeia\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official site|http://apps.who.int/phint/}}\n* [http://www.who.int/medicines/publications/pharmacopoeia/Annex1-TRS992.pdf?ua=1 Procedure for the development of monographs and other texts for The International Pharmacopoeia]. WHO Technical Report Series No. 992, 2015, Annex 1.\n* [http://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/ha