ewer.htm?point=353460:429105:150 Modern-day map of Preston] on Lancashire County Council's MARIO map system\n\n{{Railway stations in Lancashire}}\n{{City of Preston buildings}}\n{{City of Preston culture}}\n{{Major railway stations in Great Britain}}\n\n{{Good article}}\n\n[[Category:Railway stations in Preston]]\n[[Category:Former North Union Railway stations]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1838]]\n[[Category:Railway stations served by Caledonian Sleeper]]\n[[Category:Railway stations served by TransPennine Express]]\n[[Category:Northern franchise railway stations]]\n[[Category:Railway stations served by Avanti West Coast]]\n[[Category:Union stations in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Grade II listed buildings in Lancashire]]\n[[Category:Grade II listed railway stations]]\n[[Category:History of Preston]]\n[[Category:1838 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Preston, Lancashire]]\n", "name_user": "Kalmbach", "label": "safe", "comment": "Apostrophes do not make plurals.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Preston_railway_station"}
{"title_page": "Darius Boyd", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox rugby league biography\n|name          = Darius \u201cstink beetle\u201d Boyd\n|fullname      =\n|image         = Darius Boyd Broncos.jpg\n|imagesize     = 290\n|caption       = \n|position      = {{rlp|WG|FB|CE}}\n|birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1987|7|17}}\n|birth_place   = [[Gold Coast, Queensland, Australia]]\n|height        = {{convert|184|cm|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|weight        = {{convert|93|kg|stlb|abbr=on}}\n|retired       = no\n|club1         = [[Brisbane Broncos]]\n|year1start    = 2006\n|year1end      = 08\n|appearances1  = 74\n|tries1        = 32\n|goals1        = 0\n|fieldgoals1   = 0\n|points1       = 128\n|club2         = {{nowrap|[[St. George Illawarra Dragons|St. George Illawarra]]}}\n|year2start    = 2009\n|year2end      = 11\n|appearances2  = 70\n|tries2        = 13\n|goals2        = 0\n|fieldgoals2   = 0\n|points2       = 52\n|club3         = [[Newcastle Knights]]\n|year3start    = 2012\n|year3end      = 14\n|appearances3  = 62\n|tries3        = 17\n|goals3        = 0\n|fieldgoals3   = 0\n|points3       = 68\n|club4         = [[Brisbane Broncos]]\n|year4start    = 2015\n|year4end      = present\n|appearances4  = 115\n|tries4        = 22\n|goals4        = 0\n|fieldgoals4   = 0\n|points4       = 88\n|teamA         = [[Queensland rugby league team|Queensland]]\n|yearAstart    = 2008\n|yearAend      = 17\n|appearancesA  = 28\n|triesA        = 17\n|goalsA        = 0\n|fieldgoalsA   = 0\n|pointsA       = 68\n|teamB         = [[Australian national rugby league team|Australia]]\n|yearBstart    = 2008\n|yearBend      = 17\n|appearancesB  = 23\n|triesB        = 16\n|goalsB        = 0\n|fieldgoalsB   = 0\n|pointsB       = 64\n|teamC         = [[Prime Minister's XIII]]\n|yearCstart    = 2012\n|yearCend      = \n|appearancesC  = 1\n|triesC        = 0\n|goalsC        = 0\n|fieldgoalsC   = 0\n|pointsC       = 0\n|retited       = \n|source        = <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.loverugbyleague.com/stats/players/Darius-Boyd/ |title=Darius Boyd - Player Stats |publisher=Love Rugby League |date= |accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/players/darius-boyd/summary.html|title=Darius Boyd - Career Stats & Summary|publisher=Rugby League Project|date=|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref>\n|updated       = 17 September 2019\n}}\n\n'''Darius Boyd''' (born 17 July 1987) is an Australian professional [[rugby league]] footballer who plays as a {{rlp|fb}}, [[Five-eighth|five eighth]] and on the {{rlp|wg}} for the [[Brisbane Broncos]] in the [[National Rugby League|NRL]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://broncos.com.au/index.php?page_id=individual_player&player_id=73&team_id=1|accessdate=3 June 2008|publisher=[[Brisbane Broncos]]|title=Brisbane Broncos \u2013 Darius Boyd|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080720142058/http://www.broncos.com.au/index.php?page_id=individual_player&player_id=73&team_id=1|archive-date=20 July 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> and has played for [[Australia national rugby league team|Australia]] at international level and State of Origin for QLD. Boyd captained the Brisbane Broncos from 2017-2019.  \n\nBoyd previously played for the [[St. George Illawarra Dragons]] in 2009-2011 and the [[Newcastle Knights]] in 2012-2014 all under a single coach: [[Wayne Bennett (rugby league)|Wayne Bennett]] before switching back to Broncos in 2015. Boyd has won the [[2006 NRL Grand Final]] with the Broncos and the [[2010 NRL Grand Final]] with the [[St George Illawarra Dragons|Dragons]]. He is a [[Queensland rugby league team|Queensland]] [[State of Origin series|State of Origin]] and [[Prime Minister\u2019s XIII]] representative.\n\n==Early life==\nBoyd was born at the [[Gold Coast Hospital]], in [[Queensland, Australia]] on 17 July 1987. He was raised by his single mother throughout most of his childhood.<ref name=\"origindebut\"/>\n\nHe began playing junior football at a young age for the Parkwood Sharks, which led to playing at halftime during a [[Gold Coast Chargers|Gold Coast Seagulls]] match in 1993. He later switched clubs to the Mudgeeraba Redbacks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/darius-boyd-nrl-stars-pain-about-not-knowing-who-is-father-is/news-story/bc59091afe79587c8e9b4930b805c2f8 |title=Darius Boyd's Pain About Not Knowing Who His Father Is |website=Couriermail.com.au |accessdate=2017-06-05}}</ref> Boyd attended Robina State High School during this time but switched schools to the famed rugby league nursery, [[Palm Beach Currumbin High School]], in Year 10. It was at this point Boyd's mother became ill and he starting living with his grandmother, as well as spending periods of time living with football friend's families. {{Citation needed|date=March 2017}} Following graduation in 2004, he was not recruited by any NRL teams and decided to repeat Year 12 at PBC in the hope of garnering attention from NRL teams. The decision turned out to be a fruitful one with the [[Brisbane Broncos]] offering Boyd a scholarship, followed by a $20,000 contract for the [[2006 NRL season]]. {{Citation needed|date=March 2017}} Boyd was questioned by police in 2009 relating to an alleged sexual assault in a Brisbane nightclub.<ref>{{Cite news\n| last = Doneman\n| first = Paula \n| coauthors = \n| title = Woman breaks silence over Broncos nightclub sex scandal\n| work = [[The Courier Mail]]\n| place = Australia\n| page = \n| language = \n| publisher = [[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corp]]\n| date = 11 November 2009\n| url = https://amp.couriermail.com.au/news/national/woman-breaks-silence-over-broncos-scandal/news-story/264110c02c2f84439c71053337105806\n| accessdate = 10 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Playing career==\nIn 2005, while playing for Palm Beach Currumbin, Boyd was selected at fullback for the [[Australia national schoolboy rugby league team|Australian Schoolboys]] team.<ref>{{cite web|title=SportingPulse Homepage for Australian Secondary Schools Rugby League|url=http://www.sportingpulse.com/assoc_page.cgi?c=7-2130-0-0-0&sID=26424|accessdate=10 October 2008| publisher=SportingPulse}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://secure.ausport.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0007/98638/Australian_Rugby_League_2005.pdf |title=Notice of General Meeting |website=Web.archive.org |accessdate=2017-06-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090705170103/https://secure.ausport.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0007/98638/Australian_Rugby_League_2005.pdf |archivedate=5 July 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He then debuted for the [[Burleigh Bears]] in the [[Queensland Cup]]. After playing for Burleigh, Boyd was signed by the [[Brisbane Broncos]]. He later said, \"I was a bit scared of leaving home as an 18-year-old but Brisbane was always my favourite club since I was a little fella. I had to move into the Broncos' house and was a pretty shy, quiet kid so didn't want to leave the family and different things but after a week or two they made me feel welcome.\"<ref>{{cite news| work= nrl.com| title=Boyd: I almost waited for Titans| author=Tony Webeck| url=http://www.nrl.com/boyd-i-almost-waited-for-titans/tabid/10874/newsid/94281/default.aspx|accessdate=30 March 2016|date=29 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2006===\nIn round 1, Boyd made his [[NRL]] debut for the Broncos, against the [[North Queensland Cowboys]],<ref>[http://www.rleague.com//db/player/b/boyd_darius/index.php]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130116211854/http://www.rleague.com//db/player/b/boyd_darius/index.php|date=16 January 2013 }}</ref> scoring a try on debut in the Broncos 36-4 loss at [[Suncorp Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2006-03-12/cowboys-whip-broncos/816266|title=Cowboys whip Broncos - ABC News (Australian Broadcasting Corporation)|publisher=Abc.net.au|date=2006-03-12|accessdate=2015-10-11}}</ref> Playing on the wing for the majority of the season, Boyd got a chance at his preferred position of fullback for a number of games after the regular fullback, [[Karmichael Hunt]], went down with injuries. At the end of the regular season, Boyd won the Broncos' Rookie of the Year award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefanatics.com/sports.news.view.php?id=322793|title=Civoniceva voted Broncos best in 2006 - Sports News - Fanatics - the world's biggest events|publisher=Fanatics|date=|accessdate=2015-10-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/ftimages/2006/10/01/1159641212849.html|title=Broncos triumph in NRL grand final - Sport|newspaper=smh.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-11}}</ref> Boyd played on the wing for the Broncos in their [[2006 NRL Grand Final]] 15-8 win over the [[Melbourne Storm]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.smh.com.au/sinbin/archives/2006/10/nrl_grand_final_live_storm_v_b.html|title=NRL grand final live: Storm v Broncos|publisher=Blogs.smh.com.au|date=|accessdate=2015-10-11}}</ref> Boyd played in 27 matches and scored 11 tries in an impressive debut year in the NRL.\n\n===2007===\nAs 2006 NRL Premiers, the Brisbane Broncos travelled to England to face 2006 [[Super League]] champions, [[St Helens R.F.C.]], in the [[2007 World Club Challenge]].<ref>[http://www.theepochtimes.com/news/7-2-24/52104.html ] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150629200625/http://www.theepochtimes.com/news/7-2-24/52104.html|date=29 June 2015 }}</ref> Boyd played on the wing and scored a try in the Broncos 14-18 loss. Boyd finished the [[2007 NRL season]] with him playing in 22 matches and scoring 7 tries.\n[[File:Darius Boyd (Brisbane Broncos vs. Canberra Raiders 2008).jpg|thumb|150px|left|Boyd while playing for the Broncos in 2008]]\n\n===2008===\nIn Round 1 against the [[Penrith Panthers]], Boyd scored a hat-trick in the Broncos 48-12 win at [[Suncorp Stadium]].<ref>https://www.smh.com.au/sport/nrl/broncos-thump-panthers-20080317-gds5jg.html</ref> In May 2008, Boyd started to receive attention from other clubs as he was off-contract at the end of the year. There was speculation that he would move to the [[Canterbury-Bankstown Bulldogs]], alongside fellow Broncos [[Michael Ennis]] and [[Ben Hannant]],<ref>[http://www.foxsports.com.au/story/0,8659,24189096-23214,00.html]   {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080821014256/http://www.foxsports.com.au/story/0%2C8659%2C24189096-23214%2C00.html |date=21 August 2008 }}</ref> or possibly the [[St. George Illawarra Dragons]], following his coach at Brisbane, [[Wayne Bennett (rugby league)|Wayne Bennett]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/nrl/titans-in-running-for-boyd/story-e6frep76-1111116470751|title=Titans in Running for Boyd|publisher=Couriermail.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref> After leading the NRL try-scoring table for most of the first half of the season, Boyd was selected for the [[Queensland rugby league team|Queensland team]] to play [[New South Wales rugby league team|New South Wales]] in Game 2 of the [[2008 State of Origin series]] due to teammate [[Justin Hodges]] suspension.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/06/03/2263771.htm?section=justin|title=Lockyer, Boyd in for Maroons|publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC Online]]|date=3 June 2008|accessdate=3 June 2008}}</ref> Boyd scored 2 tries on debut, both from passes from centre [[Greg Inglis]], with Queensland winning 30-0 at [[Suncorp Stadium]]<ref name=\"origindebut\">{{cite news|url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/story/0,8659,23850457-23214,00.html|title=Boyd quick to show try-scoring feats|accessdate=12 June 2008|date=12 June 2008|publisher=[[Fox Sports (Australia)|Fox Sports]]}}</ref> Boyd also played in Game 3 as the Maroons won 16-10 at [[ANZ Stadium]] and won the series 2-1.<ref>https://www.abc.net.au/news/2008-07-02/maroons-secure-origin-hat-trick/2492256</ref> On 20 August 2008, Boyd signed a 3-year contract with the Dragons starting in 2009,<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=3 June 2008|date=3 June 2008|publisher=[[The Courier Mail]]|url=http://www.news.com.au/couriermail/sport/nrl/story/0,26746,23799455-5016283,00.html|title=Broncos boss Cullen 'shocked' by Justin Hodges charge| first=Steve| last=Ricketts}}</ref> following teammate [[Nick Emmett]] and coach Wayne Bennett. Boyd finished the [[2008 NRL season]] with him playing in 24 matches and scoring 13 tries. On 16 October 2008, Boyd was called up to the [[Australia national rugby league team|Australian]] [[2008 Rugby League World Cup|2008 World Cup squad]] due to teammate Justin Hodges being ruled out with a shoulder injury. On 9 November 2008, Boyd made his international debut for Australia against [[Papua New Guinea national rugby league team|Papua New Guinea]], playing on the wing in the 46-6 win at [[1300SMILES Stadium]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Andy Wilson|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2008/nov/09/australia-papua-new-guinea-rugby|title=Rugby League: Australia ease to comfortable 46-6 win over Papua New Guinea &#124; Sport|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=2015-10-11}}</ref> Boyd only played in 1 match in the World Cup tournament.\n\n===2009===\nIn Round 1 of the [[2009 NRL season]], Boyd made his club debut for the [[St George Illawarra Dragons]] against the Melbourne Storm, playing at fullback in the 17-16 loss at [[Olympic Park]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/storm-win-in-golden-point/story-e6frg6n6-1111119128178|title=Storm Win in Golden Point|publisher=Theaustralian.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref> \nIn Round 4, he travelled to Brisbane for his and Wayne Bennett's first match against their old club, which the Dragons won 25-12, ending the Broncos unbeaten start to the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/nrl/st-george-illawarra-dragons-beat-brisbane-broncos/story-e6frexp0-1225694569392|title=Dragons Beat Broncos|publisher=Dailytelegraph.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref> On 8 May, Boyd played for Australia in the [[2009 Anzac Test|Anzac Test]], playing on the wing and scoring a try in the 38-10.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=[[Fox Sports (Australia)|Fox Sports]]|title=Kangaroos selectors stick by losing World Cup team for New Zealand Test|first=Tom|last=Wald|url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/story/0,8659,25422175-5016947,00.html|date=3 May 2009|accessdate=3 May 2009}}</ref> Boyd was selected in the Queensland squad for the [[2009 State of Origin series]], playing in all 3 matches and scoring 1 try in the record-breaking 4th consecutive series win. In Round 20 against the [[New Zealand Warriors]], Boyd scored his first try as a Dragon in the 29-4 win at [[Mt Smart Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/dragons-closer-to-minor-premiership-warriors-finished-for-season/story-e6frg6n6-1225754876668|title=Dragons Closer to Minor Premiership Warriors Finished for Season|publisher=Theaustralian.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref> In August, Boyd's performance at a press conference, in which the 22-year-old fullback delivered one-sentence responses to eight questions posed to him at a training session in Wollongong, drew an apology to journalists from Dragons coach Wayne Bennett.<ref>{{cite news|title=Wayne Bennett apologises for Darius Boyd interview|url=http://www.illawarramercury.com.au/story/621094/wayne-bennett-apologises-for-darius-boyd-interview/|accessdate=18 July 2013|newspaper=[[Illawarra Mercury]]|date=18 August 2009}}</ref> Boyd finished his first year with the Dragons with 2 tries in  22 matches.\n\n===2010===\nIn Round 5 against his former team the [[Brisbane Broncos]], Boyd played his 100th career match in the Dragons 34-16 win and was named Man of the Match at [[WIN Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/nrl/nrl-premiership/st-george-illawarra-defeat-brisbane-broncos-34-16-at-win-stadium/story-fn2mcuj6-1225919343211|title=St George Illawara Defeat Brisbane Broncos 34-16|publisher=Foxsports.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref> In Round 7, Boyd received the inaugural \"Spirit of ANZAC Medal\" as Man of the Match in the annual [[ANZAC Day Cup]] in the Dragons 28-6 win against the [[Sydney Roosters]] at [[Sydney Football Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/nrl/nrl-premiership/st-george-illawarra-defeat-sydney-roosters-28-6-on-anzac-day-at-the-sfs/story-fn2mcuj6-1225919720783|title=St George Illawara Defeat Sydney Roosters 28-6 on ANZAC Day|publisher=Foxsports.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref> Boyd played on the wing for Queensland in all three matches of the [[2010 State of Origin series]], scoring a try in each match to become the series' top try-scorer. Towards the end of the season, Boyd was one of the favourites for the [[Dally M Medal]], having had a sizeable lead in points over the previous year's winner [[Jarryd Hayne]] and Sydney Roosters player [[Todd Carney]] when voting went behind closed doors after Round 16. He ended up finishing third, 2 points behind eventual winner Todd Carney and 1 point behind [[Wests Tigers]] hooker [[Robbie Farah]]. On 3 October 2010, Boyd played in the Dragons 2010 NRL Grand Final against the Sydney Roosters, playing at fullback in the Dragons 32-8 win and was awarded the Clive Churchill Medal as man of the match.<ref>http://www.illawarramercury.com.au/news/local/sport/rugby-league/2010-clive-churchill-winner-darius-boyd/1958382.aspx?storypage=0\n</ref> Boyd finished his successful [[2010 NRL season]] with him playing in 25 matches and scoring 2 tries. After the 2010 season, Boyd suggested that he may leave the Dragons if head coach Wayne Bennett did so.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/league-news/boyd-could-follow-bennett-out-of-dragons-20101006-166u0.html| work=The Sydney Morning Herald| title=Boyd could follow Bennett out of Dragons| date=6 October 2010}}</ref> On 4 October 2010, Boyd was selected in the Australia Kangaroos 24-man squad for the [[2010 Four Nations]].<ref>https://www.nrl.com/news/2010/10/04/australian-team-named-for-four-nations/</ref> Boyd only played in 1 match, playing against New Zealand, playing at fullback and scoring a try in the 34-20 win at [[Eden Park]].<ref>http://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/4317235/Rowdy-crowd-mars-Eden-Park-rugby-league-test</ref> Boyd won the 2010 [[RLIF]] Fullback of the Year award in the off-season.\n\n===2011===\nBoyd played in the Dragons [[Rugby League Charity Shield (Australia)|Charity Shield]] 32-10 win over the [[South Sydney Rabbitohs]], scoring a try while playing at five-eighth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/nrl/nrl-premiers-st-george-illawarra-defeat-south-sydney-32-in-charity-shield-match-at-anz-stadium/story-e6frf3ou-1226005357795|title=St George Illawara Defeat South Sydney|publisher=Foxsports.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref> Boyd also played in the Dragons' [[2011 World Club Challenge]] against the [[Wigan Warriors]], playing at fullback in the 21-15 win at [[DW Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/nrl/st-george-illawarra-dragons-voted-team-under-most-pressure-by-nrl-rivals/story-e6frep7x-1226014896897|title=Dragons Voted Team Most Under Pressure by NRL Rivals|publisher=Couriermail.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref> In Round 1 against the [[Gold Coast Titans]], Boyd equalled his 2009 and 2010 efforts with a double in the Dragons 25-16 win at [[Robina Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/nrl/dragons-25-titans-16-darius-boyd-scores-twice-as-nrl-premiers-open-season-with-win/story-e6frep5x-1226020415406|title=Darius Boyd Scores Twice as NRL Premiers Open Season with Win|publisher=Couriermail.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref> On 30 March 2011, Wayne Bennett announced he would not coach the Dragons in 2012, hinting that Boyd may leave the club as well.<ref name=\"TVNZ_4094006\">{{cite web|url=http://tvnz.co.nz/rugby-league-news/bennett-boyd-heading-back-broncos-4094006|title=Bennett, Boyd heading back to Broncos?|date=31 March 2011|work=[[Television New Zealand]]|accessdate=27 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/asst-price-to-coach-dragons-after-bennett/tabid/10874/newsid/62005/default.aspx|title=News Article|publisher=Nrl.com|date=|accessdate=2015-10-11}}</ref> After Bennett signed a 4-year contract with the [[Newcastle Knights]], Boyd was offered contracts from the Knights and the [[Gold Coast Titans]]. On 9 May 2011, the Titans officially withdrew their offer. On 9 June 2011, Boyd signed a 4-year contract with the Newcastle Knights starting in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/boyd-signs-four-year-deal-with-knights/tabid/10874/newsid/63231/default.aspx|title=News Article|publisher=Nrl.com|date=|accessdate=2015-10-11}}</ref> Boyd played in all three matches of the [[2011 State of Origin series]] in the Maroons 6th consecutive series win. Boyd\u2019s final game for the Dragons was against his former club, the [[Brisbane Broncos]] at [[Suncorp Stadium]]. Boyd scored the try that forced golden point for the Dragons, after they were down 12-6, but the Dragons ultimately lost the match 13-12, after his test, state and former club captain, [[Darren Lockyer]] kicked the winning field goal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/nrl/brisbane-broncos-v-st-george-illawarra-dragons-at-suncorp-stadium/story-e6frep5x-1226139829136|title=Broncos v Dragons|publisher=Couriermail.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref> Boyd finished the [[2011 NRL season]] with him playing in 22 matches and scoring 9 tries. On 16 October 2011, Boyd scored 2 tries for Australia in the 42-6 test match win against New Zealand at [[Hunter Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/nrl/kangaroos/kangaroos-beat-new-zealand-42-6-in-rugby-leage-test-at/story-fn2mcuhw-1226167876650|title=Kangaroos Beat New Zealand 42-6|publisher=Foxsports.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref> Boyd was selected in the Australian squad for the [[2011 Four Nations]] tournament held in the United Kingdom. Boyd played all 4 matches and scoring 3 triesincluding playing at fullback in the Kangaroos 30-8 Four Nations Final win against [[England national rugby league team|England]] at [[Elland Road]].<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2011/nov/19/four-nations-england-australia</ref>\n[[File:Boyd.PNG|thumb|left|Boyd while playing for the Knights in 2012]]\n\n===2012===\n[[File:Darius Boyd PM XIII.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Boyd playing for the Prime Minister's XIII in 2012]]\nIn Round 1 of the [[2012 NRL season]], Boyd made his club debut for the [[Newcastle Knights]] against his former club the [[St George Illawarra Dragons]], playing at fullback in the Knights 15-14 golden point extra time loss at [[Hunter Stadium]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Greg Prichard|url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/league-match-report/apprentice-price-gets-one-over-master-in-thrilling-seasonopener-20120302-1u66m.html|title=Apprentice Price gets one over master in thrilling season-opener|newspaper=Smh.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-11}}</ref> On 20 April 2012, Boyd played for Australia in the [[2012 Anzac Test]], playing on the wing in the Kangaroos 20-12 win [[Eden Park]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/lowdown-on-test-blockbuster/story-e6frexni-1226334489834|title=Lowdown on Test Blockbuster|publisher=Dailytelegraph.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref> Boyd played on the wing for Queensland in all three matches of the [[2012 State of Origin series]], scoring 3 tries in the Maroons 7th consecutive series win.\n\nIn Round 21 against the [[Canberra Raiders]], Boyd scored his first club try as a Knight in the 36-6 win at [[Canberra Stadium]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Jon Tuxworth|url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/league-match-report/bennett-breaks-canberra-hoodoo-as-knights-stay-on-a-roll-20120729-235pf.html|title=Bennett breaks Canberra hoodoo as Knights stay on a roll|newspaper=Smh.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-11}}</ref> Boyd finished his first year with the Knights with him playing in 22 matches and scoring 3 tries. On 23 September 2012, Boyd for [[Prime Minister\u2019s XIII]] against [[Papua New Guinea national rugby league team|Papua New Guinea]], playing at fullback in the 24-18 win at [[Port Moresby]].<ref>https://www.nrl.com/news/2012/09/23/prime-ministers-xiii-scrape-home-in-port-moresby/</ref> On 13 October 2012, Boyd played on the wing for Australia in their 18-10 win over New Zealand.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/nrl/live-blog-australia-v-new-zealand/story-e6frfgbo-1226494980023|title=Australia v New Zealand|publisher=Heraldsun.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref>\n\n===2013===\nOn 19 April 2013, Boyd played for Australia on the wing and scored a try in the [[2013 Anzac Test]] 32-12 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/nrl/australia-beats-new-zealand-32-12-at-canbera-stadium/story-e6frexnr-1226624627487|title=Australia Beats New Zealand 32-12|publisher=Dailytelegraph.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref> He played all three games and was the top try scorer with 3 in the [[2013 State of Origin series]] in which Queensland extended their record for consecutive series victories to eight. Boyd played in 26 matches and scored 11 tries for the Knights. Selected in the 24-man Australian [[2013 Rugby League World Cup]] squad,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/rugby-league-world-cup-squads/tabid/10874/newsid/75063/default.aspx|title=Rugby League World Cup squads|publisher=NRL.com|date=|accessdate=2015-10-11}}</ref> he played in 5 matches and scored 4 tries. Boyd played on the wing in the Kangaroos 34-2 World Cup Final win against the Kiwis at [[Old Trafford]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Bott|first=Richard|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/rugbyleague/article-2516064/Australia-34-New-Zealand-2-Kangaroos-crowned-world-champions.html|title=Australia 34 New Zealand 2: Kangaroos crowned world champions &#124; Daily Mail Online|publisher=Dailymail.co.uk|date=|accessdate=2015-10-11}}</ref>\n\n===2014===\nOn 2 May 2014, Boyd played on the wing for Australia in the [[2014 Anzac Test]], in the Kangaroos 30-18 win at [[Sydney Football Stadium]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Chris Barrett|url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/league-match-report/australia-get-the-victory-but-new-zealand-take-the-plaudits-after-giving-world-champions-a-scare-20140502-zr3lc.html|title=Australia get the victory but New Zealand take the plaudits after giving world champions a scare|newspaper=Smh.com.au|date=2014-05-02|accessdate=2015-10-11}}</ref> In Round 13 against the [[Wests Tigers]] at [[Hunter Stadium]], Boyd played his 200th career match in the Knights 23-20 loss at [[Hunter Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Dillon|first=Robert|url=http://www.theherald.com.au/story/2337900/luckless-knights-slump-to-sixth-straight-loss-pics/|title=Luckless Knights slump to sixth straight loss, pics &#124; Newcastle Herald|publisher=Theherald.com.au|date=2014-06-08|accessdate=2015-10-11}}</ref> Boyd played on the wing in all 3 matches of the [[2014 State of Origin series]], scoring 3 tries in the Maroons first series defeat since 2005.\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/sport/nrl/jarryd-hayne-steers-nsw-blues-to-state-of-origin-win-over-maroons/story-fnca0von-1226935045717|title=Jarryd Hayne Steers NSW Blues to State of Origin Win Over Maroons|publisher=Theaustralian.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Michael Chammas|url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/league-match-report/queensland-maroons-beat-nsw-blues-to-score-consolation-win-20140709-zt1wq.html|title=Queensland Maroons beat NSW Blues to score consolation win|newspaper=Smh.com.au|date=2014-07-09|accessdate=2015-10-11}}</ref> On 23 July 2014, Boyd admitted himself to a [[mental health]] clinic to treat [[Depression (mood)|depression]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Brett Keeble|url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/league-news/newcastle-knights-darius-boyd-admitted-to-mental-health-clinic-to-treat-depression-20140723-zvwa2.html|title=Newcastle Knights Darius Boyd admitted to mental health clinic to treat depression|newspaper=Smh.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-11}}</ref> On 14 August, Boyd completed his treatment for depression and came out about him admitting himself to rehab.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/nrl/darius-boyd-reveals-how-he-hit-rock-bottom-his-21-days-in-rehab-and-the-family-demons-he-is-confronting-to-beat-depression/story-fni3gf5j-1227025848132|title=Darius Boyd Reveals How He Hit Rock Bottom|publisher=Dailytelegraph.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref> He didn't make a return to the Knights for the rest of the year as he continued to focus on his recovery. On 31 October 2014, Boyd was released from the final year of his Knights contract.<ref>{{cite news|author=Robert Dillon|url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/newcastle-knights/darius-boyd-released-by-newcastle-knights-20141031-11f9tp.html|title=Darius Boyd released by Newcastle Knights|newspaper=Smh.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-11}}</ref> On 21 November 2014, Boyd signed a three-year contract with the Brisbane Broncos, returning to the club where he made his debut in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.broncos.com.au/news/2014/11/21/boyd_a_bronco_again.html|title=Boyd A Bronco Again|publisher=Broncos|date=|accessdate=2015-10-11}}</ref> He finished the [[2014 NRL season]] with him playing in 14 matches and scoring 3 tries.\n\n===2015===\nOn 5 December 2015, Boyd ruptured his [[Achilles tendon]] during pre-season training; this injury was expected to keep him out of action for at least six months, possibly seeing him sidelined for the entire 2015 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/nrl/nrl-premiership/brisbane-broncos-darius-boyd-snaps-achilles-will-miss-up-to-nine-months/story-e6frf3pc-1227145685369|title=Broncos Darius Boyd Snaps Achilles ; Will Miss Up To Nine Months|publisher=Foxsports.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref> However, Boyd made a surprise return in Round 9 against the [[Penrith Panthers]] at fullback in the Broncos 8-5 win at [[Suncorp Stadium]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Beth Newman|url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/darius-boyd-makes-successful-comeback-for-brisbane-broncos-20150508-ggxqx5.html|title=Darius Boyd makes successful comeback for Brisbane Broncos|newspaper=Smh.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref> Queensland coach, [[Mal Meninga]], showing faith in Boyd to perform in Origin despite not playing the majority of the early [[2015 NRL season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/nrl/qld-state-of-origin-2015-team-live-coverage-as-mal-meninga-confirms-squad/story-fniablg6-1227359881127|title=State of Origin 2015 Live Team Coverage|publisher=Couriermail.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref> Boyd played in all 3 matches and scored a try for Queensland in the [[2015 State of Origin series]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/nrl/state-of-origin-2015-game-3-maroons-winger-darius-boyd-boasts-deadly-suncorp-scoring-record/story-fniablkr-1227424014110?sv=e6b88f22d8270968c05a0dbfa38f9fc2|title=Darius Boyd Boasts Deadly Suncorp Scoring Record|publisher=Couriermail.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref> In Round 16 against his former club the [[Newcastle Knights]], Boyd scored his first try after returning to the Broncos in the 44-22 win at [[Suncorp Stadium]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Beth Newman|url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/state-of-origin/broncos-and-maroons-prop-josh-mcguire-pragmatic-after-achilles-injury-20150626-ghz1te.html|title=Broncos and Maroons prop Josh McGuire pragmatic after achilles injury|newspaper=Smh.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref> In the Preliminary Finals match against the [[Sydney Roosters]], Boyd scored an intercept try in the first minute of the match after Roosters winger [[Shaun Kenny-Dowall]] attempted a 20-metre pass to fullback [[Roger Tuivasa-Sheck]], the Broncos later won 31-12, sending them to the Grand Final.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/league-match-report/roosters-winger-shaun-kennydowalls-shocker-helps-brisbane-broncos-to-another-nrl-grand-final-20150925-gjvbgh.html|title=Roosters winger Shaun Kenny-Dowall's shocker helps Brisbane Broncos to another NRL grand final|newspaper=Smh.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref> On 4 October 2015, in the [[2015 NRL Grand Final]] against the [[North Queensland Cowboys]], Boyd played at fullback in the Broncos historic golden point 17-16 loss.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/league-match-report/nrl-grand-final-2015-north-queensland-cowboys-outgun-brisbane-broncos-to-win-premiership-20151004-gk12is.html|title=NRL Grand Final 2015: North Queensland Cowboys outgun Brisbane Broncos to win premiership|newspaper=Smh.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/nrl/nrl-grand-final-player-ratings-broncos-v-cowboys-who-starred-and-who-struggled/story-fni3fbgz-1227556818349?sv=d513a72ed0eabb4bbeaad8561926d617|title=NRL Grand Final Player Ratings|publisher=Dailytelegraph.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref> Boyd finished his return year with the Brisbane Broncos with him playing in 18 matches and scoring 3 tries in the [[2015 NRL season]].\n\n===2016===\nOn 1 February, Boyd was named in the Broncos' [[2016 NRL Auckland Nines]] squad.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/thaiday-to-captain-broncos-nines-squad/tabid/10874/newsid/91547/default.aspx|title=Thaiday to captain Broncos' Nines squad|website=NRL.com|date=|accessdate=2016-02-02}}</ref> Following a season-ending shoulder injury to his Queensland Origin team-mate [[Billy Slater]], Boyd was selected to play Fullback for Australia against New Zealand in the [[2016 Anzac Test]], scoring a try on the 16-0 win at [[Hunter Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/representative-round-team-lists/tabid/10874/newsid/95512/default.aspx|title=UPDATED: Representative Round team lists|publisher=NRL.com|date=2016-02-28|accessdate=2016-05-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160604182259/http://www.nrl.com/representative-round-team-lists/tabid/10874/newsid/95512/default.aspx|archive-date=4 June 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.news.com.au/sport/nrl/live-coverage-of-the-anzac-test-between-australia-and-new-zealand-at-hunter-stadium-newcastle/news-story/5300bf4c11d489981ee82f5d0622f823|title=Australia v New Zealand Trans-Tasman test live blog, scores, results , stats, video|work=News.com.au|date=2016-05-03|accessdate=2016-05-07}}</ref> With [[Billy Slater]] already out of action due to injury, Boyd filled the Fullback role for Queensland in the [[2016 State of Origin series]], where he played in all 3 matches and scored 1 try in the Maroons series win.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/nrl/state-of-origin/state-of-origin-2016-billy-slater-says-darius-boyd-has-taken-fullback-play-to-another-level/news-story/02d9086af88d48f068e60163d73ae337|title=Billy Slater Says Darius Boyd Has Taken Fullback Play to Another Level|website=Couriermail.com.au|accessdate=2016-10-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Margan|first=Max|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/nrl/article-3687979/State-Origin-Game-3-Fans-flock-ANZ-Stadium-watch-Queensland-Maroons-NSW-Blues.html|title=State of Origin Game 3: Fans flock to ANZ Stadium to watch Queensland Maroons take on NSW Blues &#124; Daily Mail Online|website=Dailymail.co.uk|date=2016-07-13|accessdate=2016-10-03}}</ref> In Round 14 against the [[Canberra Raiders]], Boyd scored a classy hat trick of tries in a space of 14 minutes in the Broncos 26-18 win at [[Suncorp Stadium]]. This was the first time Boyd scored a hat trick of tries since Round 1 of the 2008 season.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/nrl/nrl-2016-darius-boyd-hattrick-soothes-injury-pain-in-brisbane-broncos-win-over-canberra-raiders/news-story/83bba91089ff963e5c978583c2a389b1|title=Darius Boyd Hattrick Soothes Injury Pain in Brisbane Broncos Win Over Canberra Raiders|website=Couriermail.com.au|accessdate=2016-10-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2016/jun/10/boyd-earns-darren-lockyer-comparisons-from-wayne-bennett-after-broncos-win|title=Boyd earns Darren Lockyer comparisons from Wayne Bennett after Broncos win &#124; Sport|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=2016-10-03}}</ref> Boyd finished the [[2016 NRL season]] with him playing in 25 matches and scoring 9 tries for the Broncos. On 20 September 2016, Boyd was added to the Kangaroos [[2016 Rugby League Four Nations|2016 Four Nations]] train-on squad.<ref>{{cite web|last=Luca|first=Rocco|url=http://rugbyleagueweek.com.au/kangaroos-train-squad-announced-2/|title=Kangaroos train-on squad announced|publisher=Rugby League Week|date=2016-09-20|accessdate=2016-10-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161023013118/http://rugbyleagueweek.com.au/kangaroos-train-squad-announced-2/|archive-date=23 October 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> On 4 October 2016, Boyd was selected in the [[Australian Kangaroos]] Final 24-man squad for the tournament.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/2016-kangaroos-four-nations-squad/tabid/10874/newsid/101933/default.aspx |title=2016 Kangaroos Four Nations squad |website=NRL.com |date=2016-10-04 |accessdate=2017-06-05}}</ref> Boyd played in 4 matches and scored 2 tries of tournament including starting at fullback and scoring a try in the Kangaroos 34-8 Four Nations Final win against New Zealand at [[Anfield]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Laybourn |first=Ian |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/rugbyleague/article-3954908/Australia-34-8-New-Zealand-Mal-Meninga-s-ruthless-storm-victory-Four-Nations-final-Anfield.html |title=Australia 34-8 New Zealand: Mal Meninga's ruthless side storm to victory in Four Nations final at Anfield |website=Dailymail.co.uk |date=2016-11-20 |accessdate=2017-06-05}}</ref> On 7 October 2016, Boyd was awarded with the [[Paul Morgan (rugby league)|Paul Morgan]] Medal as being the Broncos best-and-fairest player of the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/nrl/teams/broncos/broncos-fullback-darius-boyd-has-won-his-first-brisbane-bestandfairest-award/news-story/bb5ff9d3895867bdb460418ab0656a85 |title=Darius Boyd Has Won His First Brisbane Best and Fairest Award |website=Couriermail.com.au |accessdate=2017-06-05}}</ref>\n\n===2017===\nBefore the start of the 2017 season, Boyd joined the likes of [[Darren Lockyer]], [[Wally Lewis]], [[Allan Langer]] and [[Gorden Tallis]] when he was named the ninth Broncos captain in the club's 30-year history.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Meyn|first1=Travis|title=Brisbane Broncos captain 2017: Darius Boyd takes over from Corey Parker, completing NRL career resurrection|url=http://www.news.com.au/sport/brisbane-broncos-new-captain-for-2017/news-story/445391b4a52669c7096cd8e9e8fc5a0b|work=news.com.au|accessdate=19 March 2017}}</ref> In February, he was selected in the Broncos [[2017 NRL Auckland Nines]] squad.<ref>https://www.nrl.com/news/2017/02/04/2017-downer-nrl-auckland-nines-squads/</ref> His first game as captain of the Broncos ended with a 27-18 loss at [[Halliwell Jones Stadium]] to the [[Warrington Wolves]] in the [[2017 World Club Series]].<ref name=\"Warrington 27-18 Brisbane: Wolves' first-half blitz stuns Broncos\">{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/rugby-league/warrington-vs-brisbane/45988|title=Warrington 27-18 Brisbane: Wolves' first-half blitz stuns Broncos|publisher=Sky Sports|date=19 February 2017|accessdate=30 May 2017}}</ref> In Round 3 against the [[Melbourne Storm]], Boyd played his 250th NRL career match in the Broncos 14-12 loss at [[AAMI Park]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/sport/nrl/darius-boyd-is-softly-spoken-but-his-leadership-speaks-volumes/news-story/337ed1bf28a16be23ebe7db70bc3037c|title=Subscribe - theaustralian|website=Theaustralian.com.au|accessdate=2017-06-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/nrl/teams/broncos/melbourne-storm-defeat-brisbane-broncos-1412-as-billy-slater-makes-his-nrl-return/news-story/dcb4733a1d63ccf98d396828d9cc3b5b|title=Cool Storm break Broncos hearts|website=Couriermail.com.au|accessdate=2017-06-05}}</ref> On 5 May, Boyd played for Australia in the [[2017 ANZAC Test]]  where he started at fullback in the 30-12 win.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/sport/nrl/live-australia-vs-new-zealand-anzac-test-in-canberra/news-story/f5b42d8e4765c3040d1f0114dff2a2de |title=Australia vs New Zealand Anzac Test: Live scores, highlights, result, video |website=News.com.au |date=2017-05-05 |accessdate=2017-06-05}}</ref> Despite [[Billy Slater]] coming back from injury, Boyd retained his Maroons fullback role for Game 1 of the series.<ref>http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/billy-slater-not-selected-as-darius-boyd-keeps-fullback-spot-20170521-gw9vxo.html</ref> However, in Game 2 Boyd was switched to centre to accommodate Slater's return to the fullback position.<ref>http://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/nrl/state-of-origin/state-of-origin-2017-darius-boyd-to-start-at-left-centre-as-kevin-walters-rings-the-changes/news-story/e5a3a53656c68957d95db33c6f9c875d</ref> In Round 26 against the [[North Queensland Cowboys]], Boyd injured his [[hamstring]].<ref>http://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/nrl/teams/broncos/brisbane-beat-north-queensland-2010-but-lose-darius-boyd-with-hamstring-injury/news-story/1c7e3f5d9896a5db6e7e939193f6f7e8</ref> Scans revealed bad news for Brisbane with Boyd ruled out for the next 2 finals matches. In the preliminary final against the Melbourne Storm, Boyd made his return as the Broncos looked to make the grand final for the second time in three years.<ref>http://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/nrl/teams/broncos/broncos-boosted-as-darius-boyd-cleared-to-return-against-melbourne-storm/news-story/1323d11f827bb22b197f6477e0d82ecb</ref> Commentators believed Boyd wasn't fully recovered and replays saw him limping. In the second half, Boyd succumbed to his hamstring injury, with the Broncos eventually losing 30-0 and later missed selection for the Kangaroos [[2017 Rugby League World Cup]] squad.<ref>https://www.foxsports.com.au/nrl/nrl-premiership/teams/broncos/nrl-finals-darius-boyds-backfiring-fitness-call-reminiscent-of-allan-langers-last-broncos-game-in-2002/news-story/5c0070dc684ebf3a6d083243f83662cf</ref><ref>https://www.foxsports.com.au/nrl/kangaroos/more-drama-for-kangaroos-world-cup-squad-as-darius-boyd-ruled-out-josh-mansour-called-up/news-story/72003d374ddf07deb643a5dc5099364b</ref> Boyd finished his [[2017 NRL season]] with 18 matches and 3 tries for the Broncos. On 26 October, Boyd extended his contract with the Broncos on a four-year deal, keeping him at Red Hill to until at least the 2021 season.<ref>http://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/nrl/darius-boyd-a-bronco-for-life-skipper-signs-contract-extension/news-story/46b4f57107e5e40f67d473f61eb690b2</ref>\n\n===2018===\nOn 11 June 2018, Boyd announced that he had retired from playing in representative matches after missing out on selection for Queensland. He commented, \"My time\u2019s done in rep footy. I\u2019ve had a great career, I have nothing to be disappointed about, I\u2019m really happy with everything I\u2019ve achieved in the rep arena. I don\u2019t think I have anything more to prove, it\u2019s time for the younger fellas coming in, they have great players, really quality guys coming through.\"<ref>https://www.news.com.au/sport/nrl/darius-boyd-has-called-time-on-his-representative-career/news-story/6e82b9730b8ca801b3be350c8fe89d15</ref> Between Rounds 19-21, Boyd played at centre as coach Wayne Bennett experimented playing youngster [[Jamayne Isaako]] at fullback.<ref>https://www.nrl.com/news/2018/07/19/bennett-switches-boyd-to-centre-to-plug-leaky-defence/</ref><ref>https://www.nrl.com/news/2018/07/21/brisbane-broncos-captain-darius-boyd-happy-to-remain-in-the-centres/</ref> Boyd finished the [[2018 NRL season]] with him playing of the 25 matches and scoring 5 tries for the Broncos.\n\n===2019===\nIn Round 8 against the [[South Sydney Rabbitohs]], Boyd played his 300th NRL career match, playing his milestone game against his old mentor, Rabbitohs coach [[Wayne Bennett (rugby league)|Wayne Bennett]] who Boyd spent his whole career being coached by him until the 2019 season when Bennett was given the sack by the Broncos and swapped clubs with [[Anthony Seibold]].<ref>https://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/nrl/teams/broncos/darius-boyd-set-to-mark-300th-nrl-game-against-wayne-bennett/news-story/2fade4d9d197ea1c2a48e900946a49ce</ref> The Broncos lost the match 38-6 at [[ANZ Stadium]] as the Rabbitohs dedicated the win to the recently retired Rabbitohs star [[Greg Inglis]].<ref>https://www.foxsports.com.au/nrl/nrl-premiership/live-nrl-south-sydney-rabbitohs-v-brisbane-broncos-live-scores-updates-news-blog/news-story/b461d8d29bc09584f7570b5c48cd7801</ref> Boyd has copped plenty of criticism for his form in the early rounds of the 2019 season, practically his defence and leadership. Boyd commented, \u201cI don\u2019t know what the outside noise is saying, but my body is really good and my form, I\u2019m pretty happy with it. \u201cI spoke to \u2018Seibs\u2019 (Broncos coach Anthony Seibold) and he's happy with how I'm performing, \u201cI know if we win some games the critics will go away. \u201cI can be better and I\u2019m not saying I don\u2019t have to put up my hand up and be better, because I know I do, especially as a captain, but I\u2019m not losing sleep over my performances.\u201d<ref>https://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/nrl/broncos-captain-darius-boyd-hits-back-over-criticism-of-nrl-form/news-story/64acbb2c2ea5479cd1d156dce7de10f0</ref> On 30 August 2019, Boyd was selected at Wing for the Queensland Maroons Team of the Decade.\n\nAt the end of the 2019 regular season, Brisbane finished in 8th place on the table and qualified for the finals.  Boyd captained the club in their elimination final against Parramatta which Brisbane lost 58-0 at the new [[Western Sydney Stadium]].  The defeat was Brisbane's biggest ever loss and the biggest loss in finals history which eclipsed Newtown's record when they defeated St George 55-7 in 1944.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-09-15/eels-make-history-with-58-point-finals-flogging-of-broncos/11505120/|title=Parramatta Eels eliminate Brisbane Broncos from the NRL Finals with a thumping 58-0 win|website=ABC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxsports.com.au/nrl/nrl-premiership/finals/fuming-seibold-fires-off-at-players-promises-review-of-roster-after-embarrassing-loss/news-story/aed1578918d1dbedc4eb33c3904d2b0e/|title=Fuming Seibold fires off at players, promises review of roster after \u2018embarrassing\u2019 loss|website=Fox Sports}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nrl.com/news/2019/09/15/seibold-top-to-bottom-review-needed-as-broncos-search-for-answers/|title=Seibold: 'Top to bottom' review needed as Brisbane search for answers|website=NRL}}</ref>\n\n===2020===\nOn 6 March 2020, Boyd announced that he would retire at the end of the [[2020 NRL season]] despite having one year left to run on his contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.broncos.com.au/news/2020/03/06/boyd-to-hang-up-boots-at-end-of-season/?fbclid=IwAR3TsWIfsRmy9rLQptQlQVNldmJ1bn-ctli90utV1hxSRcFOtvf1Ce16xW0|title=Boyd to hang up boots at end of season|publisher=Brisbane Broncos|date=6 March 2020|accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref> He will be the final member from the club's [[2006 NRL season|2006 premiership team]] to retire.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.couriermail.com.au/subscribe/news/1/?sourceCode=CMWEB_WRE170_a_GGL&dest=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.couriermail.com.au%2Fsport%2Fnrl%2Fteams%2Fbroncos%2Fdarius-boyd-on-broncos-captaincy-anthony-seibold-and-retirement-rumours%2Fnews-story%2F25b3f2ee74a359cf62e964a53702c180&memtype=anonymous&mode=premium|title=Darius Boyd on Broncos captaincy, Anthony Seibold and retirement rumours|publisher=The Courier Mail|date=5 December 2019|accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*[https://www.broncos.com.au/teams/telstra-premiership/brisbane-broncos/darius-boyd/ Brisbane Broncos profile]\n*[http://www.broncos.com.au/team/profiles/darius_boyd.html Broncos profile]\n*[http://www.nrl.com/telstrapremiership/playerstats/playerprofile/tabid/10898/clubid/1/playerid/443/seasonid/44/default.aspx NRL profile]\n{{S-start}}\n{{Succession box|title=[[Clive Churchill Medal]]list|before=[[Billy Slater]] ([[Melbourne Storm]])|after=[[Glenn Stewart]] ([[Manly-Warringah Sea Eagles]])|years=2010}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Brisbane Broncos Current}}\n{{Brisbane Broncos squad 2006 NRL premiership}}\n{{St. George Illawarra Dragons squad - 2010 NRL Premiers}}\n{{St. George Illawarra Dragons - 2011 World Club Challenge winners}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title= Australia squads\n| bg=#005100\n| fg=#FFCC33\n| bordercolor=#FFCC33\n|list1= \n{{Australia 2008 Rugby League World Cup squad}}\n{{Australia squad - 2010 Rugby League Four Nations}}\n{{Australia squad - 2011 Rugby League Four Nations}}\n{{Australia 2013 Rugby League World Cup squad}}\n{{Australia squad - 2016 Rugby League Four Nations}}\n}}\n{{Clive Churchill Medallists}}\n{{Rugby league footballers with 300 NRL games}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Boyd, Darius}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Australian rugby league players]]\n[[Category:Australia national rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Brisbane Broncos players]]\n[[Category:Newcastle Knights players]]\n[[Category:St. George Illawarra Dragons players]]\n[[Category:Queensland Rugby League State of Origin players]]\n[[Category:Prime Minister's XIII players]]\n[[Category:Burleigh Bears players]]\n[[Category:Clive Churchill Medal winners]]\n[[Category:Rugby league players from Queensland]]\n[[Category:Rugby league fullbacks]]\n[[Category:Rugby league wingers]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from the Gold Coast, Queensland]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox rugby league biography\n|name          = Darius Boyd\n|fullname      =\n|image         = Darius Boyd Broncos.jpg\n|imagesize     = 290\n|caption       = \n|position      = {{rlp|WG|FB|CE}}\n|birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1987|7|17}}\n|birth_place   = [[Gold Coast, Queensland, Australia]]\n|height        = {{convert|184|cm|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|weight        = {{convert|93|kg|stlb|abbr=on}}\n|retired       = no\n|club1         = [[Brisbane Broncos]]\n|year1start    = 2006\n|year1end      = 08\n|appearances1  = 74\n|tries1        = 32\n|goals1        = 0\n|fieldgoals1   = 0\n|points1       = 128\n|club2         = {{nowrap|[[St. George Illawarra Dragons|St. George Illawarra]]}}\n|year2start    = 2009\n|year2end      = 11\n|appearances2  = 70\n|tries2        = 13\n|goals2        = 0\n|fieldgoals2   = 0\n|points2       = 52\n|club3         = [[Newcastle Knights]]\n|year3start    = 2012\n|year3end      = 14\n|appearances3  = 62\n|tries3        = 17\n|goals3        = 0\n|fieldgoals3   = 0\n|points3       = 68\n|club4         = [[Brisbane Broncos]]\n|year4start    = 2015\n|year4end      = present\n|appearances4  = 115\n|tries4        = 22\n|goals4        = 0\n|fieldgoals4   = 0\n|points4       = 88\n|teamA         = [[Queensland rugby league team|Queensland]]\n|yearAstart    = 2008\n|yearAend      = 17\n|appearancesA  = 28\n|triesA        = 17\n|goalsA        = 0\n|fieldgoalsA   = 0\n|pointsA       = 68\n|teamB         = [[Australian national rugby league team|Australia]]\n|yearBstart    = 2008\n|yearBend      = 17\n|appearancesB  = 23\n|triesB        = 16\n|goalsB        = 0\n|fieldgoalsB   = 0\n|pointsB       = 64\n|teamC         = [[Prime Minister's XIII]]\n|yearCstart    = 2012\n|yearCend      = \n|appearancesC  = 1\n|triesC        = 0\n|goalsC        = 0\n|fieldgoalsC   = 0\n|pointsC       = 0\n|retited       = \n|source        = <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.loverugbyleague.com/stats/players/Darius-Boyd/ |title=Darius Boyd - Player Stats |publisher=Love Rugby League |date= |accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/players/darius-boyd/summary.html|title=Darius Boyd - Career Stats & Summary|publisher=Rugby League Project|date=|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref>\n|updated       = 17 September 2019\n}}\n\n'''Darius Boyd''' (born 17 July 1987) is an Australian professional [[rugby league]] footballer who plays as a {{rlp|fb}}, [[Five-eighth|five eighth]] and on the {{rlp|wg}} for the [[Brisbane Broncos]] in the [[National Rugby League|NRL]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://broncos.com.au/index.php?page_id=individual_player&player_id=73&team_id=1|accessdate=3 June 2008|publisher=[[Brisbane Broncos]]|title=Brisbane Broncos \u2013 Darius Boyd|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080720142058/http://www.broncos.com.au/index.php?page_id=individual_player&player_id=73&team_id=1|archive-date=20 July 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> and has played for [[Australia national rugby league team|Australia]] at international level and State of Origin for QLD. Boyd captained the Brisbane Broncos from 2017-2019.  \n\nBoyd previously played for the [[St. George Illawarra Dragons]] in 2009-2011 and the [[Newcastle Knights]] in 2012-2014 all under a single coach: [[Wayne Bennett (rugby league)|Wayne Bennett]] before switching back to Broncos in 2015. Boyd has won the [[2006 NRL Grand Final]] with the Broncos and the [[2010 NRL Grand Final]] with the [[St George Illawarra Dragons|Dragons]]. He is a [[Queensland rugby league team|Queensland]] [[State of Origin series|State of Origin]] and [[Prime Minister\u2019s XIII]] representative.\n\n==Early life==\nBoyd was born at the [[Gold Coast Hospital]], in [[Queensland, Australia]] on 17 July 1987. He was raised by his single mother throughout most of his childhood.<ref name=\"origindebut\"/>\n\nHe began playing junior football at a young age for the Parkwood Sharks, which led to playing at halftime during a [[Gold Coast Chargers|Gold Coast Seagulls]] match in 1993. He later switched clubs to the Mudgeeraba Redbacks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/darius-boyd-nrl-stars-pain-about-not-knowing-who-is-father-is/news-story/bc59091afe79587c8e9b4930b805c2f8 |title=Darius Boyd's Pain About Not Knowing Who His Father Is |website=Couriermail.com.au |accessdate=2017-06-05}}</ref> Boyd attended Robina State High School during this time but switched schools to the famed rugby league nursery, [[Palm Beach Currumbin High School]], in Year 10. It was at this point Boyd's mother became ill and he starting living with his grandmother, as well as spending periods of time living with football friend's families. {{Citation needed|date=March 2017}} Following graduation in 2004, he was not recruited by any NRL teams and decided to repeat Year 12 at PBC in the hope of garnering attention from NRL teams. The decision turned out to be a fruitful one with the [[Brisbane Broncos]] offering Boyd a scholarship, followed by a $20,000 contract for the [[2006 NRL season]]. {{Citation needed|date=March 2017}} Boyd was questioned by police in 2009 relating to an alleged sexual assault in a Brisbane nightclub.<ref>{{Cite news\n| last = Doneman\n| first = Paula \n| coauthors = \n| title = Woman breaks silence over Broncos nightclub sex scandal\n| work = [[The Courier Mail]]\n| place = Australia\n| page = \n| language = \n| publisher = [[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corp]]\n| date = 11 November 2009\n| url = https://amp.couriermail.com.au/news/national/woman-breaks-silence-over-broncos-scandal/news-story/264110c02c2f84439c71053337105806\n| accessdate = 10 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Playing career==\nIn 2005, while playing for Palm Beach Currumbin, Boyd was selected at fullback for the [[Australia national schoolboy rugby league team|Australian Schoolboys]] team.<ref>{{cite web|title=SportingPulse Homepage for Australian Secondary Schools Rugby League|url=http://www.sportingpulse.com/assoc_page.cgi?c=7-2130-0-0-0&sID=26424|accessdate=10 October 2008| publisher=SportingPulse}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://secure.ausport.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0007/98638/Australian_Rugby_League_2005.pdf |title=Notice of General Meeting |website=Web.archive.org |accessdate=2017-06-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090705170103/https://secure.ausport.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0007/98638/Australian_Rugby_League_2005.pdf |archivedate=5 July 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He then debuted for the [[Burleigh Bears]] in the [[Queensland Cup]]. After playing for Burleigh, Boyd was signed by the [[Brisbane Broncos]]. He later said, \"I was a bit scared of leaving home as an 18-year-old but Brisbane was always my favourite club since I was a little fella. I had to move into the Broncos' house and was a pretty shy, quiet kid so didn't want to leave the family and different things but after a week or two they made me feel welcome.\"<ref>{{cite news| work= nrl.com| title=Boyd: I almost waited for Titans| author=Tony Webeck| url=http://www.nrl.com/boyd-i-almost-waited-for-titans/tabid/10874/newsid/94281/default.aspx|accessdate=30 March 2016|date=29 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2006===\nIn round 1, Boyd made his [[NRL]] debut for the Broncos, against the [[North Queensland Cowboys]],<ref>[http://www.rleague.com//db/player/b/boyd_darius/index.php]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130116211854/http://www.rleague.com//db/player/b/boyd_darius/index.php|date=16 January 2013 }}</ref> scoring a try on debut in the Broncos 36-4 loss at [[Suncorp Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2006-03-12/cowboys-whip-broncos/816266|title=Cowboys whip Broncos - ABC News (Australian Broadcasting Corporation)|publisher=Abc.net.au|date=2006-03-12|accessdate=2015-10-11}}</ref> Playing on the wing for the majority of the season, Boyd got a chance at his preferred position of fullback for a number of games after the regular fullback, [[Karmichael Hunt]], went down with injuries. At the end of the regular season, Boyd won the Broncos' Rookie of the Year award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefanatics.com/sports.news.view.php?id=322793|title=Civoniceva voted Broncos best in 2006 - Sports News - Fanatics - the world's biggest events|publisher=Fanatics|date=|accessdate=2015-10-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/ftimages/2006/10/01/1159641212849.html|title=Broncos triumph in NRL grand final - Sport|newspaper=smh.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-11}}</ref> Boyd played on the wing for the Broncos in their [[2006 NRL Grand Final]] 15-8 win over the [[Melbourne Storm]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.smh.com.au/sinbin/archives/2006/10/nrl_grand_final_live_storm_v_b.html|title=NRL grand final live: Storm v Broncos|publisher=Blogs.smh.com.au|date=|accessdate=2015-10-11}}</ref> Boyd played in 27 matches and scored 11 tries in an impressive debut year in the NRL.\n\n===2007===\nAs 2006 NRL Premiers, the Brisbane Broncos travelled to England to face 2006 [[Super League]] champions, [[St Helens R.F.C.]], in the [[2007 World Club Challenge]].<ref>[http://www.theepochtimes.com/news/7-2-24/52104.html ] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150629200625/http://www.theepochtimes.com/news/7-2-24/52104.html|date=29 June 2015 }}</ref> Boyd played on the wing and scored a try in the Broncos 14-18 loss. Boyd finished the [[2007 NRL season]] with him playing in 22 matches and scoring 7 tries.\n[[File:Darius Boyd (Brisbane Broncos vs. Canberra Raiders 2008).jpg|thumb|150px|left|Boyd while playing for the Broncos in 2008]]\n\n===2008===\nIn Round 1 against the [[Penrith Panthers]], Boyd scored a hat-trick in the Broncos 48-12 win at [[Suncorp Stadium]].<ref>https://www.smh.com.au/sport/nrl/broncos-thump-panthers-20080317-gds5jg.html</ref> In May 2008, Boyd started to receive attention from other clubs as he was off-contract at the end of the year. There was speculation that he would move to the [[Canterbury-Bankstown Bulldogs]], alongside fellow Broncos [[Michael Ennis]] and [[Ben Hannant]],<ref>[http://www.foxsports.com.au/story/0,8659,24189096-23214,00.html]   {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080821014256/http://www.foxsports.com.au/story/0%2C8659%2C24189096-23214%2C00.html |date=21 August 2008 }}</ref> or possibly the [[St. George Illawarra Dragons]], following his coach at Brisbane, [[Wayne Bennett (rugby league)|Wayne Bennett]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/nrl/titans-in-running-for-boyd/story-e6frep76-1111116470751|title=Titans in Running for Boyd|publisher=Couriermail.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref> After leading the NRL try-scoring table for most of the first half of the season, Boyd was selected for the [[Queensland rugby league team|Queensland team]] to play [[New South Wales rugby league team|New South Wales]] in Game 2 of the [[2008 State of Origin series]] due to teammate [[Justin Hodges]] suspension.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/06/03/2263771.htm?section=justin|title=Lockyer, Boyd in for Maroons|publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC Online]]|date=3 June 2008|accessdate=3 June 2008}}</ref> Boyd scored 2 tries on debut, both from passes from centre [[Greg Inglis]], with Queensland winning 30-0 at [[Suncorp Stadium]]<ref name=\"origindebut\">{{cite news|url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/story/0,8659,23850457-23214,00.html|title=Boyd quick to show try-scoring feats|accessdate=12 June 2008|date=12 June 2008|publisher=[[Fox Sports (Australia)|Fox Sports]]}}</ref> Boyd also played in Game 3 as the Maroons won 16-10 at [[ANZ Stadium]] and won the series 2-1.<ref>https://www.abc.net.au/news/2008-07-02/maroons-secure-origin-hat-trick/2492256</ref> On 20 August 2008, Boyd signed a 3-year contract with the Dragons starting in 2009,<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=3 June 2008|date=3 June 2008|publisher=[[The Courier Mail]]|url=http://www.news.com.au/couriermail/sport/nrl/story/0,26746,23799455-5016283,00.html|title=Broncos boss Cullen 'shocked' by Justin Hodges charge| first=Steve| last=Ricketts}}</ref> following teammate [[Nick Emmett]] and coach Wayne Bennett. Boyd finished the [[2008 NRL season]] with him playing in 24 matches and scoring 13 tries. On 16 October 2008, Boyd was called up to the [[Australia national rugby league team|Australian]] [[2008 Rugby League World Cup|2008 World Cup squad]] due to teammate Justin Hodges being ruled out with a shoulder injury. On 9 November 2008, Boyd made his international debut for Australia against [[Papua New Guinea national rugby league team|Papua New Guinea]], playing on the wing in the 46-6 win at [[1300SMILES Stadium]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Andy Wilson|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2008/nov/09/australia-papua-new-guinea-rugby|title=Rugby League: Australia ease to comfortable 46-6 win over Papua New Guinea &#124; Sport|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=2015-10-11}}</ref> Boyd only played in 1 match in the World Cup tournament.\n\n===2009===\nIn Round 1 of the [[2009 NRL season]], Boyd made his club debut for the [[St George Illawarra Dragons]] against the Melbourne Storm, playing at fullback in the 17-16 loss at [[Olympic Park]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/storm-win-in-golden-point/story-e6frg6n6-1111119128178|title=Storm Win in Golden Point|publisher=Theaustralian.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref> \nIn Round 4, he travelled to Brisbane for his and Wayne Bennett's first match against their old club, which the Dragons won 25-12, ending the Broncos unbeaten start to the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/nrl/st-george-illawarra-dragons-beat-brisbane-broncos/story-e6frexp0-1225694569392|title=Dragons Beat Broncos|publisher=Dailytelegraph.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref> On 8 May, Boyd played for Australia in the [[2009 Anzac Test|Anzac Test]], playing on the wing and scoring a try in the 38-10.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=[[Fox Sports (Australia)|Fox Sports]]|title=Kangaroos selectors stick by losing World Cup team for New Zealand Test|first=Tom|last=Wald|url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/story/0,8659,25422175-5016947,00.html|date=3 May 2009|accessdate=3 May 2009}}</ref> Boyd was selected in the Queensland squad for the [[2009 State of Origin series]], playing in all 3 matches and scoring 1 try in the record-breaking 4th consecutive series win. In Round 20 against the [[New Zealand Warriors]], Boyd scored his first try as a Dragon in the 29-4 win at [[Mt Smart Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/dragons-closer-to-minor-premiership-warriors-finished-for-season/story-e6frg6n6-1225754876668|title=Dragons Closer to Minor Premiership Warriors Finished for Season|publisher=Theaustralian.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref> In August, Boyd's performance at a press conference, in which the 22-year-old fullback delivered one-sentence responses to eight questions posed to him at a training session in Wollongong, drew an apology to journalists from Dragons coach Wayne Bennett.<ref>{{cite news|title=Wayne Bennett apologises for Darius Boyd interview|url=http://www.illawarramercury.com.au/story/621094/wayne-bennett-apologises-for-darius-boyd-interview/|accessdate=18 July 2013|newspaper=[[Illawarra Mercury]]|date=18 August 2009}}</ref> Boyd finished his first year with the Dragons with 2 tries in  22 matches.\n\n===2010===\nIn Round 5 against his former team the [[Brisbane Broncos]], Boyd played his 100th career match in the Dragons 34-16 win and was named Man of the Match at [[WIN Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/nrl/nrl-premiership/st-george-illawarra-defeat-brisbane-broncos-34-16-at-win-stadium/story-fn2mcuj6-1225919343211|title=St George Illawara Defeat Brisbane Broncos 34-16|publisher=Foxsports.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref> In Round 7, Boyd received the inaugural \"Spirit of ANZAC Medal\" as Man of the Match in the annual [[ANZAC Day Cup]] in the Dragons 28-6 win against the [[Sydney Roosters]] at [[Sydney Football Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/nrl/nrl-premiership/st-george-illawarra-defeat-sydney-roosters-28-6-on-anzac-day-at-the-sfs/story-fn2mcuj6-1225919720783|title=St George Illawara Defeat Sydney Roosters 28-6 on ANZAC Day|publisher=Foxsports.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref> Boyd played on the wing for Queensland in all three matches of the [[2010 State of Origin series]], scoring a try in each match to become the series' top try-scorer. Towards the end of the season, Boyd was one of the favourites for the [[Dally M Medal]], having had a sizeable lead in points over the previous year's winner [[Jarryd Hayne]] and Sydney Roosters player [[Todd Carney]] when voting went behind closed doors after Round 16. He ended up finishing third, 2 points behind eventual winner Todd Carney and 1 point behind [[Wests Tigers]] hooker [[Robbie Farah]]. On 3 October 2010, Boyd played in the Dragons 2010 NRL Grand Final against the Sydney Roosters, playing at fullback in the Dragons 32-8 win and was awarded the Clive Churchill Medal as man of the match.<ref>http://www.illawarramercury.com.au/news/local/sport/rugby-league/2010-clive-churchill-winner-darius-boyd/1958382.aspx?storypage=0\n</ref> Boyd finished his successful [[2010 NRL season]] with him playing in 25 matches and scoring 2 tries. After the 2010 season, Boyd suggested that he may leave the Dragons if head coach Wayne Bennett did so.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/league-news/boyd-could-follow-bennett-out-of-dragons-20101006-166u0.html| work=The Sydney Morning Herald| title=Boyd could follow Bennett out of Dragons| date=6 October 2010}}</ref> On 4 October 2010, Boyd was selected in the Australia Kangaroos 24-man squad for the [[2010 Four Nations]].<ref>https://www.nrl.com/news/2010/10/04/australian-team-named-for-four-nations/</ref> Boyd only played in 1 match, playing against New Zealand, playing at fullback and scoring a try in the 34-20 win at [[Eden Park]].<ref>http://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/4317235/Rowdy-crowd-mars-Eden-Park-rugby-league-test</ref> Boyd won the 2010 [[RLIF]] Fullback of the Year award in the off-season.\n\n===2011===\nBoyd played in the Dragons [[Rugby League Charity Shield (Australia)|Charity Shield]] 32-10 win over the [[South Sydney Rabbitohs]], scoring a try while playing at five-eighth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/nrl/nrl-premiers-st-george-illawarra-defeat-south-sydney-32-in-charity-shield-match-at-anz-stadium/story-e6frf3ou-1226005357795|title=St George Illawara Defeat South Sydney|publisher=Foxsports.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref> Boyd also played in the Dragons' [[2011 World Club Challenge]] against the [[Wigan Warriors]], playing at fullback in the 21-15 win at [[DW Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/nrl/st-george-illawarra-dragons-voted-team-under-most-pressure-by-nrl-rivals/story-e6frep7x-1226014896897|title=Dragons Voted Team Most Under Pressure by NRL Rivals|publisher=Couriermail.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref> In Round 1 against the [[Gold Coast Titans]], Boyd equalled his 2009 and 2010 efforts with a double in the Dragons 25-16 win at [[Robina Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/nrl/dragons-25-titans-16-darius-boyd-scores-twice-as-nrl-premiers-open-season-with-win/story-e6frep5x-1226020415406|title=Darius Boyd Scores Twice as NRL Premiers Open Season with Win|publisher=Couriermail.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref> On 30 March 2011, Wayne Bennett announced he would not coach the Dragons in 2012, hinting that Boyd may leave the club as well.<ref name=\"TVNZ_4094006\">{{cite web|url=http://tvnz.co.nz/rugby-league-news/bennett-boyd-heading-back-broncos-4094006|title=Bennett, Boyd heading back to Broncos?|date=31 March 2011|work=[[Television New Zealand]]|accessdate=27 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/asst-price-to-coach-dragons-after-bennett/tabid/10874/newsid/62005/default.aspx|title=News Article|publisher=Nrl.com|date=|accessdate=2015-10-11}}</ref> After Bennett signed a 4-year contract with the [[Newcastle Knights]], Boyd was offered contracts from the Knights and the [[Gold Coast Titans]]. On 9 May 2011, the Titans officially withdrew their offer. On 9 June 2011, Boyd signed a 4-year contract with the Newcastle Knights starting in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/boyd-signs-four-year-deal-with-knights/tabid/10874/newsid/63231/default.aspx|title=News Article|publisher=Nrl.com|date=|accessdate=2015-10-11}}</ref> Boyd played in all three matches of the [[2011 State of Origin series]] in the Maroons 6th consecutive series win. Boyd\u2019s final game for the Dragons was against his former club, the [[Brisbane Broncos]] at [[Suncorp Stadium]]. Boyd scored the try that forced golden point for the Dragons, after they were down 12-6, but the Dragons ultimately lost the match 13-12, after his test, state and former club captain, [[Darren Lockyer]] kicked the winning field goal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/nrl/brisbane-broncos-v-st-george-illawarra-dragons-at-suncorp-stadium/story-e6frep5x-1226139829136|title=Broncos v Dragons|publisher=Couriermail.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref> Boyd finished the [[2011 NRL season]] with him playing in 22 matches and scoring 9 tries. On 16 October 2011, Boyd scored 2 tries for Australia in the 42-6 test match win against New Zealand at [[Hunter Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/nrl/kangaroos/kangaroos-beat-new-zealand-42-6-in-rugby-leage-test-at/story-fn2mcuhw-1226167876650|title=Kangaroos Beat New Zealand 42-6|publisher=Foxsports.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref> Boyd was selected in the Australian squad for the [[2011 Four Nations]] tournament held in the United Kingdom. Boyd played all 4 matches and scoring 3 triesincluding playing at fullback in the Kangaroos 30-8 Four Nations Final win against [[England national rugby league team|England]] at [[Elland Road]].<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2011/nov/19/four-nations-england-australia</ref>\n[[File:Boyd.PNG|thumb|left|Boyd while playing for the Knights in 2012]]\n\n===2012===\n[[File:Darius Boyd PM XIII.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Boyd playing for the Prime Minister's XIII in 2012]]\nIn Round 1 of the [[2012 NRL season]], Boyd made his club debut for the [[Newcastle Knights]] against his former club the [[St George Illawarra Dragons]], playing at fullback in the Knights 15-14 golden point extra time loss at [[Hunter Stadium]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Greg Prichard|url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/league-match-report/apprentice-price-gets-one-over-master-in-thrilling-seasonopener-20120302-1u66m.html|title=Apprentice Price gets one over master in thrilling season-opener|newspaper=Smh.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-11}}</ref> On 20 April 2012, Boyd played for Australia in the [[2012 Anzac Test]], playing on the wing in the Kangaroos 20-12 win [[Eden Park]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/lowdown-on-test-blockbuster/story-e6frexni-1226334489834|title=Lowdown on Test Blockbuster|publisher=Dailytelegraph.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref> Boyd played on the wing for Queensland in all three matches of the [[2012 State of Origin series]], scoring 3 tries in the Maroons 7th consecutive series win.\n\nIn Round 21 against the [[Canberra Raiders]], Boyd scored his first club try as a Knight in the 36-6 win at [[Canberra Stadium]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Jon Tuxworth|url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/league-match-report/bennett-breaks-canberra-hoodoo-as-knights-stay-on-a-roll-20120729-235pf.html|title=Bennett breaks Canberra hoodoo as Knights stay on a roll|newspaper=Smh.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-11}}</ref> Boyd finished his first year with the Knights with him playing in 22 matches and scoring 3 tries. On 23 September 2012, Boyd for [[Prime Minister\u2019s XIII]] against [[Papua New Guinea national rugby league team|Papua New Guinea]], playing at fullback in the 24-18 win at [[Port Moresby]].<ref>https://www.nrl.com/news/2012/09/23/prime-ministers-xiii-scrape-home-in-port-moresby/</ref> On 13 October 2012, Boyd played on the wing for Australia in their 18-10 win over New Zealand.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/nrl/live-blog-australia-v-new-zealand/story-e6frfgbo-1226494980023|title=Australia v New Zealand|publisher=Heraldsun.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref>\n\n===2013===\nOn 19 April 2013, Boyd played for Australia on the wing and scored a try in the [[2013 Anzac Test]] 32-12 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/nrl/australia-beats-new-zealand-32-12-at-canbera-stadium/story-e6frexnr-1226624627487|title=Australia Beats New Zealand 32-12|publisher=Dailytelegraph.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref> He played all three games and was the top try scorer with 3 in the [[2013 State of Origin series]] in which Queensland extended their record for consecutive series victories to eight. Boyd played in 26 matches and scored 11 tries for the Knights. Selected in the 24-man Australian [[2013 Rugby League World Cup]] squad,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/rugby-league-world-cup-squads/tabid/10874/newsid/75063/default.aspx|title=Rugby League World Cup squads|publisher=NRL.com|date=|accessdate=2015-10-11}}</ref> he played in 5 matches and scored 4 tries. Boyd played on the wing in the Kangaroos 34-2 World Cup Final win against the Kiwis at [[Old Trafford]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Bott|first=Richard|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/rugbyleague/article-2516064/Australia-34-New-Zealand-2-Kangaroos-crowned-world-champions.html|title=Australia 34 New Zealand 2: Kangaroos crowned world champions &#124; Daily Mail Online|publisher=Dailymail.co.uk|date=|accessdate=2015-10-11}}</ref>\n\n===2014===\nOn 2 May 2014, Boyd played on the wing for Australia in the [[2014 Anzac Test]], in the Kangaroos 30-18 win at [[Sydney Football Stadium]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Chris Barrett|url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/league-match-report/australia-get-the-victory-but-new-zealand-take-the-plaudits-after-giving-world-champions-a-scare-20140502-zr3lc.html|title=Australia get the victory but New Zealand take the plaudits after giving world champions a scare|newspaper=Smh.com.au|date=2014-05-02|accessdate=2015-10-11}}</ref> In Round 13 against the [[Wests Tigers]] at [[Hunter Stadium]], Boyd played his 200th career match in the Knights 23-20 loss at [[Hunter Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Dillon|first=Robert|url=http://www.theherald.com.au/story/2337900/luckless-knights-slump-to-sixth-straight-loss-pics/|title=Luckless Knights slump to sixth straight loss, pics &#124; Newcastle Herald|publisher=Theherald.com.au|date=2014-06-08|accessdate=2015-10-11}}</ref> Boyd played on the wing in all 3 matches of the [[2014 State of Origin series]], scoring 3 tries in the Maroons first series defeat since 2005.\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/sport/nrl/jarryd-hayne-steers-nsw-blues-to-state-of-origin-win-over-maroons/story-fnca0von-1226935045717|title=Jarryd Hayne Steers NSW Blues to State of Origin Win Over Maroons|publisher=Theaustralian.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Michael Chammas|url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/league-match-report/queensland-maroons-beat-nsw-blues-to-score-consolation-win-20140709-zt1wq.html|title=Queensland Maroons beat NSW Blues to score consolation win|newspaper=Smh.com.au|date=2014-07-09|accessdate=2015-10-11}}</ref> On 23 July 2014, Boyd admitted himself to a [[mental health]] clinic to treat [[Depression (mood)|depression]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Brett Keeble|url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/league-news/newcastle-knights-darius-boyd-admitted-to-mental-health-clinic-to-treat-depression-20140723-zvwa2.html|title=Newcastle Knights Darius Boyd admitted to mental health clinic to treat depression|newspaper=Smh.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-11}}</ref> On 14 August, Boyd completed his treatment for depression and came out about him admitting himself to rehab.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/nrl/darius-boyd-reveals-how-he-hit-rock-bottom-his-21-days-in-rehab-and-the-family-demons-he-is-confronting-to-beat-depression/story-fni3gf5j-1227025848132|title=Darius Boyd Reveals How He Hit Rock Bottom|publisher=Dailytelegraph.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref> He didn't make a return to the Knights for the rest of the year as he continued to focus on his recovery. On 31 October 2014, Boyd was released from the final year of his Knights contract.<ref>{{cite news|author=Robert Dillon|url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/newcastle-knights/darius-boyd-released-by-newcastle-knights-20141031-11f9tp.html|title=Darius Boyd released by Newcastle Knights|newspaper=Smh.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-11}}</ref> On 21 November 2014, Boyd signed a three-year contract with the Brisbane Broncos, returning to the club where he made his debut in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.broncos.com.au/news/2014/11/21/boyd_a_bronco_again.html|title=Boyd A Bronco Again|publisher=Broncos|date=|accessdate=2015-10-11}}</ref> He finished the [[2014 NRL season]] with him playing in 14 matches and scoring 3 tries.\n\n===2015===\nOn 5 December 2015, Boyd ruptured his [[Achilles tendon]] during pre-season training; this injury was expected to keep him out of action for at least six months, possibly seeing him sidelined for the entire 2015 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/nrl/nrl-premiership/brisbane-broncos-darius-boyd-snaps-achilles-will-miss-up-to-nine-months/story-e6frf3pc-1227145685369|title=Broncos Darius Boyd Snaps Achilles ; Will Miss Up To Nine Months|publisher=Foxsports.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref> However, Boyd made a surprise return in Round 9 against the [[Penrith Panthers]] at fullback in the Broncos 8-5 win at [[Suncorp Stadium]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Beth Newman|url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/darius-boyd-makes-successful-comeback-for-brisbane-broncos-20150508-ggxqx5.html|title=Darius Boyd makes successful comeback for Brisbane Broncos|newspaper=Smh.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref> Queensland coach, [[Mal Meninga]], showing faith in Boyd to perform in Origin despite not playing the majority of the early [[2015 NRL season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/nrl/qld-state-of-origin-2015-team-live-coverage-as-mal-meninga-confirms-squad/story-fniablg6-1227359881127|title=State of Origin 2015 Live Team Coverage|publisher=Couriermail.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref> Boyd played in all 3 matches and scored a try for Queensland in the [[2015 State of Origin series]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/nrl/state-of-origin-2015-game-3-maroons-winger-darius-boyd-boasts-deadly-suncorp-scoring-record/story-fniablkr-1227424014110?sv=e6b88f22d8270968c05a0dbfa38f9fc2|title=Darius Boyd Boasts Deadly Suncorp Scoring Record|publisher=Couriermail.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref> In Round 16 against his former club the [[Newcastle Knights]], Boyd scored his first try after returning to the Broncos in the 44-22 win at [[Suncorp Stadium]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Beth Newman|url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/state-of-origin/broncos-and-maroons-prop-josh-mcguire-pragmatic-after-achilles-injury-20150626-ghz1te.html|title=Broncos and Maroons prop Josh McGuire pragmatic after achilles injury|newspaper=Smh.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref> In the Preliminary Finals match against the [[Sydney Roosters]], Boyd scored an intercept try in the first minute of the match after Roosters winger [[Shaun Kenny-Dowall]] attempted a 20-metre pass to fullback [[Roger Tuivasa-Sheck]], the Broncos later won 31-12, sending them to the Grand Final.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/league-match-report/roosters-winger-shaun-kennydowalls-shocker-helps-brisbane-broncos-to-another-nrl-grand-final-20150925-gjvbgh.html|title=Roosters winger Shaun Kenny-Dowall's shocker helps Brisbane Broncos to another NRL grand final|newspaper=Smh.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref> On 4 October 2015, in the [[2015 NRL Grand Final]] against the [[North Queensland Cowboys]], Boyd played at fullback in the Broncos historic golden point 17-16 loss.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/league-match-report/nrl-grand-final-2015-north-queensland-cowboys-outgun-brisbane-broncos-to-win-premiership-20151004-gk12is.html|title=NRL Grand Final 2015: North Queensland Cowboys outgun Brisbane Broncos to win premiership|newspaper=Smh.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/nrl/nrl-grand-final-player-ratings-broncos-v-cowboys-who-starred-and-who-struggled/story-fni3fbgz-1227556818349?sv=d513a72ed0eabb4bbeaad8561926d617|title=NRL Grand Final Player Ratings|publisher=Dailytelegraph.com.au|accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref> Boyd finished his return year with the Brisbane Broncos with him playing in 18 matches and scoring 3 tries in the [[2015 NRL season]].\n\n===2016===\nOn 1 February, Boyd was named in the Broncos' [[2016 NRL Auckland Nines]] squad.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/thaiday-to-captain-broncos-nines-squad/tabid/10874/newsid/91547/default.aspx|title=Thaiday to captain Broncos' Nines squad|website=NRL.com|date=|accessdate=2016-02-02}}</ref> Following a season-ending shoulder injury to his Queensland Origin team-mate [[Billy Slater]], Boyd was selected to play Fullback for Australia against New Zealand in the [[2016 Anzac Test]], scoring a try on the 16-0 win at [[Hunter Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/representative-round-team-lists/tabid/10874/newsid/95512/default.aspx|title=UPDATED: Representative Round team lists|publisher=NRL.com|date=2016-02-28|accessdate=2016-05-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160604182259/http://www.nrl.com/representative-round-team-lists/tabid/10874/newsid/95512/default.aspx|archive-date=4 June 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.news.com.au/sport/nrl/live-coverage-of-the-anzac-test-between-australia-and-new-zealand-at-hunter-stadium-newcastle/news-story/5300bf4c11d489981ee82f5d0622f823|title=Australia v New Zealand Trans-Tasman test live blog, scores, results , stats, video|work=News.com.au|date=2016-05-03|accessdate=2016-05-07}}</ref> With [[Billy Slater]] already out of action due to injury, Boyd filled the Fullback role for Queensland in the [[2016 State of Origin series]], where he played in all 3 matches and scored 1 try in the Maroons series win.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/nrl/state-of-origin/state-of-origin-2016-billy-slater-says-darius-boyd-has-taken-fullback-play-to-another-level/news-story/02d9086af88d48f068e60163d73ae337|title=Billy Slater Says Darius Boyd Has Taken Fullback Play to Another Level|website=Couriermail.com.au|accessdate=2016-10-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Margan|first=Max|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/nrl/article-3687979/State-Origin-Game-3-Fans-flock-ANZ-Stadium-watch-Queensland-Maroons-NSW-Blues.html|title=State of Origin Game 3: Fans flock to ANZ Stadium to watch Queensland Maroons take on NSW Blues &#124; Daily Mail Online|website=Dailymail.co.uk|date=2016-07-13|accessdate=2016-10-03}}</ref> In Round 14 against the [[Canberra Raiders]], Boyd scored a classy hat trick of tries in a space of 14 minutes in the Broncos 26-18 win at [[Suncorp Stadium]]. This was the first time Boyd scored a hat trick of tries since Round 1 of the 2008 season.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/nrl/nrl-2016-darius-boyd-hattrick-soothes-injury-pain-in-brisbane-broncos-win-over-canberra-raiders/news-story/83bba91089ff963e5c978583c2a389b1|title=Darius Boyd Hattrick Soothes Injury Pain in Brisbane Broncos Win Over Canberra Raiders|website=Couriermail.com.au|accessdate=2016-10-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2016/jun/10/boyd-earns-darren-lockyer-comparisons-from-wayne-bennett-after-broncos-win|title=Boyd earns Darren Lockyer comparisons from Wayne Bennett after Broncos win &#124; Sport|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=2016-10-03}}</ref> Boyd finished the [[2016 NRL season]] with him playing in 25 matches and scoring 9 tries for the Broncos. On 20 September 2016, Boyd was added to the Kangaroos [[2016 Rugby League Four Nations|2016 Four Nations]] train-on squad.<ref>{{cite web|last=Luca|first=Rocco|url=http://rugbyleagueweek.com.au/kangaroos-train-squad-announced-2/|title=Kangaroos train-on squad announced|publisher=Rugby League Week|date=2016-09-20|accessdate=2016-10-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161023013118/http://rugbyleagueweek.com.au/kangaroos-train-squad-announced-2/|archive-date=23 October 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> On 4 October 2016, Boyd was selected in the [[Australian Kangaroos]] Final 24-man squad for the tournament.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/2016-kangaroos-four-nations-squad/tabid/10874/newsid/101933/default.aspx |title=2016 Kangaroos Four Nations squad |website=NRL.com |date=2016-10-04 |accessdate=2017-06-05}}</ref> Boyd played in 4 matches and scored 2 tries of tournament including starting at fullback and scoring a try in the Kangaroos 34-8 Four Nations Final win against New Zealand at [[Anfield]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Laybourn |first=Ian |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/rugbyleague/article-3954908/Australia-34-8-New-Zealand-Mal-Meninga-s-ruthless-storm-victory-Four-Nations-final-Anfield.html |title=Australia 34-8 New Zealand: Mal Meninga's ruthless side storm to victory in Four Nations final at Anfield |website=Dailymail.co.uk |date=2016-11-20 |accessdate=2017-06-05}}</ref> On 7 October 2016, Boyd was awarded with the [[Paul Morgan (rugby league)|Paul Morgan]] Medal as being the Broncos best-and-fairest player of the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/nrl/teams/broncos/broncos-fullback-darius-boyd-has-won-his-first-brisbane-bestandfairest-award/news-story/bb5ff9d3895867bdb460418ab0656a85 |title=Darius Boyd Has Won His First Brisbane Best and Fairest Award |website=Couriermail.com.au |accessdate=2017-06-05}}</ref>\n\n===2017===\nBefore the start of the 2017 season, Boyd joined the likes of [[Darren Lockyer]], [[Wally Lewis]], [[Allan Langer]] and [[Gorden Tallis]] when he was named the ninth Broncos captain in the club's 30-year history.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Meyn|first1=Travis|title=Brisbane Broncos captain 2017: Darius Boyd takes over from Corey Parker, completing NRL career resurrection|url=http://www.news.com.au/sport/brisbane-broncos-new-captain-for-2017/news-story/445391b4a52669c7096cd8e9e8fc5a0b|work=news.com.au|accessdate=19 March 2017}}</ref> In February, he was selected in the Broncos [[2017 NRL Auckland Nines]] squad.<ref>https://www.nrl.com/news/2017/02/04/2017-downer-nrl-auckland-nines-squads/</ref> His first game as captain of the Broncos ended with a 27-18 loss at [[Halliwell Jones Stadium]] to the [[Warrington Wolves]] in the [[2017 World Club Series]].<ref name=\"Warrington 27-18 Brisbane: Wolves' first-half blitz stuns Broncos\">{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/rugby-league/warrington-vs-brisbane/45988|title=Warrington 27-18 Brisbane: Wolves' first-half blitz stuns Broncos|publisher=Sky Sports|date=19 February 2017|accessdate=30 May 2017}}</ref> In Round 3 against the [[Melbourne Storm]], Boyd played his 250th NRL career match in the Broncos 14-12 loss at [[AAMI Park]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/sport/nrl/darius-boyd-is-softly-spoken-but-his-leadership-speaks-volumes/news-story/337ed1bf28a16be23ebe7db70bc3037c|title=Subscribe - theaustralian|website=Theaustralian.com.au|accessdate=2017-06-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/nrl/teams/broncos/melbourne-storm-defeat-brisbane-broncos-1412-as-billy-slater-makes-his-nrl-return/news-story/dcb4733a1d63ccf98d396828d9cc3b5b|title=Cool Storm break Broncos hearts|website=Couriermail.com.au|accessdate=2017-06-05}}</ref> On 5 May, Boyd played for Australia in the [[2017 ANZAC Test]]  where he started at fullback in the 30-12 win.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/sport/nrl/live-australia-vs-new-zealand-anzac-test-in-canberra/news-story/f5b42d8e4765c3040d1f0114dff2a2de |title=Australia vs New Zealand Anzac Test: Live scores, highlights, result, video |website=News.com.au |date=2017-05-05 |accessdate=2017-06-05}}</ref> Despite [[Billy Slater]] coming back from injury, Boyd retained his Maroons fullback role for Game 1 of the series.<ref>http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/billy-slater-not-selected-as-darius-boyd-keeps-fullback-spot-20170521-gw9vxo.html</ref> However, in Game 2 Boyd was switched to centre to accommodate Slater's return to the fullback position.<ref>http://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/nrl/state-of-origin/state-of-origin-2017-darius-boyd-to-start-at-left-centre-as-kevin-walters-rings-the-changes/news-story/e5a3a53656c68957d95db33c6f9c875d</ref> In Round 26 against the [[North Queensland Cowboys]], Boyd injured his [[hamstring]].<ref>http://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/nrl/teams/broncos/brisbane-beat-north-queensland-2010-but-lose-darius-boyd-with-hamstring-injury/news-story/1c7e3f5d9896a5db6e7e939193f6f7e8</ref> Scans revealed bad news for Brisbane with Boyd ruled out for the next 2 finals matches. In the preliminary final against the Melbourne Storm, Boyd made his return as the Broncos looked to make the grand final for the second time in three years.<ref>http://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/nrl/teams/broncos/broncos-boosted-as-darius-boyd-cleared-to-return-against-melbourne-storm/news-story/1323d11f827bb22b197f6477e0d82ecb</ref> Commentators believed Boyd wasn't fully recovered and replays saw him limping. In the second half, Boyd succumbed to his hamstring injury, with the Broncos eventually losing 30-0 and later missed selection for the Kangaroos [[2017 Rugby League World Cup]] squad.<ref>https://www.foxsports.com.au/nrl/nrl-premiership/teams/broncos/nrl-finals-darius-boyds-backfiring-fitness-call-reminiscent-of-allan-langers-last-broncos-game-in-2002/news-story/5c0070dc684ebf3a6d083243f83662cf</ref><ref>https://www.foxsports.com.au/nrl/kangaroos/more-drama-for-kangaroos-world-cup-squad-as-darius-boyd-ruled-out-josh-mansour-called-up/news-story/72003d374ddf07deb643a5dc5099364b</ref> Boyd finished his [[2017 NRL season]] with 18 matches and 3 tries for the Broncos. On 26 October, Boyd extended his contract with the Broncos on a four-year deal, keeping him at Red Hill to until at least the 2021 season.<ref>http://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/nrl/darius-boyd-a-bronco-for-life-skipper-signs-contract-extension/news-story/46b4f57107e5e40f67d473f61eb690b2</ref>\n\n===2018===\nOn 11 June 2018, Boyd announced that he had retired from playing in representative matches after missing out on selection for Queensland. He commented, \"My time\u2019s done in rep footy. I\u2019ve had a great career, I have nothing to be disappointed about, I\u2019m really happy with everything I\u2019ve achieved in the rep arena. I don\u2019t think I have anything more to prove, it\u2019s time for the younger fellas coming in, they have great players, really quality guys coming through.\"<ref>https://www.news.com.au/sport/nrl/darius-boyd-has-called-time-on-his-representative-career/news-story/6e82b9730b8ca801b3be350c8fe89d15</ref> Between Rounds 19-21, Boyd played at centre as coach Wayne Bennett experimented playing youngster [[Jamayne Isaako]] at fullback.<ref>https://www.nrl.com/news/2018/07/19/bennett-switches-boyd-to-centre-to-plug-leaky-defence/</ref><ref>https://www.nrl.com/news/2018/07/21/brisbane-broncos-captain-darius-boyd-happy-to-remain-in-the-centres/</ref> Boyd finished the [[2018 NRL season]] with him playing of the 25 matches and scoring 5 tries for the Broncos.\n\n===2019===\nIn Round 8 against the [[South Sydney Rabbitohs]], Boyd played his 300th NRL career match, playing his milestone game against his old mentor, Rabbitohs coach [[Wayne Bennett (rugby league)|Wayne Bennett]] who Boyd spent his whole career being coached by him until the 2019 season when Bennett was given the sack by the Broncos and swapped clubs with [[Anthony Seibold]].<ref>https://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/nrl/teams/broncos/darius-boyd-set-to-mark-300th-nrl-game-against-wayne-bennett/news-story/2fade4d9d197ea1c2a48e900946a49ce</ref> The Broncos lost the match 38-6 at [[ANZ Stadium]] as the Rabbitohs dedicated the win to the recently retired Rabbitohs star [[Greg Inglis]].<ref>https://www.foxsports.com.au/nrl/nrl-premiership/live-nrl-south-sydney-rabbitohs-v-brisbane-broncos-live-scores-updates-news-blog/news-story/b461d8d29bc09584f7570b5c48cd7801</ref> Boyd has copped plenty of criticism for his form in the early rounds of the 2019 season, practically his defence and leadership. Boyd commented, \u201cI don\u2019t know what the outside noise is saying, but my body is really good and my form, I\u2019m pretty happy with it. \u201cI spoke to \u2018Seibs\u2019 (Broncos coach Anthony Seibold) and he's happy with how I'm performing, \u201cI know if we win some games the critics will go away. \u201cI can be better and I\u2019m not saying I don\u2019t have to put up my hand up and be better, because I know I do, especially as a captain, but I\u2019m not losing sleep over my performances.\u201d<ref>https://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/nrl/broncos-captain-darius-boyd-hits-back-over-criticism-of-nrl-form/news-story/64acbb2c2ea5479cd1d156dce7de10f0</ref> On 30 August 2019, Boyd was selected at Wing for the Queensland Maroons Team of the Decade.\n\nAt the end of the 2019 regular season, Brisbane finished in 8th place on the table and qualified for the finals.  Boyd captained the club in their elimination final against Parramatta which Brisbane lost 58-0 at the new [[Western Sydney Stadium]].  The defeat was Brisbane's biggest ever loss and the biggest loss in finals history which eclipsed Newtown's record when they defeated St George 55-7 in 1944.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-09-15/eels-make-history-with-58-point-finals-flogging-of-broncos/11505120/|title=Parramatta Eels eliminate Brisbane Broncos from the NRL Finals with a thumping 58-0 win|website=ABC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxsports.com.au/nrl/nrl-premiership/finals/fuming-seibold-fires-off-at-players-promises-review-of-roster-after-embarrassing-loss/news-story/aed1578918d1dbedc4eb33c3904d2b0e/|title=Fuming Seibold fires off at players, promises review of roster after \u2018embarrassing\u2019 loss|website=Fox Sports}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nrl.com/news/2019/09/15/seibold-top-to-bottom-review-needed-as-broncos-search-for-answers/|title=Seibold: 'Top to bottom' review needed as Brisbane search for answers|website=NRL}}</ref>\n\n===2020===\nOn 6 March 2020, Boyd announced that he would retire at the end of the [[2020 NRL season]] despite having one year left to run on his contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.broncos.com.au/news/2020/03/06/boyd-to-hang-up-boots-at-end-of-season/?fbclid=IwAR3TsWIfsRmy9rLQptQlQVNldmJ1bn-ctli90utV1hxSRcFOtvf1Ce16xW0|title=Boyd to hang up boots at end of season|publisher=Brisbane Broncos|date=6 March 2020|accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref> He will be the final member from the club's [[2006 NRL season|2006 premiership team]] to retire.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.couriermail.com.au/subscribe/news/1/?sourceCode=CMWEB_WRE170_a_GGL&dest=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.couriermail.com.au%2Fsport%2Fnrl%2Fteams%2Fbroncos%2Fdarius-boyd-on-broncos-captaincy-anthony-seibold-and-retirement-rumours%2Fnews-story%2F25b3f2ee74a359cf62e964a53702c180&memtype=anonymous&mode=premium|title=Darius Boyd on Broncos captaincy, Anthony Seibold and retirement rumours|publisher=The Courier Mail|date=5 December 2019|accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*[https://www.broncos.com.au/teams/telstra-premiership/brisbane-broncos/darius-boyd/ Brisbane Broncos profile]\n*[http://www.broncos.com.au/team/profiles/darius_boyd.html Broncos profile]\n*[http://www.nrl.com/telstrapremiership/playerstats/playerprofile/tabid/10898/clubid/1/playerid/443/seasonid/44/default.aspx NRL profile]\n{{S-start}}\n{{Succession box|title=[[Clive Churchill Medal]]list|before=[[Billy Slater]] ([[Melbourne Storm]])|after=[[Glenn Stewart]] ([[Manly-Warringah Sea Eagles]])|years=2010}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Brisbane Broncos Current}}\n{{Brisbane Broncos squad 2006 NRL premiership}}\n{{St. George Illawarra Dragons squad - 2010 NRL Premiers}}\n{{St. George Illawarra Dragons - 2011 World Club Challenge winners}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title= Australia squads\n| bg=#005100\n| fg=#FFCC33\n| bordercolor=#FFCC33\n|list1= \n{{Australia 2008 Rugby League World Cup squad}}\n{{Australia squad - 2010 Rugby League Four Nations}}\n{{Australia squad - 2011 Rugby League Four Nations}}\n{{Australia 2013 Rugby League World Cup squad}}\n{{Australia squad - 2016 Rugby League Four Nations}}\n}}\n{{Clive Churchill Medallists}}\n{{Rugby league footballers with 300 NRL games}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Boyd, Darius}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Australian rugby league players]]\n[[Category:Australia national rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Brisbane Broncos players]]\n[[Category:Newcastle Knights players]]\n[[Category:St. George Illawarra Dragons players]]\n[[Category:Queensland Rugby League State of Origin players]]\n[[Category:Prime Minister's XIII players]]\n[[Category:Burleigh Bears players]]\n[[Category:Clive Churchill Medal winners]]\n[[Category:Rugby league players from Queensland]]\n[[Category:Rugby league fullbacks]]\n[[Category:Rugby league wingers]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from the Gold Coast, Queensland]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "27.123.224.204", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Darius_Boyd"}
{"title_page": "HIV/AIDS in the United States", "text_new": "<br />{{Sidebar\n| name = Centers for Disease Control Infographics\n| title = CDC Infographics\n| content1 = [[File:Hiv-us-map-2017.png|thumb|300px|Rates of HIV Diagnoses in the US, 2017]]\n| content2 = [[File:New-HIV-Infections-by-Race-and-Transmission-Group.png|thumb|300px|New HIV Infections by Race and Transmission Group]]\n| content3 = [[File:Cdc-hiv-us-at-a-glance.png|thumb|300px|HIV Diagnosis Trends in the U.S. and Dependent Areas, 2012\u20132016]]\n|content4 = [[File:HIV cases by transmission category CDC 2007.svg|thumb|300px|The estimated number of U.S. HIV/AIDS Cases, in 2007 by transmission category<ref name=\"CDCBasicStats\">{{Cite web\n |title=HIV/AIDS Basic Statistics\n |publisher=US Centers for Disease Control\n |date=December 18, 2017\n |url=https://www.cdc.gov/hiv/topics/surveillance/basic.htm\n |accessdate=April 26, 2018}}</ref>]]\n}}\nThe [[AIDS]] epidemic, caused by [[HIV]] (Human Immunodeficiency Virus), found its way to the [[United States]] as early as 1960, but was first noticed after doctors discovered clusters of [[Kaposi's sarcoma]] and [[pneumocystis pneumonia]] in gay men in [[Los Angeles]], [[New York City]], and [[San Francisco]] in 1981. Treatment of HIV/AIDS is primarily via a \"drug cocktail\" of [[antiretroviral drugs]], and education programs to help people avoid infection.\n\nInitially, infected foreign nationals were turned back at the U.S. border to help prevent additional infections. The number of U.S. deaths from AIDS have declined sharply since the early years of the disease's presentation domestically. In the United States in 2016, 1.1 million people aged over 13 lived with an HIV infection, of whom 14% were unaware of their infection.<ref name=\"CDCBasicStats\" /> [[Homosexuality|Gay]] and [[Bisexuality|bisexual]] men, [[African Americans]], and [[Latinos]] remain disproportionately affected by HIV/AIDS in the U.S.\n\n== Mortality and morbidity ==\n\n{{As of|2016}}, about 675,000 people have died of HIV/AIDS in the U.S. since the beginning of the HIV epidemic, and even today, nearly 13,000 people with AIDS in the United States die each year.<ref name=CDC2016Today>{{cite web|title=Today's HIV/AIDS Epidemic Factsheet|url=https://www.cdc.gov/nchhstp/newsroom/docs/factsheets/todaysepidemic-508.pdf|website=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|publisher=U.S. government|accessdate=December 31, 2016}}</ref>\n\nWith improved treatments and better [[Post-exposure prophylaxis|prophylaxis]] against opportunistic infections, [[mortality rate|death rates]] have quite significantly declined.<ref name=\"SFDPH HIV Epi Report 2008\">{{cite web\n |title        = 2008 HIV/AIDS Epidemiology Annual Report\n |publisher    = San Francisco Department of Public Health\n |date         = July 9, 2009\n |url          = http://sfhiv.org/documents/AnnualReport2008.pdf\n |accessdate   = March 21, 2010\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110724191441/http://sfhiv.org/documents/AnnualReport2008.pdf\n |archive-date = July 24, 2011\n |url-status   = dead\n |df           = mdy-all\n}}</ref>\n\nThe overall death rate among persons diagnosed with HIV/AIDS in New York City decreased by sixty-two percent from 2001 to 2012.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www1.nyc.gov/assets/doh/downloads/pdf/dires/2013-hiv-surveillance-annual-report.pdf|title=HIV Surveillance Annual Report, 2013|last=|first=|publisher=New York City Department of Health and Mental Hygiene|year=2013|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n== Containment ==\nAfter the HIV/AIDS outbreak in the 1980s, various responses emerged in an effort to alleviate the issue. These included new medical treatments, travel restrictions, and new public health policies in the United States.\n\n=== Medical treatment ===\n[[File:AIDS Deaths-US 1987-1997.png|thumb|300px|A chart of AIDS deaths in the United States from 1987 to 1997.]]\n[[File:AIDS Deaths-US 1998-2002.png|thumb|300px|A chart of AIDS deaths in the United States from 1998 to 2002.]]\nGreat progress was made in the U.S. following the introduction of three-drug anti-HIV treatments (\"cocktails\") that included [[Management of HIV/AIDS|antiretroviral drugs]]. [[David Ho (scientist)|David Ho]], a pioneer of this approach, was honored as ''[[Time Magazine]]'' Man of the Year for 1996. Deaths were rapidly reduced by more than half, with a small but welcome reduction in the yearly rate of new HIV infections. Since this time, AIDS deaths have continued to decline, but much more slowly, and not as completely in black Americans as in other population segments.<ref name=\"Left Behind Black America\">{{Cite web|last=Wilson |first=Phill |last2=Wright |first2=Kai |last3=Isbell |first3=Michael T. |title=Left Behind: Black America: a Neglected Priority in the Global AIDS Epidemic |publisher=Black AIDS Institute |date=August 2008 |url=http://www.blackaids.org/image_uploads/article_575/08_left_behind.pdf |accessdate=March 20, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100821072159/http://www.blackaids.org/image_uploads/article_575/08_left_behind.pdf |archivedate=August 21, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"NYC DPH AIDS Mortality Historic Low 2002\">{{Cite press release\n |title        = Deaths in New York City Reached Historic Low in 2002\n |publisher    = New York City Department of Health and Mental Hygiene\n |date         = January 30, 2004\n |url          = http://www.nyc.gov/html/doh/html/press_archive04/pr005-0130.shtml\n |accessdate   = March 20, 2010\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20100604072407/http://www.nyc.gov/html/doh/html/press_archive04/pr005-0130.shtml\n |archive-date = 2010-06-04\n |url-status   = dead\n}}</ref>\n\n=== Travel restrictions ===\nIn 1987 the [[Department of Health and Human Services]] (HHS) included HIV in its list of \u201ccommunicable diseases of public health significance\u201d; denying immigrants and short term foreign visits from anyone who tested positive for the virus. <ref name=\"hivexclusion\">{{cite web |title=Federal Register Volume 52, Issue 167 (August 28, 1987) |url=https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/USCODE-2018-title8/html/USCODE-2018-title8-chap12-subchapII-partII-sec1182.htm |website=govinfo.gov |publisher=Office of the Federal Register |accessdate=6 April 2020 |pages=32540-32544}}</ref> <ref name=\"usc8\">{{cite web |title=United States Code: Immigration and Nationality |url=http://cdn.loc.gov/service/ll/uscode/uscode1988-00200/uscode1988-002008012/uscode1988-002008012.pdf |website=LIbrary of Congress |publisher=Office of the Law Revision Counsel |accessdate=6 April 2020 |page=1246 |date=1988}}</ref> In 1993 the US Congress signed the National Institutes of Health Revitalization Act of 1993: removing the HHS\u2019 authority to dictate HIV as a \u201cpublic health significance\u201d, and explicitly including HIV as a cause for denying immigrants and foreign visitors entry into the US.<ref name=\"byndinad\">{{Cite report|title=Moving Beyond the U.S. Government Policy of Inadmissibility of HIV-Infected Noncitizens (PDF)|date=2007-03-01|url=https://csis-prod.s3.amazonaws.com/s3fs-public/legacy_files/files/media/csis/pubs/movingbeyondinadmissibility.pdf|last=Nieburg|first=Phillip|last2=Morrison|first2=J. Stephen|pages=7{{hyphen}}19|format=PDF}}</ref><ref>{{cite act|type= National Institutes of Health Revitalization Act|index=Sec. 2007|date=1993|legislature=103rd Congress|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/103rd-congress/senate-bill/1}}</ref>  For someone seeking US citizenship during the HIV ban, they were required to undergo a medical exam during the legalization process - testing positive would permanently deny them entry into the country.<ref name=\"imm_mexcal\">{{cite journal |last1=Morin |first1=Stephen F |last2=Carrillo |first2=H\u00e9ctor |last3=Steward |first3=Wayne T |last4=Maiorana |first4=Andre |last5=Trautwein |first5=Mark |last6=G\u00f3mez |first6=Cynthia A |title=Policy Perspectives on Public Health For Mexican Migrants in California |journal=JAIDS Journal of Acquired Immune Deficiency Syndromes |date=November 2004 |volume=37 |pages=S252\u2013S259 |doi=10.1097/01.qai.0000141254.61840.05}}</ref> The law extended to medication, where foreign travelers could be arrested for having antiretroviral drugs on their carry-ons. A famous example was in 1989: a Dutch traveler to Minnesota was arrested for \u201cseveral days\u201d because they were carrying [[AZT]] in their luggage.<ref name=\"byndinad\" />\n\nGoing into the 2000s, people who are HIV positive seeking temporary visas or vacationing to the US would have to avoid revealing their status on application forms, and plan for their medication to be sent to the US or stop taking their medication.<ref name=\"mahto2006>{{cite journal |last1=Mahto |first1=M |last2=Ponnusamy |first2=K |last3=Schuhwerk |first3=M |last4=Richens |first4=J |last5=Lambert |first5=N |last6=Wilkins |first6=E |last7=Churchill |first7=DR |last8=Miller |first8=RF |last9=Behrens |first9=RH |title=Knowledge, attitudes and health outcomes in HIV-infected travellers to the USA |journal=HIV Medicine |date=May 2006 |volume=7 |issue=4 |pages=201\u2013204 |doi=10.1111/j.1468-1293.2006.00371.x}}</ref> Eventually the US began offering temporary admission waivers for people who are HIV positive. As stated in an interoffice memorandum in 2004, foreign nationals who are HIV positive could qualify for the waiver by falling into either category: humanitarian/public interest reasons, or \u201cattendees of certain designated international events held in the United States\u201d.<ref name=\"waivers\">{{Cite report|title=Exception to Nonimmigrant HIV Waiver Policy for K and V Nonimmigrants (PDF)|date=2004-11-02|url=https://www.uscis.gov/sites/default/files/USCIS/Laws/Memoranda/Static_Files_Memoranda/Archives%201998-2008/2004/kandv_hiv110204.pdf|last=R. Yates|first=William|publisher=U.S. Citizenship and Immigration Services (USCIS)}}</ref>\n\nIn early December 2006, President [[George W. Bush]] indicated that he would issue an executive order allowing HIV-positive people to enter the [[United States]] on standard visas. It was unclear whether applicants would still have to declare their HIV status.<ref name=\"Russell2006\">{{Cite news\n  | last = Russell | first = Sabin\n  | title = Bush to ease rule limiting HIV-positive foreign visitors\n  | newspaper = San Francisco Chronicle\n  | publisher = Hearst Communications\n  | date = December 2, 2006\n  | url = http://articles.sfgate.com/2006-12-02/news/17323943_1_hiv-positive-world-aids-day-international-aids-conferences\n  | accessdate = March 21, 2010}}</ref> However, the ban remained in effect throughout Bush's Presidency. In August 2007, Congresswoman [[Barbara Lee]] of California introduced {{USBill|110|h|3337}}, the HIV Nondiscrimination in Travel and Immigration Act of 2007. This bill would have allowed travelers and immigrants entry to the United States without having to disclose their HIV status. The bill died at the end of the [[110th United States Congress|110th Congress]].<ref name=\"BBC2009\">{{cite web |title=Activist helps US HIV law change |website=BBC NEWS |date=July 6, 2009 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/8136456.stm |accessdate=April 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2008, then President George W. Bush signed {{USBill|110|h|5501}} that lifted the ban in statutory law. However, the [[United States Department of Health and Human Services]] still held the ban in administrative (written regulation) law. New impetus was added to repeal efforts when Paul Thorn, a UK tuberculosis expert who was invited to speak at the 2009 [[Pacific Health Summit]] in Seattle, was denied a visa due to his HIV positive status. A letter written by Mr. Thorn, and read in his place at the Summit, was obtained by Congressman [[Jim McDermott]], who advocated the issue to the Obama administration's Health Secretary.<ref name=\"BBC2009\" />\n\nOn October 30, 2009 President [[Barack Obama]] reauthorized the [[Ryan White]] HIV/AIDS Bill which expanded care and treatment through federal funding to nearly half a million.<ref name=\"obamawh\">{{cite web\n  | last = Crowley\n  | first = Jeffrey\n  | authorlink = Jeffrey Crowley\n  | title = Honoring the Legacy of Ryan White\n  | work = WhiteHouse.gov\n  | publisher = Office of the President of the United States\n  | date = October 30, 2009\n  | url = http://www.whitehouse.gov/blog/2009/10/30/honoring-legacy-ryan-white\n  | accessdate = March 21, 2010}}</ref> He also announced that the Department of Health and Human Services crafted regulation that would end the HIV Travel and Immigration Ban effective in January 2010;<ref name=\"obamawh\" /> on January 4, 2010, the [[United States Department of Health and Human Services]], [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] removed HIV infection from the list of \"[[communicable diseases]] of public health significance,\" due to it not being spread by casual contact, or by air, food or water, and removed HIV status as a factor to be considered in the granting of [[Visa (document)|travel visas]], disallowing HIV status from among the diseases that could prevent people who are not U.S. citizens from entering the country.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cdc.gov/immigrantrefugeehealth/laws-regs/hiv-ban-removal/final-rule-technical-qa.html |title=Final Rule Removing HIV Infection from U.S. Immigration Screening |accessdate=2017-01-02 |publisher=[[United States Department of State]] |date=2010-01-19}}</ref>\n\n=== Public health policies ===\n[[File:A woman with her hand in her hair and the other pulling up Wellcome L0052386.jpg|thumb|upright|1993 poster for \"America responds to AIDS\" \u2013 a campaign by the Department of Health]]\nSince the beginning of the HIV epidemic, several U.S. presidents have attempted to implement a national plan to control the issue. In 1987, President Reagan created a Presidential Commission on the HIV Epidemic. This commission was recruited to investigate what steps are necessary for responding to the HIV outbreak, and the consensus was to establish more HIV testing, focus on prevention and treatment as well as expanding HIV care throughout the U.S.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Yehia|first=Baligh|last2=Frank|first2=Ian|date=2011|title=Battling AIDS in America: An Evaluation of the National HIV/AIDS Strategy|journal=American Journal of Public Health|volume=101|issue=9|pages=e4\u2013e8|doi=10.2105/ajph.2011.300259|pmid=21778507|pmc=3154226|issn=0090-0036}}</ref> However, these changes were not implemented during this time, and the commission recommendations were largely ignored.\n\nAnother attempt to respond to the HIV outbreak took place in 1996, when President Clinton established the National AIDS Strategy, which aimed to reduce number of infections, enhance research on HIV treatment, increase access to resources for people affected by AIDS, and also alleviate the racial disparities in HIV treatment and care.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Improving outcomes blueprint for a national AIDS plan for the United States.|last=Collins, Chris.|date=2007|publisher=Open Society Institute|oclc=1100047917}}</ref> Similarly to Reagan's plan, the National AIDS Strategy was not successfully enforced, providing only objectives without a specific action plan for implementation.\n\nIn 2010, President Obama created the National HIV/AIDS Strategy for the United States (NHAS), with its three main objectives being to reduce the annual number of infections, reduce health disparities, and increase access to resources and HIV care.<ref name=\":2\" /> However, this new strategy differs in that it includes an Implementation Plan, with a timeline for achieving each of the three goals, as well as a document outlining the specific action plan that will be used.<ref>{{Cite book|title=National HIV/AIDS strategy : federal implementation plan.|last=United States. Office of National AIDS Policy.|date=2010|publisher=White House Office of National AIDS Policy|oclc=656320879}}</ref>\n\nPresident Trump announced a plan in his 2019 [[State of the Union Address]] to stop new HIV infections in the United States by 2030, though critics pointed to the President's policies reducing access to health insurance, anti-immigrant and anti-transgender policies as undermining this goal.<ref>[https://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2019/02/06/691934890/halting-u-s-hiv-epidemic-by-2030-difficult-but-doable Halting U.S. HIV Epidemic By 2030: Difficult But Doable]</ref> The [[Department of Health and Human Services]] issued grants to 32 HIV \"hotspots\" in 2019, and Congress earmarked over $291 million for the president's plan in FY2020.<ref>[https://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2019/12/18/789291340/some-big-health-care-policy-changes-are-hiding-in-the-federal-spending-package Some Big Health Care Policy Changes Are Hiding In The Federal Spending Package]</ref>\n\n== Public perception ==\n[[File:Prevalence of HIV infections in the United States and total AIDS deaths.svg|thumb|400px|The number of people living with HIV in the United States, and the total cumulative number of deaths.]]\n\nOne of the best known works on the history of HIV is the 1987 book ''[[And the Band Played On]]'' by [[Randy Shilts]]. Shilts contends that [[Ronald Reagan]]'s administration dragged its feet in dealing with the crisis due to homophobia, while the gay community viewed early reports and public health measures with corresponding distrust, thus allowing the disease to infect hundreds of thousands more. This resulted in the formation of ACT-UP, the [[AIDS Coalition to Unleash Power]] by [[Larry Kramer]]. Galvanized by the federal government's inactivity, the movement by AIDS activists to gain funding for AIDS research, which on a per-patient basis out-paced funding for more prevalent diseases such as cancer and heart disease, was used as a model for future lobbying for health research funding.<ref>{{cite journal\n|last= Kahn Best\n|first= Rachel\n|title= Disease Politics and Medical Research Funding: Three Ways Advocacy Shapes Policy\n|journal= American Sociological Review\n|volume= 77\n|issue= 5\n|pages= 780\u2013803\n|doi= 10.1177/0003122412458509\n|year= 2012\n|doi-access= free\n}}</ref>\n\nThe Shilts work popularized the [[HIV and AIDS misconceptions|misconception]] that the disease was introduced by a gay [[flight attendant]] named [[Ga\u00ebtan Dugas]], referred to as \"[[Index case|Patient Zero]],\" although the author did not actually make this claim in the book. However, subsequent research has revealed that there were cases of AIDS much earlier than initially known. HIV-infected blood samples have been found from as early as 1959 in Africa ''(see [[HIV]] main entry)'', and HIV has been shown to have caused the death of [[Robert Rayford]], a 16-year-old St. Louis male, in 1969, who could have contracted it as early as 7 years old due to sexual abuse, suggesting that HIV had been present, at very low prevalence, in the U.S. since before the 1970s.\n\nAn early theory asserted that a series of [[inoculation]]s against [[hepatitis B]] that were performed in the gay community of [[San Francisco]] were tainted with HIV. Although there was a high correlation between recipients of that [[vaccination]] and initial cases of AIDS, this theory has long been discredited. HIV, [[hepatitis B]], and [[hepatitis C]] are bloodborne diseases with very similar modes of transmission, and those at risk for one are at risk for the others.<ref name=\"NIOSH Bloodborne\">{{Cite web\n  | title = Bloodborne Infectious Diseases HIV/AIDS, Hepatitis B Virus, and Hepatitis C Virus\n  | publisher = US National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health\n  | date = March 10, 2010\n  | url = https://www.cdc.gov/niosh/topics/bbp/\n  | accessdate = March 21, 2010}}</ref>\n\nActivists and critics of current AIDS policies allege that another preventable impediment to stemming the spread of the disease and/or finding a treatment was the vanity of \"celebrity\" scientists. [[Robert Gallo]], an American scientist involved in the search for a new [[virus]] in the people affected by the disease, became embroiled in a legal battle with French scientist [[Luc Montagnier]], who had first discovered such a virus in tissue cultures derived from a patient suffering from enlargement of the lymphnodes (an early sign of AIDS). Montagnier had named the new virus LAV (Lymphoadenopathy-Associated Virus).\n\nGallo, who appeared to question the primacy of the French scientist's discovery, refused to recognize the \"French virus\" as the cause of AIDS, and tried instead to claim the disease was caused by a new member of a retrovirus family, [[HTLV]], which he had discovered. Critics claim that because some scientists were more interested in trying to win a Nobel prize than in helping patients, research progress was delayed and more people needlessly died. After a number of meetings and high-level political intervention, the French scientists and Gallo agreed to \"share\" the discovery of HIV, although eventually Montagnier and his group were recognized as the true discoverers, and won the 2008 Nobel Prize for it.\n\nPublicity campaigns were started in attempts to counter the incorrect and often vitriolic perception of AIDS as a \"gay plague\". These included the [[Ryan White]] case, red ribbon campaigns, celebrity dinners, the [[And the Band Played On (film)|1993 film version]] of ''And the Band Played On'', [[AIDS education|sex education programs]] in schools, and [[Public service announcement|television advertisements]]. Announcements by various celebrities that they had contracted HIV (including actor [[Rock Hudson]], basketball star [[Magic Johnson]], tennis player [[Arthur Ashe]] and singer [[Freddie Mercury]]) were significant in arousing media attention and making the general public aware of the dangers of the disease to people of all sexual orientations.<ref>Small, Neil. \"Dying in a Public Place: AIDS Deaths.\" ''The Sociological Review'' 40, no. 1_suppl (May 1992): 87\u2013111.</ref>\n\n== Perspective of doctors ==\nAIDS was met with great fear and concern by the nation, much like any other epidemic, and those who were primarily affected were populations that the majority did not think highly of: homosexuals, African-Americans, Latinos, and intravenous drug users. The general thought of the population was to create distance and establish boundaries from these people, and some doctors were not immune from such impulses. During the epidemic, doctors began to not treat AIDS patients, not only to create distance from these groups of people, but also because they were afraid to contract the disease themselves. A surgeon in Milwaukee stated, \"I've got to be selfish. It's an incurable disease that's uniformly fatal, and I'm constantly at risk for getting it. I've got to think about myself. I've got to think about my family. That responsibility is greater than to the patient.\" <ref name=\":02\">{{Cite book|title=Aids Doctors Voices from the Epidemic|last=Bayer|first=Ronald|publisher=Oxford University|year=2000|isbn=0-19-512681-5|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/aidsdoctorsvoice00rona/page/4 4\u20135]|url=https://archive.org/details/aidsdoctorsvoice00rona/page/4}}</ref>\n\nSome doctors thought it was their duty to stay away from the virus because they had other patients to think of. In a survey of doctors in the mid to late 1980s, a substantial number of physicians indicated that they didn't have an ethical obligation to treat and care for those patients with HIV/AIDS.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Link|first=Nathan|date=April 1988|title=Concerns of Medical and Pediatric House Officers about Acquiring AIDS from their Patients|url=|journal=American Journal of Public Health|volume=|pages=445\u2013459|via=}}</ref> A study of primary care providers showed that half would not care for patients if they were given a choice.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gerbert|first=Barbara|date=1991|title=Primary Care Physicians and AIDS|url=|journal=Journal of American Medical Association|volume=|pages=2837\u20132842|via=}}</ref> In 1990, a national survey of doctors showed that \"only 24% believed that office-based practitioners should be legally required to provide care to individuals with HIV infection.\"<ref name=\":02\" /> However, there were many doctors who chose to care for these patients with AIDS for different reasons: they shared the same sexual orientation as the infected, a commitment to providing care to the diseased, an interest in the mysteries of infectious disease, or a desire to tame the awful threat.<ref name=\":02\" /> Treating patients infected with the AIDS virus changed some doctors' personal lives, as it caused them to have to deal with some of the same stigmas that their patients had. This disease also weighed on their minds, because they often had to deal with witnessing the death of patients and most often those patients were as young or even younger than they were.\n\n== By race/ethnicity ==\n'''African Americans''' continue to experience the most severe burden of HIV, compared with other races and ethnicities. Black people represent approximately 13% of the U.S. population, but accounted for an estimated 43% of new HIV infections in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/hiv/group/racialethnic/africanamericans/index.html|title=HIV and African Americans {{!}} Race/Ethnicity {{!}} HIV by Group {{!}} HIV/AIDS {{!}} CDC|date=2019-03-19|website=www.cdc.gov|language=en-us|access-date=2019-07-10}}</ref> Furthermore, they make up nearly 52% of AIDS-related deaths in America. While the overall rates of HIV incidences and prevalence have decreased, they have increased in one particular demographic: African American gay and bisexual men (a 4% increase). In America, black households were reported to have the lowest median income, leading to lower rates of individuals with health insurance. This creates cost barriers to antiretroviral treatments. The racial disparities between women afflicted with HIV/AIDS have been made clear in a 2010 study as well, which showed that 64% of women infected with HIV that year were Black women.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Steiner|first=Riley J.|last2=Finocchario-Kessler|first2=Sarah|last3=Dariotis|first3=Jacinda K.|date=2013|title=Engaging HIV Care Providers in Conversations With Their Reproductive-Age Patients About Fertility Desires and Intentions: A Historical Review of the HIV Epidemic in the United States|journal=American Journal of Public Health|volume=103|issue=8|pages=1357\u20131366|doi=10.2105/ajph.2013.301265|pmid=23763424|pmc=4007857|issn=0090-0036}}</ref> This unequal distribution has led researchers to studying the long-term effects of racial and gender discrimination along with HIV-related stigma, and how this plays a role in people's lives.\n\n'''Hispanics/Latinos''' are also disproportionately affected by HIV. Hispanics/Latinos represented 16% of the population but accounted for 21% of new HIV infections in 2010. This disparity is even more apparent among Latina women, which represent 13% of the population but account for 20% of reported HIV cases among women in the United States.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Peragallo|date=2005|title=A Randomized Clinical Trial of an HIV-Risk-Reduction Intervention Among Low-Income Latino Women|journal=Nursing Research|volume=54|issue=4|pages=264|doi=10.1097/00006199-200507000-00008|issn=0029-6562}}</ref> Hispanics/Latinos accounted for 20% of people living with HIV infection in 2011. Disparities persist in the estimated rate of new HIV infections in Hispanics/Latinos. In 2010, the rate of new HIV infections for Latino males was 2.9 times that for white males, and the rate of new infections for Latinas was 4.2 times that for white females. Since the epidemic began, more than 100,888 Hispanics/Latinos with an AIDS diagnosis have died, including 2,863 in 2016.<ref name=\"cdchisplats\">{{cite web |title=HIV and Hispanics/Latinos |url=https://www.cdc.gov/hiv/group/racialethnic/hispaniclatinos/index.html |website=CDC.gov |publisher=Centre for Disease Control and Prevention |accessdate=Apr 6, 2020|date=2018-08-21}}</ref>\n\n'''American Indian/Alaskan Native''' Communities in the United States also see a higher rate of HIV/AIDS in comparison to whites, Asians, and Native Hawaiians/other Native Pacific Islanders. Although AI/AN sufferers of HIV/AIDS only represent roughly 1% of all sufferers in the U.S.,<ref name=\"CDCAIAN\">{{cite web |title=HIV and American Indians and Alaska Natives |url=https://www.cdc.gov/hiv/group/racialethnic/aian/index.html |website=CDC.gov |publisher=Centre for Disease Control and Prevention |accessdate=December 4, 2018|date=2018-08-21}}</ref> the number of diagnoses amongst AI/AN gay and bisexual men rose by 54% between 2011 and 2015. Additionally, the survival rate of diagnosed AI/AN was the lowest of all races in the United States between 1998 and 2005.<ref>{{cite web |title=A Briefing on HIV/AIDS in Indian Country - Fall 2017 |url=https://www.nihb.org/docs/10022017/NIHB%20HIV%20BRIEFING_NTHC_FINAL.pdf |website=nihb.org |publisher=National Indian Health Board |accessdate=December 4, 2018}}</ref> In recent years, the Centres for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) have put in place a \"high impact prevention approach\"<ref>{{cite web |title=HIV among American Indians and Alaska Natives in the United States |url=https://www.cdc.gov/hiv/group/racialethnic/aian/index.html |website=cdc.org |accessdate=December 4, 2018|date=2018-08-21}}</ref> in partnership with the Indian Health Service and the CDC Tribal Advisory Committee to tackle the growing rates in a culturally appropriate way.\nThe higher rate of HIV/AIDS cases amongst AI/AN people have been attributed to a number of factors including socioeconomic disadvantages faced by AI/AN communities, which may result in difficulty accessing healthcare and high-quality housing. It may be more difficult for gay and bisexual AI/AN men to access healthcare due to living in rural communities, or due to stigma attached to their sexualities. AI/AN people have also been reported to have higher rates of other STIs, including chlamydia and gonorrhea, which also increases likeliness of contracting or transmitting HIV.<ref>{{cite web |title=HIV in American Indians and Alaska Natives in the United States |url=https://www.cdc.gov/hiv/group/racialethnic/aian/index.html |website=cdc.org |publisher=Centre for Disease Control and Prevention |accessdate=December 4, 2018|date=2018-08-21}}</ref> Furthermore, as there are over 560 federally recognised AI/AN tribes, there is some difficulty in creating outreach programmes which effectively appeal to all tribes whilst remaining culturally appropriate. As well as fear of stigma from within AI/AN communities, there may also be a fear amongst LGBTQ+ AI/AN of a lack of understanding from health professionals in the United States, particularly amongst [[Two Spirit]] people. A 2013 NASTAD report calls for the inclusion of LGBT and Two Spirit AI/AN in HIV/AID program planning and asserts that \"health departments should utilize local experts to better understand regional definitions of \"Two Spirit\" and incorporate modules on Native gay men and Two Spirit people into cultural sensitivity courses for public health service providers\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Issue Brief: Native Gay Men and Two Spirit People |url=https://www.nastad.org/sites/default/files/resources/docs/Issue-Brief-Two-Spirit-Final-03-14-13.pdf |website=nastad.org |publisher=National Alliance of State and Territorial AIDS Directors |accessdate=December 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== \"Down-Low\" culture amongst Black MSM ===\n{{Main|Down-low (sexual slang)}}\n\nDown-low is an [[African American slang]] term<ref name=\"Cassell's Dic\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5GpLcC4a5fAC&pg=PA414|title=Cassell's Dictionary of Slang|last=Green|first=Jonathon|date=2006 |page= 893 |publisher=Sterling Publishing|isbn=978-0-304-36636-1|location=|quote=down low n. [1990s+] (US Black) a state of secrecy. down low adj. [1990s+] (US Black) covert, secret (i.e. keeping a low profile)}}</ref> that typically refers to a subculture of Black men who usually identify as heterosexual, but [[Men who have sex with men|who have sex with men]]; some avoid sharing this information even if they have female sexual partner(s) married or single.<ref name=\"Coming Up from the Down Low\">{{cite web|last=King |first=J.L. |first2=Courtney |last2=Carreras |title=Coming Up from the Down Low: The Journey to Acceptance, Healing and Honest Love |page=36 |publisher=Three Rivers Press |date=April 25, 2006 |url=http://www.enotalone.com/article/4411.html |accessdate=2009-12-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100818015102/http://www.enotalone.com/article/4411.html |archivedate=August 18, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"Secret Gay\">{{cite news| last =  Johnson| first =  Jason|title=Secret gay encounters of black men could be raising women's infection rate| newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle| date=May 1, 2005| url =  http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?file=/c/a/2005/05/01/MNG4TCID0F1.DTL&type=health |accessdate=2009-12-18}}</ref><ref name=\"Black masculinities\">{{cite book| last =  Mutua| first =  Athena|title=Progressive Black Masculinities| publisher=Routledge| page = 169| isbn = 978-0-415-97687-9 |date=September 28, 2006| url =  https://books.google.com/books?id=GAzEzR3dap4C&pg=PT197&lpg=PT197&q=%22down%20low%22%2C%20adapted%20by%20a%20subculture%20of%20black%20men| accessdate = 2009-12-18}}</ref><ref name=\"Outing Hip-Hop\">{{cite magazine| last=Bennett| first =  Jessica| title = Outing Hip-Hop| magazine = Newsweek| date=May 19, 2008| url =  http://www.newsweek.com/id/137380/page/1| accessdate=2009-12-19}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a study published in the [[Journal of Bisexuality]], \"[t]he Down Low is a lifestyle predominately practiced by young, urban Black men who have sex with other men and women, yet do not identify as gay or bisexual\".<ref name=\"Attitudes Towards\">{{cite journal |last=Heath |first=Jessie |first2=Kathy |last2=Goggin |title=Attitudes Towards Male Homosexuality, Bisexuality, and the Down Low Lifestyle: Demographic Differences and HIV Implications |journal=Journal of Bisexuality |doi=10.1080/15299710802659997 |volume=9 |issue=1 |pages=17\u201331 |date=January 2009 }}</ref>\n\nIn this context, \"being on the Down Low\" is more than just men having sex with men in secret, or a variant of [[closeted]] homosexuality or bisexuality\u2014it is a sexual identity that is, at least partly, defined by its \"cult of masculinity\" and its rejection of what is perceived as [[white people|White]] culture (including white [[LGBT]] culture) and terms.<ref name=\"Secret Gay\" /><ref name=\"Double Lives\">{{cite news |last= Denizet-Lewis |first= Benoit |title=Double Lives On The Down Low |newspaper=The New York Times |date=August 3, 2003 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/08/03/magazine/double-lives-on-the-down-low.html |accessdate=2012-04-26}}</ref><ref name=\"Down-Low Debate\">{{cite news |last=Wright |first=Kaimeans |title=The Great Down-Low Debate: A New Black Sexual Identity May Be an Incubator for AIDS |newspaper=The Village Voice |date=June 5, 2001 |url=http://www.villagevoice.com/2001-06-05/news/the-great-down-low-debate/1 |accessdate=2008-03-19}}</ref><ref name=\"Sex, lies\">{{cite news |title=Sex, lies and the \"down low\" |work=Salon.com |date=August 16, 2004 |url=http://www.salon.com/mwt/feature/2004/08/16/down_low/index.html |archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20080307114914/http://dir.salon.com/story/mwt/feature/2004/08/16/down_low/index.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=March 7, 2008 |accessdate=2009-12-18}}</ref> A 2003 ''[[New York Times Magazine]]'' cover story on the Down Low phenomenon explains that the Black community sees ''\"homosexuality as a White man's perversion.\"''<ref name=\"Double Lives\" />\n\nThe [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]] cited three findings that relate to African-American men who operate on the down-low (engage in MSM activity but don't disclose to others):\n* African American men who have sex with men (MSM), but who do not disclose their sexual orientation (nondisclosers), have a high prevalence of HIV infection (14%); nearly three times higher than nondisclosing MSMs of other races/ethnicities (5%).\n* Confirming previous research, the study of 5,589 MSM, aged 15\u201329 years, in six U.S. cities found that African American MSM were more likely not to disclose their sexual orientation compared with White MSM (18% vs. 8%).\n* HIV-infected nondisclosers were less likely to know their HIV status (98% were unaware of their infection compared with 75% of HIV-positive disclosers), and more likely to have had recent female sex partners.<ref name=\"MMWR\">{{cite web |title=CDC: Morbidity and Mortality Weekly Report |publisher=CDC: US Center for Disease Control and Prevention |date=February 7, 2003 |url=https://www.cdc.gov/media/mmwrnews/n030207.htm#mmwr1 |accessdate=2009-10-31 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091005104759/http://cdc.gov/media/mmwrnews/n030207.htm#mmwr1 |archive-date=October 5, 2009 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Risk Factors contributing to the Black HIV rate ===\n{{Original research section|date=May 2018}}\n{{citation needed section|date=October 2019}}\n\nAccessibility to healthcare is very important in preventing and treating HIV/AIDS. It can be affected by health insurance which is available to people through private insurers, [[Medicare (United States)|Medicare]] and [[Medicaid]] which leaves some people still vulnerable. Historically, African Americans have faced discrimination when it comes to receiving healthcare.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Armstrong|first=Katrina|last2=Putt|first2=Mary|last3=Halbert|first3=Chanita H.|last4=Grande|first4=David|last5=Schwartz|first5=Jerome Sanford|last6=Liao|first6=Kaijun|last7=Marcus|first7=Noora|last8=Demeter|first8=Mirar B.|last9=Shea|first9=Judy A.|date=February 2013|title=Prior Experiences of Racial Discrimination and Racial Differences in Health Care System Distrust|journal=Medical Care|volume=51|issue=2|pages=144\u2013150|doi=10.1097/mlr.0b013e31827310a1|pmid=23222499|pmc=3552105|issn=0025-7079}}</ref> During the time of slavery, slave owners would get medical attention for slaves because they were deemed as property, while slaves that the slave owners believed were not able to recover were sent to be experimented on. In the late eighteenth century and early nineteenth century, universities dug up African American bodies to autopsy, and some night doctors would snatch people off the streets to examine. African Americans have been experimented on and exploited for centuries. The Tuskegee Syphilis study experimented vulnerable men in the South who had syphilis. They kept treatment from these men to see what would happen. [[Henrietta Lacks]] was also exploited when researchers took her cancerous cells and grew them to experiment on them.<ref>{{cite book|title=Black Man in a White Coat|last=Tweedy|first=Damon|publisher=Picador|year=2015|isbn=|location=New York|pages=153\u2013178}}</ref>\n\nHomosexuality is viewed negatively in the African American Community. \"In a qualitative study of 745 racially and ethnic diverse undergraduates attending a large Midwestern university, Calzo and Ward (2009) determined that parents of African-American participants discussed homosexuality more frequently than the parents of other respondents. In analyses of the values communicated, Calzo and Ward (2009) reported that Black parents offered greater indication that homosexuality is perverse and unnatural\".<ref name=\"Hill 2013 475\u2013487\">{{cite journal|last=Hill|first=William Allen|last2=McNeely|first2=Clea|date=2013|title=HIV/AIDS Disparity between African-American and Caucasian Men Who Have Sex with Men: Intervention Strategies for the Black Church|jstor=24484999|journal=Journal of Religion and Health|volume=52|issue=2|pages=475\u2013487|doi=10.1007/s10943-011-9496-2|pmid=21538178}}</ref>\n\nHomosexuality is seen as a threat to the African American empowerment.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Not In My Family|last=Robertson|first=Gil|publisher=Agate|year=2006|isbn=978-1-932841-24-4|location=Canada|pages=80\u201382}}</ref> Masculinity is seen as important for the African American community because it shows that the community is in control of their own destiny. Since the stigma circling homosexuality is that it is \"effeminate\", then homosexuality is seen as a threat to masculinity. \"Black manhood, then, depends on men's ability to be provider, progenitor, and protector. But, as the Black male performance of parts of this script is thwarted by economic and cultural factors, the performance of Black masculinity becomes predicated on a particular performance of Black sexuality and avoidance of weakness and femininity. If sexuality remains one of the few ways that Black men can recapture a masculinity withheld from them in the marketplace, endorsing Black homosexuality subverts the cultural project of reinscribing masculinity within the Black community.\" This critical view is influenced by Internalized homophobia. \"Internalized homophobia is defined as the lesbian, gay, or bisexual individual's inward direction of society's homophobic attitudes (Meyer 1995).\"<ref name=\"Hill 2013 475\u2013487\" />\n\nThe African American community's social norms regarding homosexuality have influenced a higher percentage of African Americans with internalized homophobia. This homophobic culture is sustained within the African American community through the church because religion is a vital part of the African American community: \"As reported by Peterson and Jones (2009), AA MSM tended to be more involved with religious communities than NHW MSM.\" Because the church reiterates this stigma of homosexuality, the African American community has higher rates of internalized homophobia. This internalized homophobia causes a lower chance of HIV/AIDS education on prevention and care within the African American community.<ref name=\"Hill 2013 475\u2013487\" />\n\nSex education varies throughout the United States and in some areas could use more informative measures. African-Americans and Hispanic/ Latinos experience higher rates of lower socioeconomic statuses and fewer opportunities than white people. This causes limited access to (higher) education in lower socioeconomic areas. Sex education on HIV prevention has decreased from 64% (2000) to 41% (2014). Out of the 50 states, 26 put a larger emphasis on abstinence sex education. Abstinence only sex education is correlated to increasing rates of HIV especially in teenagers and young adults.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.avert.org/professionals/hiv-around-world/western-central-europe-north-america/usa|title=HIV and AIDS in the United States of America (USA)|date=2015-07-21|work=AVERT|access-date=2018-05-11|language=en}}</ref>\n\nWith mass incarceration of the African American community, HIV has been [[infectious diseases within American prisons|spreading rapidly throughout jails and prisons]]. \"Among jail populations, African American men are 5 times as likely as white men, and twice as likely as Hispanic/Latino men, to be diagnosed with HIV.\" Since most people contract HIV before being incarcerated, it is hard to know who has the disease and to keep it from spreading. A lack of hygiene in prisons perpetuates these problems. Many inmates do not disclose their high-risk behaviors, such as anal sex or injection drug use, because they fear being stigmatized and ostracized by other inmates. There is also a lack of educational programs on disease prevention for inmates. Because \"nine out of ten jail inmates are released in under 72 hours which makes it hard to test them for HIV and help them find treatment,\" the problem persists outside of prison.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thebodypro.com/article/hiv-in-correctional-settings|title=HIV Among Incarcerated Populations in the United States|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Activism and response ==\nStarting in the early 1980s, AIDS activist groups and organizations began to emerge and advocate for people infected with HIV in the United States. Though it was an important aspect of the movement, activism went beyond the pursuit of funding for AIDS research. Groups acted to educate and raise awareness of the disease and its effects on different populations, even those thought to be at low-risk of contracting HIV. This was done through publications and \"alternative media\" created by those living with or close to the disease.<ref>{{Cite book|title=AIDS TV: Identity, Community, and Alternative Video|last=Juhasz|first=Alexandra|publisher=Duke University Press|year=1995|isbn=978-0-8223-1695-4|location=Durham, North Carolina|pages=}}</ref>\n\nIn contrast to this \"alternative media\" created by activist groups, mass media reports on AIDS were not as prevalent, most likely due to the stigma surrounding the topic. The general public was therefore not exposed to information regarding the disease. In addition, the federal government and laws in place essentially prevented individuals afflicted with AIDS from getting sufficient information about the disease. Risk reduction education was not easily accessible, so activist groups took action in releasing information to the public through these publications.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=HEREK|first=GREGORY M.|date=1999|title=AIDS and Stigma|journal=American Behavioral Scientist|language=en-US|volume=42|issue=7|pages=1106\u20131116|doi=10.1177/0002764299042007004|issn=0002-7642|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/2627cf2069a85bbd3ec607ae91cb6fd4d6c6b859}}</ref>\n\nActivist groups worked to prevent spread of HIV by distributing information about safe sex. They also existed to support people living with HIV/AIDS, offering therapy, support groups, and hospice care.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite book|title=Reproductive Justice: An Introduction|last=Ross|first=Loretta|publisher=University of California Press|year=2017|isbn=978-0-520-28820-1|location=Oakland, California|pages=}}</ref> Organizations like [[Gay Men's Health Crisis]], the Lesbian AIDS Project, and SisterLove were created to address the needs of certain populations living with HIV/AIDS. Other groups, like the [[NAMES Project AIDS Memorial Quilt|NAMES Project]], emerged as a way of memorializing those who had passed, refusing to let them be forgotten by the historical narrative. One group, the Association for Drug Abuse Prevention and Treatment (ADAPT), headed by [[Yolanda Serrano]], coordinated with their local prison, [[Rikers Island Correctional Facility|Riker's Island Correctional Facility]], to advocate for those imprisoned and AIDS positive to be released early, so that they could pass away in the comfort of their own homes.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=U-UCAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA35&lpg=PA35&dq=yolanda+serrano+and+adapt#v=onepage&q=yolanda%20serrano%20and%20adapt&f=false|title=ADAPT and Survive|last=Carter|first=Zoe|date=1988-05-09|magazine=New York Magazine|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref>\n\nBoth men and women, heterosexual and queer populations were active in establishing and maintaining these parts of the movement. Because AIDS was initially thought only to impact gay men, most narratives of activism focus on their contributions to the movement. However, women also played a significant role in raising awareness, rallying for change, and caring for those impacted by the disease. Lesbians helped organize and spread information about transmission between women, as well as supporting gay men in their work. Narratives of activism also tend to focus on organizing done in coastal cities, but AIDS activism was present and widespread across both urban and more rural areas of the United States. Organizers sought to address needs specific to their communities, whether that was working to establish [[Needle exchange programme|needle exchange programs]], fighting against housing or employment discrimination, or issues faced primarily by people identified as members of specific groups (such as sex workers, mothers and children, or incarcerated people).\n\nInitially when the AIDS epidemic surfaced in the United States, a large proportion of patients were LGBT community members, leading to stigmatization of the disease. Because of this, the AIDS activist groups took initiative in testing and experimenting with new possible medications for treating HIV, after researchers outside of the community refused. This research originally done by early activist groups contributed to treatments still being used today.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Street science : community knowledge and environmental health justice|last=Corburn, Jason.|date=2005|publisher=MIT Press|isbn=0-262-03333-X|oclc=58830060}}</ref>\n\n=== Present day activism ===\nAn effective response to HIV/AIDS requires that groups of vulnerable populations have access to HIV prevention programs with information and services that are specific to them.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.avert.org/professionals/hiv-social-issues/key-affected-populations|title=Key Affected Populations, HIV and AIDS|last=|first=|date=2015-07-24|website=Avert: Global Information and Education on HIV and AIDS|access-date=}}</ref> In the present day, some activist groups and AIDS organizations that were established during the height of the epidemic are still present and working to assist people living with AIDS.<ref name=\":0\" /> They may offer any combination of the following: health education, counseling and support, or advocacy for law and policy. AIDS organizations also continue to call for public awareness and support through participation in events like pride parades, [[World AIDS Day]], or [[AIDS Walk|AIDS walks]]. Newer activism has appeared in advocacy for [[Pre-Exposure Prophylaxis]] (PrEP), which has shown to significantly limit transmission of HIV. While PrEP appears to be extremely successful in suppressing the spread of HIV infection, there is some evidence that the reduction in HIV risk has led to some people taking more sexual risks, specifically, reduced use of condoms in anal sex.<ref>Holt M, Lea T, Mao L, Kolstee J, Zablotska I, Duck T, Allan B, West M, Lee E, Hull P, Grulich A, De Wit J, Prestage G (August 2018). \"Community-level changes in condom use and uptake of HIV pre-exposure prophylaxis by gay and bisexual men in Melbourne and Sydney, Australia: results of repeated behavioural surveillance in 2013-17\". The Lancet. HIV. 5 (8): e448\u2013e456. doi:10.1016/s2352-3018(18)30072-9. {{PMID|29885813}}.</ref>\n\n== Current status ==\n\nThe CDC estimates at the end of 2017, there were 1,018,346 adults and adolescents with diagnosed HIV in the US and dependent areas.<ref name=\"cdcataglance\">{{cite web |title=Statistics Overview |website=CDC |accessdate=Apr 6, 2020 |url=https://www.cdc.gov/hiv/statistics/overview/index.html}}</ref> {{As of|2016|lc=y||df=}}, the CDC estimated about 14% of infections had not been diagnosed.<ref name=\"cdcataglance\" /> Since 2010, the number of people living with HIV has increased, while the annual number of new HIV infections has declined to 37,832 diagnosed in 2018.<ref name=\"cdcataglance\" /><ref name=\"CDCBasicStats\" /> Within the overall estimates, however, some groups are affected more than others. 70% of 2018 diagnoses were among men who have sex with men, 7% were among injection drug users, and new infections disproportionately occurred among heterosexual women and African Americans.<ref name=\"cdcataglance\" /><ref name=\"CDCBasicStats\" />\n\nAn estimated 15,807 people with an AIDS diagnosis died in 2016,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/hiv/library/reports/hiv-surveillance.html|title=Diagnoses of HIV Infection in the United States and Dependent Areas, 2016|date=November 2017|work=HIV Surveillance Report, 2016|publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]]|accessdate=April 26, 2018}}</ref> and approximately 658,507 people in the United States with an AIDS diagnosis have died overall. The deaths of persons with an AIDS diagnosis can be due to any cause\u2014that is, the death may or may not be related to AIDS.\n\nThe most recent CDC HIV Surveillance Report estimates that 38,281 new cases of HIV were diagnosed in the United States in 2017, a rate of 11.8 per 100,000 population.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/hiv/library/reports/hiv-surveillance.html|title=HIV Surveillance {{!}} Reports{{!}} Resource Library {{!}} HIV/AIDS {{!}} CDC|date=2019-11-07|website=www.cdc.gov|language=en-us|accessdate=2019-11-21}}</ref> This rate is a decrease from the previous year's estimates, which indicated 39,589 new infections and a rate of 12.2 per 100,000 population.<ref name=\":1\" /> Individuals in the age range 25\u201329 years-old had the highest rates of new infection, with a rate of 32.9 per 100,000.<ref name=\":1\" /> With regard to race and ethnicity, the highest rates of new infections in 2017 occurred in the Black/African-American population, with a new infection rate of 41.1 per 100,000. This more than doubled the next highest rate for a racial or ethnic group, which was Hispanic/Latino with a rate of 16.6 per 100,000.<ref name=\":1\" /> The lowest rates of new infection in 2017 occurred in the White population and Asian population, which each had a new infection rate of 5.1 per 100,000.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nAccording to CDC estimates, the most common transmission category of new infections remained male-to-male sexual contact, which accounted for roughly 66.6% of all new infections in the United States in 2017.<ref name=\":1\" /> With regard to region of residence, the highest rates of new infections in 2017 occurred in the United States South, with 19,968 total new infections and 16.1 infections per 100,000.<ref name=\":1\" /> The region identified as 'South' includes Alabama, Arkansas, Delaware, District of Columbia, Florida, Georgia, Kentucky, Louisiana, Maryland, Mississippi, North Carolina, Oklahoma, South Carolina, Tennessee, Texas, Virginia, and West Virginia.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn the United States, men who have sex with men (MSM), described as gay and bisexual,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/hiv/group/msm/|title=Gay and Bisexual Men \u2013 HIV by Group|date=February 27, 2018|website=www.cdc.gov}}</ref> make up about 55% of the total HIV-positive population, and 67% of new HIV cases and 83% of the estimated new HIV diagnoses among ''all'' males aged 13 and older, and an estimated 92% of new HIV diagnoses among all men in their age group (2014 report). 1 in 6 gay and bisexual men are therefore expected to be diagnosed with HIV in their lifetime if current rates continue. Gay and bisexual men accounted for an estimated 54% of people diagnosed with AIDS, with 39% being African American, 32% being white, and 24% being Hispanic/Latino.<ref>{{cite web|title=HIV Among Gay and Bisexual Men|url=https://www.cdc.gov/hiv/pdf/group/msm/cdc-hiv-msm.pdf|accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> The CDC estimates that more than 600,000 gay and bisexual men are currently living with HIV in the United States.<ref>https://www.cdc.gov/hiv/pdf/group/msm/cdc-hiv-msm.pdf</ref> A review of four studies in which trans women in the United States were tested for HIV found that 27.7% tested positive.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Estimating HIV Prevalence and Risk Behaviors of Transgender Persons in the United States: A Systematic Review|pmid=17694429 |doi=10.1007/s10461-007-9299-3 |volume=12|issue=1|date=Jan 2008|journal=AIDS Behav|pages=1\u201317|last1=Herbst |first1=J. H |last2=Jacobs |first2=E. D |last3=Finlayson |first3=T. J |last4=McKleroy |first4=V. S |last5=Neumann |first5=M. S |last6=Crepaz |first6=N |author7=HIV/AIDS Prevention Research Synthesis Team|url=https://hal.archives-ouvertes.fr/hal-02319357/file/Poster%20Olga%20L%20Gonzalez%202019.pdf }}</ref>\n\nIn a 2008 study, the Center for Disease Control found that, of the study participants who were men who had sex with men (\"MSM\"), almost one in five (19%) had HIV and \"among those who were infected, nearly half (44 percent) were unaware of their HIV status.\" The research found that white MSM \"represent a greater number of new HIV infections than any other population, followed closely by black MSM\u2014who are one of the most disproportionately affected subgroups in the U.S.\" and that most new infections among white MSM occurred among those aged 30\u201339 followed closely by those aged 40\u201349, while most new infections among black MSM have occurred among young black MSM (aged 13\u201329).<ref name=\"2010sept_cdc\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/nchhstp/.../docs/FastFacts-MSM-FINAL508COMP.pdf|title=CDC Fact Sheet \u2013 HIV and AIDS among Gay and Bisexual Men \u2013 Sept 2010}}{{Dead link|date=August 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes}}</ref><ref name=\"kaiser_2010gaymale_hiv\">{{cite web |url=http://www.kaiserhealthnews.org/Daily-Reports/2010/September/24/AIDS-gay-men.aspx|title=CDC: One In Five Gay Men HIV-Positive |date=September 24, 2010 |publisher=Kaiser Health News}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, a major HIV outbreak, [[Indiana]]'s largest-ever, occurred in two largely rural, economically depressed and poor counties in the southern portion of the state, due to the injection of a relatively new opioid-type drug called Opana ([[oxymorphone]]), which is designed be taken in pill form but is ground up and injected intravenously using needles. Because of the lack of HIV cases in that area beforehand and the youth of many but not all of those affected, the relative unavailability in the local area of safe needle exchange programs and of treatment centers capable of dealing with long-term health needs, HIV care, and drug addiction during the initial phases of the outbreak, it was not initially adequately contained and dealt with until those were set up by the government, and acute awareness of the issue spread. Such centers have now been opened, and short-term care is beginning to be provided; once the scope of the outbreak became clear, Governor [[Mike Pence]], despite some initial reservations, approved a legislative measure to allow safe, clean needle exchange programs and treatment for those affected, which could end up being instituted statewide.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/2015/04/24/402034996/hiv-outbreak-in-indiana-grows-with-nearly-140-confirmed-cases|title=HIV Outbreak In Indiana Grows With Nearly 140 Confirmed Cases|last1=Block |first1=Melissa |last2=Adams|first2=Jerome |date=April 24, 2015|publisher=NPR|accessdate=May 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Criminal transmission of HIV in the United States]]\n* [[Adult Industry Medical Health Care Foundation]]\n* [[AIDS Education and Training Centers (AETCs)]]\n* [[People With AIDS]] Self-Empowerment Movement\n* [[HIV/AIDS in New York City]]\n* [[Hank M. Tavera]]\n* [[President's Emergency Plan for AIDS Relief]] (international)\n* [[:Category:HIV/AIDS activism|HIV/AIDS activism]]\n* [[:Category:HIV/AIDS activists|HIV/AIDS activists]]\n\n'''International:'''\n* [[AIDS pandemic]]\n* [[HIV/AIDS in North America]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n# {{cite book | last = Cante | first = Richard C. | title = Gay Men and the Forms of Contemporary US Culture | publisher = Ashgate Publishing |isbn=978-0-7546-7230-2 |date=March 2008 | location = London}}\n# {{cite journal\n| last = Bogart |first = Laura | last2 = Thorburn |first2 = Sheryl\n| title = Are HIV/AIDS conspiracy beliefs a barrier to HIV prevention among African Americans?\n| journal = J. Acquir. Immune Defic. Syndr.\n| volume = 38 | issue = 2 | pages = 213\u20138 |date=February 2005 | pmid = 15671808\n| doi=10.1097/00126334-200502010-00014}}\n# {{Cite book\n  | last = Walker\n  | first = Robert Searles\n  | title = AIDS: Today, Tomorrow : an Introduction to the HIV Epidemic in America\n  | publisher = Humanities Press Intl |edition= 2nd | year = 1994\n  | location = Atlantic Highlands, New Jersey\n  | isbn = 978-0-391-03859-2 |oclc=30399464}}\n# {{Cite book\n  | last = Siplon | first = Patricia\n  | title = AIDS and the policy struggle in the United States\n  | publisher = Georgetown University Press | year = 2002\n  | location = Washington D.C.\n  | isbn = 978-0-87840-378-3 |oclc= 48964730}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.aids.gov/ AIDS.gov \u2013 The U.S. Federal Domestic HIV/AIDS Resource]\n* [http://www.aidsvu.org/ AIDSVu.org \u2013 Interactive Map Illustrating HIV Prevalence in the United States]\n* [https://asteria.fivecolleges.edu/findaids/sophiasmith/mnsss291.html Finding Aid \u2013 Voices of Feminism Oral History Project, 1990\u20132006]\n\n{{North America topic|HIV/AIDS in}}\n{{LGBT in the United States}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hiv Aids In The United States}}\n[[Category:1960 establishments in the United States]]\n[[Category:HIV/AIDS in the United States| ]]\n[[Category:LGBT history in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "}}<br />{{Sidebar\n| name = Centers for Disease Control Infographics\n| title = CDC Infographics\n| content1 = [[File:Hiv-us-map-2017.png|thumb|300px|Rates of HIV Diagnoses in the US, 2017]]\n| content2 = [[File:New-HIV-Infections-by-Race-and-Transmission-Group.png|thumb|300px|New HIV Infections by Race and Transmission Group]]\n| content3 = [[File:Cdc-hiv-us-at-a-glance.png|thumb|300px|HIV Diagnosis Trends in the U.S. and Dependent Areas, 2012\u20132016]]\n|content4 = [[File:HIV cases by transmission category CDC 2007.svg|thumb|300px|The estimated number of U.S. HIV/AIDS Cases, in 2007 by transmission category<ref name=\"CDCBasicStats\">{{Cite web\n |title=HIV/AIDS Basic Statistics\n |publisher=US Centers for Disease Control\n |date=December 18, 2017\n |url=https://www.cdc.gov/hiv/topics/surveillance/basic.htm\n |accessdate=April 26, 2018}}</ref>]]\n}}\nThe [[AIDS]] epidemic, caused by [[HIV]] (Human Immunodeficiency Virus), found its way to the [[United States]] as early as 1960, but was first noticed after doctors discovered clusters of [[Kaposi's sarcoma]] and [[pneumocystis pneumonia]] in gay men in [[Los Angeles]], [[New York City]], and [[San Francisco]] in 1981. Treatment of HIV/AIDS is primarily via a \"drug cocktail\" of [[antiretroviral drugs]], and education programs to help people avoid infection.\n\nInitially, infected foreign nationals were turned back at the U.S. border to help prevent additional infections. The number of U.S. deaths from AIDS have declined sharply since the early years of the disease's presentation domestically. In the United States in 2016, 1.1 million people aged over 13 lived with an HIV infection, of whom 14% were unaware of their infection.<ref name=\"CDCBasicStats\" /> [[Homosexuality|Gay]] and [[Bisexuality|bisexual]] men, [[African Americans]], and [[Latinos]] remain disproportionately affected by HIV/AIDS in the U.S.\n\n== Mortality and morbidity ==\n\n{{As of|2016}}, about 675,000 people have died of HIV/AIDS in the U.S. since the beginning of the HIV epidemic, and even today, nearly 13,000 people with AIDS in the United States die each year.<ref name=CDC2016Today>{{cite web|title=Today's HIV/AIDS Epidemic Factsheet|url=https://www.cdc.gov/nchhstp/newsroom/docs/factsheets/todaysepidemic-508.pdf|website=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|publisher=U.S. government|accessdate=December 31, 2016}}</ref>\n\nWith improved treatments and better [[Post-exposure prophylaxis|prophylaxis]] against opportunistic infections, [[mortality rate|death rates]] have quite significantly declined.<ref name=\"SFDPH HIV Epi Report 2008\">{{cite web\n |title        = 2008 HIV/AIDS Epidemiology Annual Report\n |publisher    = San Francisco Department of Public Health\n |date         = July 9, 2009\n |url          = http://sfhiv.org/documents/AnnualReport2008.pdf\n |accessdate   = March 21, 2010\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110724191441/http://sfhiv.org/documents/AnnualReport2008.pdf\n |archive-date = July 24, 2011\n |url-status   = dead\n |df           = mdy-all\n}}</ref>\n\nThe overall death rate among persons diagnosed with HIV/AIDS in New York City decreased by sixty-two percent from 2001 to 2012.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www1.nyc.gov/assets/doh/downloads/pdf/dires/2013-hiv-surveillance-annual-report.pdf|title=HIV Surveillance Annual Report, 2013|last=|first=|publisher=New York City Department of Health and Mental Hygiene|year=2013|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n== Containment ==\nAfter the HIV/AIDS outbreak in the 1980s, various responses emerged in an effort to alleviate the issue. These included new medical treatments, travel restrictions, and new public health policies in the United States.\n\n=== Medical treatment ===\n[[File:AIDS Deaths-US 1987-1997.png|thumb|300px|A chart of AIDS deaths in the United States from 1987 to 1997.]]\n[[File:AIDS Deaths-US 1998-2002.png|thumb|300px|A chart of AIDS deaths in the United States from 1998 to 2002.]]\nGreat progress was made in the U.S. following the introduction of three-drug anti-HIV treatments (\"cocktails\") that included [[Management of HIV/AIDS|antiretroviral drugs]]. [[David Ho (scientist)|David Ho]], a pioneer of this approach, was honored as ''[[Time Magazine]]'' Man of the Year for 1996. Deaths were rapidly reduced by more than half, with a small but welcome reduction in the yearly rate of new HIV infections. Since this time, AIDS deaths have continued to decline, but much more slowly, and not as completely in black Americans as in other population segments.<ref name=\"Left Behind Black America\">{{Cite web|last=Wilson |first=Phill |last2=Wright |first2=Kai |last3=Isbell |first3=Michael T. |title=Left Behind: Black America: a Neglected Priority in the Global AIDS Epidemic |publisher=Black AIDS Institute |date=August 2008 |url=http://www.blackaids.org/image_uploads/article_575/08_left_behind.pdf |accessdate=March 20, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100821072159/http://www.blackaids.org/image_uploads/article_575/08_left_behind.pdf |archivedate=August 21, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"NYC DPH AIDS Mortality Historic Low 2002\">{{Cite press release\n |title        = Deaths in New York City Reached Historic Low in 2002\n |publisher    = New York City Department of Health and Mental Hygiene\n |date         = January 30, 2004\n |url          = http://www.nyc.gov/html/doh/html/press_archive04/pr005-0130.shtml\n |accessdate   = March 20, 2010\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20100604072407/http://www.nyc.gov/html/doh/html/press_archive04/pr005-0130.shtml\n |archive-date = 2010-06-04\n |url-status   = dead\n}}</ref>\n\n=== Travel restrictions ===\nIn 1987 the [[Department of Health and Human Services]] (HHS) included HIV in its list of \u201ccommunicable diseases of public health significance\u201d; denying immigrants and short term foreign visits from anyone who tested positive for the virus. <ref name=\"hivexclusion\">{{cite web |title=Federal Register Volume 52, Issue 167 (August 28, 1987) |url=https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/USCODE-2018-title8/html/USCODE-2018-title8-chap12-subchapII-partII-sec1182.htm |website=govinfo.gov |publisher=Office of the Federal Register |accessdate=6 April 2020 |pages=32540-32544}}</ref> <ref name=\"usc8\">{{cite web |title=United States Code: Immigration and Nationality |url=http://cdn.loc.gov/service/ll/uscode/uscode1988-00200/uscode1988-002008012/uscode1988-002008012.pdf |website=LIbrary of Congress |publisher=Office of the Law Revision Counsel |accessdate=6 April 2020 |page=1246 |date=1988}}</ref> In 1993 the US Congress signed the National Institutes of Health Revitalization Act of 1993: removing the HHS\u2019 authority to dictate HIV as a \u201cpublic health significance\u201d, and explicitly including HIV as a cause for denying immigrants and foreign visitors entry into the US.<ref name=\"byndinad\">{{Cite report|title=Moving Beyond the U.S. Government Policy of Inadmissibility of HIV-Infected Noncitizens (PDF)|date=2007-03-01|url=https://csis-prod.s3.amazonaws.com/s3fs-public/legacy_files/files/media/csis/pubs/movingbeyondinadmissibility.pdf|last=Nieburg|first=Phillip|last2=Morrison|first2=J. Stephen|pages=7{{hyphen}}19|format=PDF}}</ref><ref>{{cite act|type= National Institutes of Health Revitalization Act|index=Sec. 2007|date=1993|legislature=103rd Congress|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/103rd-congress/senate-bill/1}}</ref>  For someone seeking US citizenship during the HIV ban, they were required to undergo a medical exam during the legalization process - testing positive would permanently deny them entry into the country.<ref name=\"imm_mexcal\">{{cite journal |last1=Morin |first1=Stephen F |last2=Carrillo |first2=H\u00e9ctor |last3=Steward |first3=Wayne T |last4=Maiorana |first4=Andre |last5=Trautwein |first5=Mark |last6=G\u00f3mez |first6=Cynthia A |title=Policy Perspectives on Public Health For Mexican Migrants in California |journal=JAIDS Journal of Acquired Immune Deficiency Syndromes |date=November 2004 |volume=37 |pages=S252\u2013S259 |doi=10.1097/01.qai.0000141254.61840.05}}</ref> The law extended to medication, where foreign travelers could be arrested for having antiretroviral drugs on their carry-ons. A famous example was in 1989: a Dutch traveler to Minnesota was arrested for \u201cseveral days\u201d because they were carrying [[AZT]] in their luggage.<ref name=\"byndinad\" />\n\nGoing into the 2000s, people who are HIV positive seeking temporary visas or vacationing to the US would have to avoid revealing their status on application forms, and plan for their medication to be sent to the US or stop taking their medication.<ref name=\"mahto2006>{{cite journal |last1=Mahto |first1=M |last2=Ponnusamy |first2=K |last3=Schuhwerk |first3=M |last4=Richens |first4=J |last5=Lambert |first5=N |last6=Wilkins |first6=E |last7=Churchill |first7=DR |last8=Miller |first8=RF |last9=Behrens |first9=RH |title=Knowledge, attitudes and health outcomes in HIV-infected travellers to the USA |journal=HIV Medicine |date=May 2006 |volume=7 |issue=4 |pages=201\u2013204 |doi=10.1111/j.1468-1293.2006.00371.x}}</ref> Eventually the US began offering temporary admission waivers for people who are HIV positive. As stated in an interoffice memorandum in 2004, foreign nationals who are HIV positive could qualify for the waiver by falling into either category: humanitarian/public interest reasons, or \u201cattendees of certain designated international events held in the United States\u201d.<ref name=\"waivers\">{{Cite report|title=Exception to Nonimmigrant HIV Waiver Policy for K and V Nonimmigrants (PDF)|date=2004-11-02|url=https://www.uscis.gov/sites/default/files/USCIS/Laws/Memoranda/Static_Files_Memoranda/Archives%201998-2008/2004/kandv_hiv110204.pdf|last=R. Yates|first=William|publisher=U.S. Citizenship and Immigration Services (USCIS)}}</ref>\n\nIn early December 2006, President [[George W. Bush]] indicated that he would issue an executive order allowing HIV-positive people to enter the [[United States]] on standard visas. It was unclear whether applicants would still have to declare their HIV status.<ref name=\"Russell2006\">{{Cite news\n  | last = Russell | first = Sabin\n  | title = Bush to ease rule limiting HIV-positive foreign visitors\n  | newspaper = San Francisco Chronicle\n  | publisher = Hearst Communications\n  | date = December 2, 2006\n  | url = http://articles.sfgate.com/2006-12-02/news/17323943_1_hiv-positive-world-aids-day-international-aids-conferences\n  | accessdate = March 21, 2010}}</ref> However, the ban remained in effect throughout Bush's Presidency. In August 2007, Congresswoman [[Barbara Lee]] of California introduced {{USBill|110|h|3337}}, the HIV Nondiscrimination in Travel and Immigration Act of 2007. This bill would have allowed travelers and immigrants entry to the United States without having to disclose their HIV status. The bill died at the end of the [[110th United States Congress|110th Congress]].<ref name=\"BBC2009\">{{cite web |title=Activist helps US HIV law change |website=BBC NEWS |date=July 6, 2009 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/8136456.stm |accessdate=April 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2008, then President George W. Bush signed {{USBill|110|h|5501}} that lifted the ban in statutory law. However, the [[United States Department of Health and Human Services]] still held the ban in administrative (written regulation) law. New impetus was added to repeal efforts when Paul Thorn, a UK tuberculosis expert who was invited to speak at the 2009 [[Pacific Health Summit]] in Seattle, was denied a visa due to his HIV positive status. A letter written by Mr. Thorn, and read in his place at the Summit, was obtained by Congressman [[Jim McDermott]], who advocated the issue to the Obama administration's Health Secretary.<ref name=\"BBC2009\" />\n\nOn October 30, 2009 President [[Barack Obama]] reauthorized the [[Ryan White]] HIV/AIDS Bill which expanded care and treatment through federal funding to nearly half a million.<ref name=\"obamawh\">{{cite web\n  | last = Crowley\n  | first = Jeffrey\n  | authorlink = Jeffrey Crowley\n  | title = Honoring the Legacy of Ryan White\n  | work = WhiteHouse.gov\n  | publisher = Office of the President of the United States\n  | date = October 30, 2009\n  | url = http://www.whitehouse.gov/blog/2009/10/30/honoring-legacy-ryan-white\n  | accessdate = March 21, 2010}}</ref> He also announced that the Department of Health and Human Services crafted regulation that would end the HIV Travel and Immigration Ban effective in January 2010;<ref name=\"obamawh\" /> on January 4, 2010, the [[United States Department of Health and Human Services]], [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] removed HIV infection from the list of \"[[communicable diseases]] of public health significance,\" due to it not being spread by casual contact, or by air, food or water, and removed HIV status as a factor to be considered in the granting of [[Visa (document)|travel visas]], disallowing HIV status from among the diseases that could prevent people who are not U.S. citizens from entering the country.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cdc.gov/immigrantrefugeehealth/laws-regs/hiv-ban-removal/final-rule-technical-qa.html |title=Final Rule Removing HIV Infection from U.S. Immigration Screening |accessdate=2017-01-02 |publisher=[[United States Department of State]] |date=2010-01-19}}</ref>\n\n=== Public health policies ===\n[[File:A woman with her hand in her hair and the other pulling up Wellcome L0052386.jpg|thumb|upright|1993 poster for \"America responds to AIDS\" \u2013 a campaign by the Department of Health]]\nSince the beginning of the HIV epidemic, several U.S. presidents have attempted to implement a national plan to control the issue. In 1987, President Reagan created a Presidential Commission on the HIV Epidemic. This commission was recruited to investigate what steps are necessary for responding to the HIV outbreak, and the consensus was to establish more HIV testing, focus on prevention and treatment as well as expanding HIV care throughout the U.S.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Yehia|first=Baligh|last2=Frank|first2=Ian|date=2011|title=Battling AIDS in America: An Evaluation of the National HIV/AIDS Strategy|journal=American Journal of Public Health|volume=101|issue=9|pages=e4\u2013e8|doi=10.2105/ajph.2011.300259|pmid=21778507|pmc=3154226|issn=0090-0036}}</ref> However, these changes were not implemented during this time, and the commission recommendations were largely ignored.\n\nAnother attempt to respond to the HIV outbreak took place in 1996, when President Clinton established the National AIDS Strategy, which aimed to reduce number of infections, enhance research on HIV treatment, increase access to resources for people affected by AIDS, and also alleviate the racial disparities in HIV treatment and care.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Improving outcomes blueprint for a national AIDS plan for the United States.|last=Collins, Chris.|date=2007|publisher=Open Society Institute|oclc=1100047917}}</ref> Similarly to Reagan's plan, the National AIDS Strategy was not successfully enforced, providing only objectives without a specific action plan for implementation.\n\nIn 2010, President Obama created the National HIV/AIDS Strategy for the United States (NHAS), with its three main objectives being to reduce the annual number of infections, reduce health disparities, and increase access to resources and HIV care.<ref name=\":2\" /> However, this new strategy differs in that it includes an Implementation Plan, with a timeline for achieving each of the three goals, as well as a document outlining the specific action plan that will be used.<ref>{{Cite book|title=National HIV/AIDS strategy : federal implementation plan.|last=United States. Office of National AIDS Policy.|date=2010|publisher=White House Office of National AIDS Policy|oclc=656320879}}</ref>\n\nPresident Trump announced a plan in his 2019 [[State of the Union Address]] to stop new HIV infections in the United States by 2030, though critics pointed to the President's policies reducing access to health insurance, anti-immigrant and anti-transgender policies as undermining this goal.<ref>[https://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2019/02/06/691934890/halting-u-s-hiv-epidemic-by-2030-difficult-but-doable Halting U.S. HIV Epidemic By 2030: Difficult But Doable]</ref> The [[Department of Health and Human Services]] issued grants to 32 HIV \"hotspots\" in 2019, and Congress earmarked over $291 million for the president's plan in FY2020.<ref>[https://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2019/12/18/789291340/some-big-health-care-policy-changes-are-hiding-in-the-federal-spending-package Some Big Health Care Policy Changes Are Hiding In The Federal Spending Package]</ref>\n\n== Public perception ==\n[[File:Prevalence of HIV infections in the United States and total AIDS deaths.svg|thumb|400px|The number of people living with HIV in the United States, and the total cumulative number of deaths.]]\n\nOne of the best known works on the history of HIV is the 1987 book ''[[And the Band Played On]]'' by [[Randy Shilts]]. Shilts contends that [[Ronald Reagan]]'s administration dragged its feet in dealing with the crisis due to homophobia, while the gay community viewed early reports and public health measures with corresponding distrust, thus allowing the disease to infect hundreds of thousands more. This resulted in the formation of ACT-UP, the [[AIDS Coalition to Unleash Power]] by [[Larry Kramer]]. Galvanized by the federal government's inactivity, the movement by AIDS activists to gain funding for AIDS research, which on a per-patient basis out-paced funding for more prevalent diseases such as cancer and heart disease, was used as a model for future lobbying for health research funding.<ref>{{cite journal\n|last= Kahn Best\n|first= Rachel\n|title= Disease Politics and Medical Research Funding: Three Ways Advocacy Shapes Policy\n|journal= American Sociological Review\n|volume= 77\n|issue= 5\n|pages= 780\u2013803\n|doi= 10.1177/0003122412458509\n|year= 2012\n|doi-access= free\n}}</ref>\n\nThe Shilts work popularized the [[HIV and AIDS misconceptions|misconception]] that the disease was introduced by a gay [[flight attendant]] named [[Ga\u00ebtan Dugas]], referred to as \"[[Index case|Patient Zero]],\" although the author did not actually make this claim in the book. However, subsequent research has revealed that there were cases of AIDS much earlier than initially known. HIV-infected blood samples have been found from as early as 1959 in Africa ''(see [[HIV]] main entry)'', and HIV has been shown to have caused the death of [[Robert Rayford]], a 16-year-old St. Louis male, in 1969, who could have contracted it as early as 7 years old due to sexual abuse, suggesting that HIV had been present, at very low prevalence, in the U.S. since before the 1970s.\n\nAn early theory asserted that a series of [[inoculation]]s against [[hepatitis B]] that were performed in the gay community of [[San Francisco]] were tainted with HIV. Although there was a high correlation between recipients of that [[vaccination]] and initial cases of AIDS, this theory has long been discredited. HIV, [[hepatitis B]], and [[hepatitis C]] are bloodborne diseases with very similar modes of transmission, and those at risk for one are at risk for the others.<ref name=\"NIOSH Bloodborne\">{{Cite web\n  | title = Bloodborne Infectious Diseases HIV/AIDS, Hepatitis B Virus, and Hepatitis C Virus\n  | publisher = US National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health\n  | date = March 10, 2010\n  | url = https://www.cdc.gov/niosh/topics/bbp/\n  | accessdate = March 21, 2010}}</ref>\n\nActivists and critics of current AIDS policies allege that another preventable impediment to stemming the spread of the disease and/or finding a treatment was the vanity of \"celebrity\" scientists. [[Robert Gallo]], an American scientist involved in the search for a new [[virus]] in the people affected by the disease, became embroiled in a legal battle with French scientist [[Luc Montagnier]], who had first discovered such a virus in tissue cultures derived from a patient suffering from enlargement of the lymphnodes (an early sign of AIDS). Montagnier had named the new virus LAV (Lymphoadenopathy-Associated Virus).\n\nGallo, who appeared to question the primacy of the French scientist's discovery, refused to recognize the \"French virus\" as the cause of AIDS, and tried instead to claim the disease was caused by a new member of a retrovirus family, [[HTLV]], which he had discovered. Critics claim that because some scientists were more interested in trying to win a Nobel prize than in helping patients, research progress was delayed and more people needlessly died. After a number of meetings and high-level political intervention, the French scientists and Gallo agreed to \"share\" the discovery of HIV, although eventually Montagnier and his group were recognized as the true discoverers, and won the 2008 Nobel Prize for it.\n\nPublicity campaigns were started in attempts to counter the incorrect and often vitriolic perception of AIDS as a \"gay plague\". These included the [[Ryan White]] case, red ribbon campaigns, celebrity dinners, the [[And the Band Played On (film)|1993 film version]] of ''And the Band Played On'', [[AIDS education|sex education programs]] in schools, and [[Public service announcement|television advertisements]]. Announcements by various celebrities that they had contracted HIV (including actor [[Rock Hudson]], basketball star [[Magic Johnson]], tennis player [[Arthur Ashe]] and singer [[Freddie Mercury]]) were significant in arousing media attention and making the general public aware of the dangers of the disease to people of all sexual orientations.<ref>Small, Neil. \"Dying in a Public Place: AIDS Deaths.\" ''The Sociological Review'' 40, no. 1_suppl (May 1992): 87\u2013111.</ref>\n\n== Perspective of doctors ==\nAIDS was met with great fear and concern by the nation, much like any other epidemic, and those who were primarily affected were populations that the majority did not think highly of: homosexuals, African-Americans, Latinos, and intravenous drug users. The general thought of the population was to create distance and establish boundaries from these people, and some doctors were not immune from such impulses. During the epidemic, doctors began to not treat AIDS patients, not only to create distance from these groups of people, but also because they were afraid to contract the disease themselves. A surgeon in Milwaukee stated, \"I've got to be selfish. It's an incurable disease that's uniformly fatal, and I'm constantly at risk for getting it. I've got to think about myself. I've got to think about my family. That responsibility is greater than to the patient.\" <ref name=\":02\">{{Cite book|title=Aids Doctors Voices from the Epidemic|last=Bayer|first=Ronald|publisher=Oxford University|year=2000|isbn=0-19-512681-5|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/aidsdoctorsvoice00rona/page/4 4\u20135]|url=https://archive.org/details/aidsdoctorsvoice00rona/page/4}}</ref>\n\nSome doctors thought it was their duty to stay away from the virus because they had other patients to think of. In a survey of doctors in the mid to late 1980s, a substantial number of physicians indicated that they didn't have an ethical obligation to treat and care for those patients with HIV/AIDS.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Link|first=Nathan|date=April 1988|title=Concerns of Medical and Pediatric House Officers about Acquiring AIDS from their Patients|url=|journal=American Journal of Public Health|volume=|pages=445\u2013459|via=}}</ref> A study of primary care providers showed that half would not care for patients if they were given a choice.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gerbert|first=Barbara|date=1991|title=Primary Care Physicians and AIDS|url=|journal=Journal of American Medical Association|volume=|pages=2837\u20132842|via=}}</ref> In 1990, a national survey of doctors showed that \"only 24% believed that office-based practitioners should be legally required to provide care to individuals with HIV infection.\"<ref name=\":02\" /> However, there were many doctors who chose to care for these patients with AIDS for different reasons: they shared the same sexual orientation as the infected, a commitment to providing care to the diseased, an interest in the mysteries of infectious disease, or a desire to tame the awful threat.<ref name=\":02\" /> Treating patients infected with the AIDS virus changed some doctors' personal lives, as it caused them to have to deal with some of the same stigmas that their patients had. This disease also weighed on their minds, because they often had to deal with witnessing the death of patients and most often those patients were as young or even younger than they were.\n\n== By race/ethnicity ==\n'''African Americans''' continue to experience the most severe burden of HIV, compared with other races and ethnicities. Black people represent approximately 13% of the U.S. population, but accounted for an estimated 43% of new HIV infections in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/hiv/group/racialethnic/africanamericans/index.html|title=HIV and African Americans {{!}} Race/Ethnicity {{!}} HIV by Group {{!}} HIV/AIDS {{!}} CDC|date=2019-03-19|website=www.cdc.gov|language=en-us|access-date=2019-07-10}}</ref> Furthermore, they make up nearly 52% of AIDS-related deaths in America. While the overall rates of HIV incidences and prevalence have decreased, they have increased in one particular demographic: African American gay and bisexual men (a 4% increase). In America, black households were reported to have the lowest median income, leading to lower rates of individuals with health insurance. This creates cost barriers to antiretroviral treatments. The racial disparities between women afflicted with HIV/AIDS have been made clear in a 2010 study as well, which showed that 64% of women infected with HIV that year were Black women.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Steiner|first=Riley J.|last2=Finocchario-Kessler|first2=Sarah|last3=Dariotis|first3=Jacinda K.|date=2013|title=Engaging HIV Care Providers in Conversations With Their Reproductive-Age Patients About Fertility Desires and Intentions: A Historical Review of the HIV Epidemic in the United States|journal=American Journal of Public Health|volume=103|issue=8|pages=1357\u20131366|doi=10.2105/ajph.2013.301265|pmid=23763424|pmc=4007857|issn=0090-0036}}</ref> This unequal distribution has led researchers to studying the long-term effects of racial and gender discrimination along with HIV-related stigma, and how this plays a role in people's lives.\n\n'''Hispanics/Latinos''' are also disproportionately affected by HIV. Hispanics/Latinos represented 16% of the population but accounted for 21% of new HIV infections in 2010. This disparity is even more apparent among Latina women, which represent 13% of the population but account for 20% of reported HIV cases among women in the United States.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Peragallo|date=2005|title=A Randomized Clinical Trial of an HIV-Risk-Reduction Intervention Among Low-Income Latino Women|journal=Nursing Research|volume=54|issue=4|pages=264|doi=10.1097/00006199-200507000-00008|issn=0029-6562}}</ref> Hispanics/Latinos accounted for 20% of people living with HIV infection in 2011. Disparities persist in the estimated rate of new HIV infections in Hispanics/Latinos. In 2010, the rate of new HIV infections for Latino males was 2.9 times that for white males, and the rate of new infections for Latinas was 4.2 times that for white females. Since the epidemic began, more than 100,888 Hispanics/Latinos with an AIDS diagnosis have died, including 2,863 in 2016.<ref name=\"cdchisplats\">{{cite web |title=HIV and Hispanics/Latinos |url=https://www.cdc.gov/hiv/group/racialethnic/hispaniclatinos/index.html |website=CDC.gov |publisher=Centre for Disease Control and Prevention |accessdate=Apr 6, 2020|date=2018-08-21}}</ref>\n\n'''American Indian/Alaskan Native''' Communities in the United States also see a higher rate of HIV/AIDS in comparison to whites, Asians, and Native Hawaiians/other Native Pacific Islanders. Although AI/AN sufferers of HIV/AIDS only represent roughly 1% of all sufferers in the U.S.,<ref name=\"CDCAIAN\">{{cite web |title=HIV and American Indians and Alaska Natives |url=https://www.cdc.gov/hiv/group/racialethnic/aian/index.html |website=CDC.gov |publisher=Centre for Disease Control and Prevention |accessdate=December 4, 2018|date=2018-08-21}}</ref> the number of diagnoses amongst AI/AN gay and bisexual men rose by 54% between 2011 and 2015. Additionally, the survival rate of diagnosed AI/AN was the lowest of all races in the United States between 1998 and 2005.<ref>{{cite web |title=A Briefing on HIV/AIDS in Indian Country - Fall 2017 |url=https://www.nihb.org/docs/10022017/NIHB%20HIV%20BRIEFING_NTHC_FINAL.pdf |website=nihb.org |publisher=National Indian Health Board |accessdate=December 4, 2018}}</ref> In recent years, the Centres for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) have put in place a \"high impact prevention approach\"<ref>{{cite web |title=HIV among American Indians and Alaska Natives in the United States |url=https://www.cdc.gov/hiv/group/racialethnic/aian/index.html |website=cdc.org |accessdate=December 4, 2018|date=2018-08-21}}</ref> in partnership with the Indian Health Service and the CDC Tribal Advisory Committee to tackle the growing rates in a culturally appropriate way.\nThe higher rate of HIV/AIDS cases amongst AI/AN people have been attributed to a number of factors including socioeconomic disadvantages faced by AI/AN communities, which may result in difficulty accessing healthcare and high-quality housing. It may be more difficult for gay and bisexual AI/AN men to access healthcare due to living in rural communities, or due to stigma attached to their sexualities. AI/AN people have also been reported to have higher rates of other STIs, including chlamydia and gonorrhea, which also increases likeliness of contracting or transmitting HIV.<ref>{{cite web |title=HIV in American Indians and Alaska Natives in the United States |url=https://www.cdc.gov/hiv/group/racialethnic/aian/index.html |website=cdc.org |publisher=Centre for Disease Control and Prevention |accessdate=December 4, 2018|date=2018-08-21}}</ref> Furthermore, as there are over 560 federally recognised AI/AN tribes, there is some difficulty in creating outreach programmes which effectively appeal to all tribes whilst remaining culturally appropriate. As well as fear of stigma from within AI/AN communities, there may also be a fear amongst LGBTQ+ AI/AN of a lack of understanding from health professionals in the United States, particularly amongst [[Two Spirit]] people. A 2013 NASTAD report calls for the inclusion of LGBT and Two Spirit AI/AN in HIV/AID program planning and asserts that \"health departments should utilize local experts to better understand regional definitions of \"Two Spirit\" and incorporate modules on Native gay men and Two Spirit people into cultural sensitivity courses for public health service providers\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Issue Brief: Native Gay Men and Two Spirit People |url=https://www.nastad.org/sites/default/files/resources/docs/Issue-Brief-Two-Spirit-Final-03-14-13.pdf |website=nastad.org |publisher=National Alliance of State and Territorial AIDS Directors |accessdate=December 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== \"Down-Low\" culture amongst Black MSM ===\n{{Main|Down-low (sexual slang)}}\n\nDown-low is an [[African American slang]] term<ref name=\"Cassell's Dic\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5GpLcC4a5fAC&pg=PA414|title=Cassell's Dictionary of Slang|last=Green|first=Jonathon|date=2006 |page= 893 |publisher=Sterling Publishing|isbn=978-0-304-36636-1|location=|quote=down low n. [1990s+] (US Black) a state of secrecy. down low adj. [1990s+] (US Black) covert, secret (i.e. keeping a low profile)}}</ref> that typically refers to a subculture of Black men who usually identify as heterosexual, but [[Men who have sex with men|who have sex with men]]; some avoid sharing this information even if they have female sexual partner(s) married or single.<ref name=\"Coming Up from the Down Low\">{{cite web|last=King |first=J.L. |first2=Courtney |last2=Carreras |title=Coming Up from the Down Low: The Journey to Acceptance, Healing and Honest Love |page=36 |publisher=Three Rivers Press |date=April 25, 2006 |url=http://www.enotalone.com/article/4411.html |accessdate=2009-12-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100818015102/http://www.enotalone.com/article/4411.html |archivedate=August 18, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"Secret Gay\">{{cite news| last =  Johnson| first =  Jason|title=Secret gay encounters of black men could be raising women's infection rate| newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle| date=May 1, 2005| url =  http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?file=/c/a/2005/05/01/MNG4TCID0F1.DTL&type=health |accessdate=2009-12-18}}</ref><ref name=\"Black masculinities\">{{cite book| last =  Mutua| first =  Athena|title=Progressive Black Masculinities| publisher=Routledge| page = 169| isbn = 978-0-415-97687-9 |date=September 28, 2006| url =  https://books.google.com/books?id=GAzEzR3dap4C&pg=PT197&lpg=PT197&q=%22down%20low%22%2C%20adapted%20by%20a%20subculture%20of%20black%20men| accessdate = 2009-12-18}}</ref><ref name=\"Outing Hip-Hop\">{{cite magazine| last=Bennett| first =  Jessica| title = Outing Hip-Hop| magazine = Newsweek| date=May 19, 2008| url =  http://www.newsweek.com/id/137380/page/1| accessdate=2009-12-19}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a study published in the [[Journal of Bisexuality]], \"[t]he Down Low is a lifestyle predominately practiced by young, urban Black men who have sex with other men and women, yet do not identify as gay or bisexual\".<ref name=\"Attitudes Towards\">{{cite journal |last=Heath |first=Jessie |first2=Kathy |last2=Goggin |title=Attitudes Towards Male Homosexuality, Bisexuality, and the Down Low Lifestyle: Demographic Differences and HIV Implications |journal=Journal of Bisexuality |doi=10.1080/15299710802659997 |volume=9 |issue=1 |pages=17\u201331 |date=January 2009 }}</ref>\n\nIn this context, \"being on the Down Low\" is more than just men having sex with men in secret, or a variant of [[closeted]] homosexuality or bisexuality\u2014it is a sexual identity that is, at least partly, defined by its \"cult of masculinity\" and its rejection of what is perceived as [[white people|White]] culture (including white [[LGBT]] culture) and terms.<ref name=\"Secret Gay\" /><ref name=\"Double Lives\">{{cite news |last= Denizet-Lewis |first= Benoit |title=Double Lives On The Down Low |newspaper=The New York Times |date=August 3, 2003 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/08/03/magazine/double-lives-on-the-down-low.html |accessdate=2012-04-26}}</ref><ref name=\"Down-Low Debate\">{{cite news |last=Wright |first=Kaimeans |title=The Great Down-Low Debate: A New Black Sexual Identity May Be an Incubator for AIDS |newspaper=The Village Voice |date=June 5, 2001 |url=http://www.villagevoice.com/2001-06-05/news/the-great-down-low-debate/1 |accessdate=2008-03-19}}</ref><ref name=\"Sex, lies\">{{cite news |title=Sex, lies and the \"down low\" |work=Salon.com |date=August 16, 2004 |url=http://www.salon.com/mwt/feature/2004/08/16/down_low/index.html |archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20080307114914/http://dir.salon.com/story/mwt/feature/2004/08/16/down_low/index.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=March 7, 2008 |accessdate=2009-12-18}}</ref> A 2003 ''[[New York Times Magazine]]'' cover story on the Down Low phenomenon explains that the Black community sees ''\"homosexuality as a White man's perversion.\"''<ref name=\"Double Lives\" />\n\nThe [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]] cited three findings that relate to African-American men who operate on the down-low (engage in MSM activity but don't disclose to others):\n* African American men who have sex with men (MSM), but who do not disclose their sexual orientation (nondisclosers), have a high prevalence of HIV infection (14%); nearly three times higher than nondisclosing MSMs of other races/ethnicities (5%).\n* Confirming previous research, the study of 5,589 MSM, aged 15\u201329 years, in six U.S. cities found that African American MSM were more likely not to disclose their sexual orientation compared with White MSM (18% vs. 8%).\n* HIV-infected nondisclosers were less likely to know their HIV status (98% were unaware of their infection compared with 75% of HIV-positive disclosers), and more likely to have had recent female sex partners.<ref name=\"MMWR\">{{cite web |title=CDC: Morbidity and Mortality Weekly Report |publisher=CDC: US Center for Disease Control and Prevention |date=February 7, 2003 |url=https://www.cdc.gov/media/mmwrnews/n030207.htm#mmwr1 |accessdate=2009-10-31 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091005104759/http://cdc.gov/media/mmwrnews/n030207.htm#mmwr1 |archive-date=October 5, 2009 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Risk Factors contributing to the Black HIV rate ===\n{{Original research section|date=May 2018}}\n{{citation needed section|date=October 2019}}\n\nAccessibility to healthcare is very important in preventing and treating HIV/AIDS. It can be affected by health insurance which is available to people through private insurers, [[Medicare (United States)|Medicare]] and [[Medicaid]] which leaves some people still vulnerable. Historically, African Americans have faced discrimination when it comes to receiving healthcare.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Armstrong|first=Katrina|last2=Putt|first2=Mary|last3=Halbert|first3=Chanita H.|last4=Grande|first4=David|last5=Schwartz|first5=Jerome Sanford|last6=Liao|first6=Kaijun|last7=Marcus|first7=Noora|last8=Demeter|first8=Mirar B.|last9=Shea|first9=Judy A.|date=February 2013|title=Prior Experiences of Racial Discrimination and Racial Differences in Health Care System Distrust|journal=Medical Care|volume=51|issue=2|pages=144\u2013150|doi=10.1097/mlr.0b013e31827310a1|pmid=23222499|pmc=3552105|issn=0025-7079}}</ref> During the time of slavery, slave owners would get medical attention for slaves because they were deemed as property, while slaves that the slave owners believed were not able to recover were sent to be experimented on. In the late eighteenth century and early nineteenth century, universities dug up African American bodies to autopsy, and some night doctors would snatch people off the streets to examine. African Americans have been experimented on and exploited for centuries. The Tuskegee Syphilis study experimented vulnerable men in the South who had syphilis. They kept treatment from these men to see what would happen. [[Henrietta Lacks]] was also exploited when researchers took her cancerous cells and grew them to experiment on them.<ref>{{cite book|title=Black Man in a White Coat|last=Tweedy|first=Damon|publisher=Picador|year=2015|isbn=|location=New York|pages=153\u2013178}}</ref>\n\nHomosexuality is viewed negatively in the African American Community. \"In a qualitative study of 745 racially and ethnic diverse undergraduates attending a large Midwestern university, Calzo and Ward (2009) determined that parents of African-American participants discussed homosexuality more frequently than the parents of other respondents. In analyses of the values communicated, Calzo and Ward (2009) reported that Black parents offered greater indication that homosexuality is perverse and unnatural\".<ref name=\"Hill 2013 475\u2013487\">{{cite journal|last=Hill|first=William Allen|last2=McNeely|first2=Clea|date=2013|title=HIV/AIDS Disparity between African-American and Caucasian Men Who Have Sex with Men: Intervention Strategies for the Black Church|jstor=24484999|journal=Journal of Religion and Health|volume=52|issue=2|pages=475\u2013487|doi=10.1007/s10943-011-9496-2|pmid=21538178}}</ref>\n\nHomosexuality is seen as a threat to the African American empowerment.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Not In My Family|last=Robertson|first=Gil|publisher=Agate|year=2006|isbn=978-1-932841-24-4|location=Canada|pages=80\u201382}}</ref> Masculinity is seen as important for the African American community because it shows that the community is in control of their own destiny. Since the stigma circling homosexuality is that it is \"effeminate\", then homosexuality is seen as a threat to masculinity. \"Black manhood, then, depends on men's ability to be provider, progenitor, and protector. But, as the Black male performance of parts of this script is thwarted by economic and cultural factors, the performance of Black masculinity becomes predicated on a particular performance of Black sexuality and avoidance of weakness and femininity. If sexuality remains one of the few ways that Black men can recapture a masculinity withheld from them in the marketplace, endorsing Black homosexuality subverts the cultural project of reinscribing masculinity within the Black community.\" This critical view is influenced by Internalized homophobia. \"Internalized homophobia is defined as the lesbian, gay, or bisexual individual's inward direction of society's homophobic attitudes (Meyer 1995).\"<ref name=\"Hill 2013 475\u2013487\" />\n\nThe African American community's social norms regarding homosexuality have influenced a higher percentage of African Americans with internalized homophobia. This homophobic culture is sustained within the African American community through the church because religion is a vital part of the African American community: \"As reported by Peterson and Jones (2009), AA MSM tended to be more involved with religious communities than NHW MSM.\" Because the church reiterates this stigma of homosexuality, the African American community has higher rates of internalized homophobia. This internalized homophobia causes a lower chance of HIV/AIDS education on prevention and care within the African American community.<ref name=\"Hill 2013 475\u2013487\" />\n\nSex education varies throughout the United States and in some areas could use more informative measures. African-Americans and Hispanic/ Latinos experience higher rates of lower socioeconomic statuses and fewer opportunities than white people. This causes limited access to (higher) education in lower socioeconomic areas. Sex education on HIV prevention has decreased from 64% (2000) to 41% (2014). Out of the 50 states, 26 put a larger emphasis on abstinence sex education. Abstinence only sex education is correlated to increasing rates of HIV especially in teenagers and young adults.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.avert.org/professionals/hiv-around-world/western-central-europe-north-america/usa|title=HIV and AIDS in the United States of America (USA)|date=2015-07-21|work=AVERT|access-date=2018-05-11|language=en}}</ref>\n\nWith mass incarceration of the African American community, HIV has been [[infectious diseases within American prisons|spreading rapidly throughout jails and prisons]]. \"Among jail populations, African American men are 5 times as likely as white men, and twice as likely as Hispanic/Latino men, to be diagnosed with HIV.\" Since most people contract HIV before being incarcerated, it is hard to know who has the disease and to keep it from spreading. A lack of hygiene in prisons perpetuates these problems. Many inmates do not disclose their high-risk behaviors, such as anal sex or injection drug use, because they fear being stigmatized and ostracized by other inmates. There is also a lack of educational programs on disease prevention for inmates. Because \"nine out of ten jail inmates are released in under 72 hours which makes it hard to test them for HIV and help them find treatment,\" the problem persists outside of prison.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thebodypro.com/article/hiv-in-correctional-settings|title=HIV Among Incarcerated Populations in the United States|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Activism and response ==\nStarting in the early 1980s, AIDS activist groups and organizations began to emerge and advocate for people infected with HIV in the United States. Though it was an important aspect of the movement, activism went beyond the pursuit of funding for AIDS research. Groups acted to educate and raise awareness of the disease and its effects on different populations, even those thought to be at low-risk of contracting HIV. This was done through publications and \"alternative media\" created by those living with or close to the disease.<ref>{{Cite book|title=AIDS TV: Identity, Community, and Alternative Video|last=Juhasz|first=Alexandra|publisher=Duke University Press|year=1995|isbn=978-0-8223-1695-4|location=Durham, North Carolina|pages=}}</ref>\n\nIn contrast to this \"alternative media\" created by activist groups, mass media reports on AIDS were not as prevalent, most likely due to the stigma surrounding the topic. The general public was therefore not exposed to information regarding the disease. In addition, the federal government and laws in place essentially prevented individuals afflicted with AIDS from getting sufficient information about the disease. Risk reduction education was not easily accessible, so activist groups took action in releasing information to the public through these publications.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=HEREK|first=GREGORY M.|date=1999|title=AIDS and Stigma|journal=American Behavioral Scientist|language=en-US|volume=42|issue=7|pages=1106\u20131116|doi=10.1177/0002764299042007004|issn=0002-7642|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/2627cf2069a85bbd3ec607ae91cb6fd4d6c6b859}}</ref>\n\nActivist groups worked to prevent spread of HIV by distributing information about safe sex. They also existed to support people living with HIV/AIDS, offering therapy, support groups, and hospice care.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite book|title=Reproductive Justice: An Introduction|last=Ross|first=Loretta|publisher=University of California Press|year=2017|isbn=978-0-520-28820-1|location=Oakland, California|pages=}}</ref> Organizations like [[Gay Men's Health Crisis]], the Lesbian AIDS Project, and SisterLove were created to address the needs of certain populations living with HIV/AIDS. Other groups, like the [[NAMES Project AIDS Memorial Quilt|NAMES Project]], emerged as a way of memorializing those who had passed, refusing to let them be forgotten by the historical narrative. One group, the Association for Drug Abuse Prevention and Treatment (ADAPT), headed by [[Yolanda Serrano]], coordinated with their local prison, [[Rikers Island Correctional Facility|Riker's Island Correctional Facility]], to advocate for those imprisoned and AIDS positive to be released early, so that they could pass away in the comfort of their own homes.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=U-UCAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA35&lpg=PA35&dq=yolanda+serrano+and+adapt#v=onepage&q=yolanda%20serrano%20and%20adapt&f=false|title=ADAPT and Survive|last=Carter|first=Zoe|date=1988-05-09|magazine=New York Magazine|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref>\n\nBoth men and women, heterosexual and queer populations were active in establishing and maintaining these parts of the movement. Because AIDS was initially thought only to impact gay men, most narratives of activism focus on their contributions to the movement. However, women also played a significant role in raising awareness, rallying for change, and caring for those impacted by the disease. Lesbians helped organize and spread information about transmission between women, as well as supporting gay men in their work. Narratives of activism also tend to focus on organizing done in coastal cities, but AIDS activism was present and widespread across both urban and more rural areas of the United States. Organizers sought to address needs specific to their communities, whether that was working to establish [[Needle exchange programme|needle exchange programs]], fighting against housing or employment discrimination, or issues faced primarily by people identified as members of specific groups (such as sex workers, mothers and children, or incarcerated people).\n\nInitially when the AIDS epidemic surfaced in the United States, a large proportion of patients were LGBT community members, leading to stigmatization of the disease. Because of this, the AIDS activist groups took initiative in testing and experimenting with new possible medications for treating HIV, after researchers outside of the community refused. This research originally done by early activist groups contributed to treatments still being used today.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Street science : community knowledge and environmental health justice|last=Corburn, Jason.|date=2005|publisher=MIT Press|isbn=0-262-03333-X|oclc=58830060}}</ref>\n\n=== Present day activism ===\nAn effective response to HIV/AIDS requires that groups of vulnerable populations have access to HIV prevention programs with information and services that are specific to them.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.avert.org/professionals/hiv-social-issues/key-affected-populations|title=Key Affected Populations, HIV and AIDS|last=|first=|date=2015-07-24|website=Avert: Global Information and Education on HIV and AIDS|access-date=}}</ref> In the present day, some activist groups and AIDS organizations that were established during the height of the epidemic are still present and working to assist people living with AIDS.<ref name=\":0\" /> They may offer any combination of the following: health education, counseling and support, or advocacy for law and policy. AIDS organizations also continue to call for public awareness and support through participation in events like pride parades, [[World AIDS Day]], or [[AIDS Walk|AIDS walks]]. Newer activism has appeared in advocacy for [[Pre-Exposure Prophylaxis]] (PrEP), which has shown to significantly limit transmission of HIV. While PrEP appears to be extremely successful in suppressing the spread of HIV infection, there is some evidence that the reduction in HIV risk has led to some people taking more sexual risks, specifically, reduced use of condoms in anal sex.<ref>Holt M, Lea T, Mao L, Kolstee J, Zablotska I, Duck T, Allan B, West M, Lee E, Hull P, Grulich A, De Wit J, Prestage G (August 2018). \"Community-level changes in condom use and uptake of HIV pre-exposure prophylaxis by gay and bisexual men in Melbourne and Sydney, Australia: results of repeated behavioural surveillance in 2013-17\". The Lancet. HIV. 5 (8): e448\u2013e456. doi:10.1016/s2352-3018(18)30072-9. {{PMID|29885813}}.</ref>\n\n== Current status ==\n\nThe CDC estimates at the end of 2017, there were 1,018,346 adults and adolescents with diagnosed HIV in the US and dependent areas.<ref name=\"cdcataglance\">{{cite web |title=Statistics Overview |website=CDC |accessdate=Apr 6, 2020 |url=https://www.cdc.gov/hiv/statistics/overview/index.html}}</ref> {{As of|2016|lc=y||df=}}, the CDC estimated about 14% of infections had not been diagnosed.<ref name=\"cdcataglance\" /> Since 2010, the number of people living with HIV has increased, while the annual number of new HIV infections has declined to 37,832 diagnosed in 2018.<ref name=\"cdcataglance\" /><ref name=\"CDCBasicStats\" /> Within the overall estimates, however, some groups are affected more than others. 70% of 2018 diagnoses were among men who have sex with men, 7% were among injection drug users, and new infections disproportionately occurred among heterosexual women and African Americans.<ref name=\"cdcataglance\" /><ref name=\"CDCBasicStats\" />\n\nAn estimated 15,807 people with an AIDS diagnosis died in 2016,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/hiv/library/reports/hiv-surveillance.html|title=Diagnoses of HIV Infection in the United States and Dependent Areas, 2016|date=November 2017|work=HIV Surveillance Report, 2016|publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]]|accessdate=April 26, 2018}}</ref> and approximately 658,507 people in the United States with an AIDS diagnosis have died overall. The deaths of persons with an AIDS diagnosis can be due to any cause\u2014that is, the death may or may not be related to AIDS.\n\nThe most recent CDC HIV Surveillance Report estimates that 38,281 new cases of HIV were diagnosed in the United States in 2017, a rate of 11.8 per 100,000 population.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/hiv/library/reports/hiv-surveillance.html|title=HIV Surveillance {{!}} Reports{{!}} Resource Library {{!}} HIV/AIDS {{!}} CDC|date=2019-11-07|website=www.cdc.gov|language=en-us|accessdate=2019-11-21}}</ref> This rate is a decrease from the previous year's estimates, which indicated 39,589 new infections and a rate of 12.2 per 100,000 population.<ref name=\":1\" /> Individuals in the age range 25\u201329 years-old had the highest rates of new infection, with a rate of 32.9 per 100,000.<ref name=\":1\" /> With regard to race and ethnicity, the highest rates of new infections in 2017 occurred in the Black/African-American population, with a new infection rate of 41.1 per 100,000. This more than doubled the next highest rate for a racial or ethnic group, which was Hispanic/Latino with a rate of 16.6 per 100,000.<ref name=\":1\" /> The lowest rates of new infection in 2017 occurred in the White population and Asian population, which each had a new infection rate of 5.1 per 100,000.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nAccording to CDC estimates, the most common transmission category of new infections remained male-to-male sexual contact, which accounted for roughly 66.6% of all new infections in the United States in 2017.<ref name=\":1\" /> With regard to region of residence, the highest rates of new infections in 2017 occurred in the United States South, with 19,968 total new infections and 16.1 infections per 100,000.<ref name=\":1\" /> The region identified as 'South' includes Alabama, Arkansas, Delaware, District of Columbia, Florida, Georgia, Kentucky, Louisiana, Maryland, Mississippi, North Carolina, Oklahoma, South Carolina, Tennessee, Texas, Virginia, and West Virginia.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn the United States, men who have sex with men (MSM), described as gay and bisexual,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/hiv/group/msm/|title=Gay and Bisexual Men \u2013 HIV by Group|date=February 27, 2018|website=www.cdc.gov}}</ref> make up about 55% of the total HIV-positive population, and 67% of new HIV cases and 83% of the estimated new HIV diagnoses among ''all'' males aged 13 and older, and an estimated 92% of new HIV diagnoses among all men in their age group (2014 report). 1 in 6 gay and bisexual men are therefore expected to be diagnosed with HIV in their lifetime if current rates continue. Gay and bisexual men accounted for an estimated 54% of people diagnosed with AIDS, with 39% being African American, 32% being white, and 24% being Hispanic/Latino.<ref>{{cite web|title=HIV Among Gay and Bisexual Men|url=https://www.cdc.gov/hiv/pdf/group/msm/cdc-hiv-msm.pdf|accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> The CDC estimates that more than 600,000 gay and bisexual men are currently living with HIV in the United States.<ref>https://www.cdc.gov/hiv/pdf/group/msm/cdc-hiv-msm.pdf</ref> A review of four studies in which trans women in the United States were tested for HIV found that 27.7% tested positive.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Estimating HIV Prevalence and Risk Behaviors of Transgender Persons in the United States: A Systematic Review|pmid=17694429 |doi=10.1007/s10461-007-9299-3 |volume=12|issue=1|date=Jan 2008|journal=AIDS Behav|pages=1\u201317|last1=Herbst |first1=J. H |last2=Jacobs |first2=E. D |last3=Finlayson |first3=T. J |last4=McKleroy |first4=V. S |last5=Neumann |first5=M. S |last6=Crepaz |first6=N |author7=HIV/AIDS Prevention Research Synthesis Team|url=https://hal.archives-ouvertes.fr/hal-02319357/file/Poster%20Olga%20L%20Gonzalez%202019.pdf }}</ref>\n\nIn a 2008 study, the Center for Disease Control found that, of the study participants who were men who had sex with men (\"MSM\"), almost one in five (19%) had HIV and \"among those who were infected, nearly half (44 percent) were unaware of their HIV status.\" The research found that white MSM \"represent a greater number of new HIV infections than any other population, followed closely by black MSM\u2014who are one of the most disproportionately affected subgroups in the U.S.\" and that most new infections among white MSM occurred among those aged 30\u201339 followed closely by those aged 40\u201349, while most new infections among black MSM have occurred among young black MSM (aged 13\u201329).<ref name=\"2010sept_cdc\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/nchhstp/.../docs/FastFacts-MSM-FINAL508COMP.pdf|title=CDC Fact Sheet \u2013 HIV and AIDS among Gay and Bisexual Men \u2013 Sept 2010}}{{Dead link|date=August 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes}}</ref><ref name=\"kaiser_2010gaymale_hiv\">{{cite web |url=http://www.kaiserhealthnews.org/Daily-Reports/2010/September/24/AIDS-gay-men.aspx|title=CDC: One In Five Gay Men HIV-Positive |date=September 24, 2010 |publisher=Kaiser Health News}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, a major HIV outbreak, [[Indiana]]'s largest-ever, occurred in two largely rural, economically depressed and poor counties in the southern portion of the state, due to the injection of a relatively new opioid-type drug called Opana ([[oxymorphone]]), which is designed be taken in pill form but is ground up and injected intravenously using needles. Because of the lack of HIV cases in that area beforehand and the youth of many but not all of those affected, the relative unavailability in the local area of safe needle exchange programs and of treatment centers capable of dealing with long-term health needs, HIV care, and drug addiction during the initial phases of the outbreak, it was not initially adequately contained and dealt with until those were set up by the government, and acute awareness of the issue spread. Such centers have now been opened, and short-term care is beginning to be provided; once the scope of the outbreak became clear, Governor [[Mike Pence]], despite some initial reservations, approved a legislative measure to allow safe, clean needle exchange programs and treatment for those affected, which could end up being instituted statewide.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/2015/04/24/402034996/hiv-outbreak-in-indiana-grows-with-nearly-140-confirmed-cases|title=HIV Outbreak In Indiana Grows With Nearly 140 Confirmed Cases|last1=Block |first1=Melissa |last2=Adams|first2=Jerome |date=April 24, 2015|publisher=NPR|accessdate=May 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Criminal transmission of HIV in the United States]]\n* [[Adult Industry Medical Health Care Foundation]]\n* [[AIDS Education and Training Centers (AETCs)]]\n* [[People With AIDS]] Self-Empowerment Movement\n* [[HIV/AIDS in New York City]]\n* [[Hank M. Tavera]]\n* [[President's Emergency Plan for AIDS Relief]] (international)\n* [[:Category:HIV/AIDS activism|HIV/AIDS activism]]\n* [[:Category:HIV/AIDS activists|HIV/AIDS activists]]\n\n'''International:'''\n* [[AIDS pandemic]]\n* [[HIV/AIDS in North America]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n# {{cite book | last = Cante | first = Richard C. | title = Gay Men and the Forms of Contemporary US Culture | publisher = Ashgate Publishing |isbn=978-0-7546-7230-2 |date=March 2008 | location = London}}\n# {{cite journal\n| last = Bogart |first = Laura | last2 = Thorburn |first2 = Sheryl\n| title = Are HIV/AIDS conspiracy beliefs a barrier to HIV prevention among African Americans?\n| journal = J. Acquir. Immune Defic. Syndr.\n| volume = 38 | issue = 2 | pages = 213\u20138 |date=February 2005 | pmid = 15671808\n| doi=10.1097/00126334-200502010-00014}}\n# {{Cite book\n  | last = Walker\n  | first = Robert Searles\n  | title = AIDS: Today, Tomorrow : an Introduction to the HIV Epidemic in America\n  | publisher = Humanities Press Intl |edition= 2nd | year = 1994\n  | location = Atlantic Highlands, New Jersey\n  | isbn = 978-0-391-03859-2 |oclc=30399464}}\n# {{Cite book\n  | last = Siplon | first = Patricia\n  | title = AIDS and the policy struggle in the United States\n  | publisher = Georgetown University Press | year = 2002\n  | location = Washington D.C.\n  | isbn = 978-0-87840-378-3 |oclc= 48964730}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.aids.gov/ AIDS.gov \u2013 The U.S. Federal Domestic HIV/AIDS Resource]\n* [http://www.aidsvu.org/ AIDSVu.org \u2013 Interactive Map Illustrating HIV Prevalence in the United States]\n* [https://asteria.fivecolleges.edu/findaids/sophiasmith/mnsss291.html Finding Aid \u2013 Voices of Feminism Oral History Project, 1990\u20132006]\n\n{{North America topic|HIV/AIDS in}}\n{{LGBT in the United States}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hiv Aids In The United States}}\n[[Category:1960 establishments in the United States]]\n[[Category:HIV/AIDS in the United States| ]]\n[[Category:LGBT history in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Estoytranquile", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HIV/AIDS_in_the_United_States"}
{"title_page": "Commission for Academic Accreditation", "text_new": "{{Infobox Government agency\n|agency_name     = <small>United Arab Emirates</small> <br> Commission for Academic Accreditation (CAA)\n|nativename      = <big>'''\u0645\u0641\u0648\u0636\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0627\u0639\u062a\u0645\u0627\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0643\u0627\u062f\u064a\u0645\u064a'''</big>\n|nativename_a    =\n|nativename_r    =\n|logo            = \n|logo_width      = \n|logo_caption    = \n|jurisdiction    = [[UAE]]\n|headquarters    = [[Abu Dhabi]]\n|coordinates     = \n|chief1_name     = Mohamed Yousif Baniyas<ref name=\"caa-comm\">{{cite web| url=https://www.caa.ae/caa/DesktopDefault.aspx?tabindex=3&tabid=57 | title=Commissioners | publisher=Commission for Academic Accreditation | location=UAE | accessdate=17 March 2019}}</ref>\n|chief1_position = Director\n|chief2_name     = Emad Abuelrub<ref name=\"caa-comm\" />\n|chief2_position = Deputy Director\n|chief3_name     = \n|chief3_position = \n|parent_agency   = [[Ministry of Education (United Arab Emirates)|Ministry of Education]]\n|child1_agency   = \n|child2_agency   =\n|website         = {{URL|https://www.caa.ae}}\n|seal=|formed=|employees=|budget=|chief4_name=|chief4_position=|chief5_name=|chief5_position=|chief6_name=|chief6_position=|chief7_name=|chief7_position=|chief8_name=|chief8_position=|chief9_name=|chief9_position=|parent_department=}}\n\nThe '''Commission for Academic Accreditation''' ('''CAA''') is the UAE government-run institutional [[licensure]] and degree [[Academic accreditation|accreditation]] organization for private universities and their academic programmes in the [[United Arab Emirates]] (UAE).<ref>[http://www.abudhabi.ae/egovPoolPortal_WAR/appmanager/ADeGP/Citizen?_nfpb=true&_pageLabel=p19662&lang=en Commission for Academic Accreditation], [http://www.abudhabi.ae/ Abu Dhabi Government Portal] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140208070657/https://www.abudhabi.ae/ |date=2014-02-08 }}, UAE.</ref> It was established in 1999, with headquarters in UAE's capital city [[Abu Dhabi]], and is a department of the [[Ministry of Education (United Arab Emirates)|Ministry of Education]].<ref>[http://www.mohesr.ae/department_caa.html The Commission for Academic Accreditation (CAA)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091108135917/http://www.mohesr.ae/department_caa.html |date=2009-11-08 }}, Ministry of Higher Education and Scientific Research, UAE.</ref> The CAA is a member of the [[Arab Network for Quality Assurance in Higher Education]] (ANQAHE).<ref>[http://english.anqahe.org/ ANQAHE web portal]{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nThe CAA has a number of commissioners led by its director, Dr Mohammad Yousef Baniyas.<ref>[http://www.caa.ae/caa/DesktopDefault.aspx?tabindex=3&tabid=57 Commissioners], Commission for Academic Accreditation, UAE.</ref> Institutions must follow standards set by the CAA.<ref>''Standards for Licensure and Accreditation'', Commission for Academic Accreditation, [[Ministry of Higher Education and Scientific Research]], United Arab Emirates. Fourth Edition, 2007.</ref> There are specific standards for [[e-learning]]<ref>''e-Learning Standards for Licensure and Accreditation'', Commission for Academic Accreditation, [[Ministry of Higher Education and Scientific Research]], United Arab Emirates, 2007.</ref> and, since 2009, for vocational education and technical training.<ref>[http://www.caa.ae/caa/images/standards2009.pdf ''Standards for Licensure and Accreditation of Technical and Vocational Education and Training'', Commission for Academic Accreditation, Ministry of Higher Education and Scientific Research, United Arab Emirates, 2009]</ref> Licensure and accreditation are achieved through submission of supporting documentation and site visits by a commissioner and a visiting committee of experienced academics with appropriate expertise.\n\nAll non-federal [[higher education]] institutions operating outside a [[Free economic zone#United Arab Emirates|free zone]] in the UAE must have a license to operate and their academic programmes must be accredited before students may be admitted. Many institutions operating within a free zone nevertheless submit themselves to the CAA for license and accreditation. More recently, degree programmes at federal (government-run) institutions are also now accredited.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of recognized higher education accreditation organizations]]\n* [[List of universities and colleges in the United Arab Emirates]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.caa.ae/ CAA website]\n\n{{coord missing|United Arab Emirates}}\n\n[[Category:1999 establishments in the United Arab Emirates]]\n[[Category:Government agencies established in 1999]]\n[[Category:Organisations based in Abu Dhabi]]\n[[Category:Education in the United Arab Emirates]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in the United Arab Emirates|*Commission for Academic Accreditation]]\n[[Category:Higher education accreditation]]\n[[Category:Government agencies of the United Arab Emirates]]\n[[Category:Quality assurance organizations]]\n\n\n{{UAE-stub}}\n{{gov-agency-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Government agency\n|agency_name     = <small>United Arab Emirates</small> <br> Commission for Academic Accreditation (CAA)\n|nativename      = <big>'''\u0647\u064a\u0626\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0627\u0639\u062a\u0645\u0627\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0643\u0627\u062f\u064a\u0645\u064a'''</big>\n|nativename_a    =\n|nativename_r    =\n|logo            = \n|logo_width      = \n|logo_caption    = \n|jurisdiction    = [[UAE]]\n|headquarters    = [[Abu Dhabi]]\n|coordinates     = \n|chief1_name     = Mohamed Yousif Baniyas<ref name=\"caa-comm\">{{cite web| url=https://www.caa.ae/caa/DesktopDefault.aspx?tabindex=3&tabid=57 | title=Commissioners | publisher=Commission for Academic Accreditation | location=UAE | accessdate=17 March 2019}}</ref>\n|chief1_position = Director\n|chief2_name     = Badr Aboul-Ela<ref name=\"caa-comm\" />\n|chief2_position = Advisor\n|chief3_name     = \n|chief3_position = \n|parent_agency   = [[Ministry of Education (United Arab Emirates)|Ministry of Education]]\n|child1_agency   = \n|child2_agency   =\n|website         = {{URL|https://www.caa.ae}}\n|seal=|formed=|employees=|budget=|chief4_name=|chief4_position=|chief5_name=|chief5_position=|chief6_name=|chief6_position=|chief7_name=|chief7_position=|chief8_name=|chief8_position=|chief9_name=|chief9_position=|parent_department=}}\n\nThe '''Commission for Academic Accreditation''' ('''CAA''') is the UAE government-run institutional [[licensure]] and degree [[Academic accreditation|accreditation]] organization for private universities and their academic programmes in the [[United Arab Emirates]] (UAE).<ref>[http://www.abudhabi.ae/egovPoolPortal_WAR/appmanager/ADeGP/Citizen?_nfpb=true&_pageLabel=p19662&lang=en Commission for Academic Accreditation], [http://www.abudhabi.ae/ Abu Dhabi Government Portal] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140208070657/https://www.abudhabi.ae/ |date=2014-02-08 }}, UAE.</ref> It was established in 1999, with headquarters in UAE's capital city [[Abu Dhabi]], and is a department of the [[Ministry of Education (United Arab Emirates)|Ministry of Education]].<ref>[http://www.mohesr.ae/department_caa.html The Commission for Academic Accreditation (CAA)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091108135917/http://www.mohesr.ae/department_caa.html |date=2009-11-08 }}, Ministry of Higher Education and Scientific Research, UAE.</ref> The CAA is a member of the [[Arab Network for Quality Assurance in Higher Education]] (ANQAHE).<ref>[http://english.anqahe.org/ ANQAHE web portal]{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nThe CAA has a number of commissioners led for many years by its former director, Dr Badr Aboul-Ela, a founder member of the organization.<ref>[http://www.caa.ae/caa/DesktopDefault.aspx?tabindex=3&tabid=57 Commissioners], Commission for Academic Accreditation, UAE.</ref> Institutions must follow standards set by the CAA.<ref>''Standards for Licensure and Accreditation'', Commission for Academic Accreditation, [[Ministry of Higher Education and Scientific Research]], United Arab Emirates. Fourth Edition, 2007.</ref> There are specific standards for [[e-learning]]<ref>''e-Learning Standards for Licensure and Accreditation'', Commission for Academic Accreditation, [[Ministry of Higher Education and Scientific Research]], United Arab Emirates, 2007.</ref> and, since 2009, for vocational education and technical training.<ref>[http://www.caa.ae/caa/images/standards2009.pdf ''Standards for Licensure and Accreditation of Technical and Vocational Education and Training'', Commission for Academic Accreditation, Ministry of Higher Education and Scientific Research, United Arab Emirates, 2009]</ref> Licensure and accreditation are achieved through submission of supporting documentation and site visits by a commissioner and a visiting committee of experienced academics with appropriate expertise.\n\nAll non-federal [[higher education]] institutions operating outside a [[Free economic zone#United Arab Emirates|free zone]] in the UAE must have a license to operate and their academic programmes must be accredited before students may be admitted. Many institutions operating within a free zone nevertheless submit themselves to the CAA for license and accreditation. More recently, degree programmes at federal (government-run) institutions are also now accredited.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of recognized higher education accreditation organizations]]\n* [[List of universities and colleges in the United Arab Emirates]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.caa.ae/ CAA website]\n\n{{coord missing|United Arab Emirates}}\n\n[[Category:1999 establishments in the United Arab Emirates]]\n[[Category:Government agencies established in 1999]]\n[[Category:Organisations based in Abu Dhabi]]\n[[Category:Education in the United Arab Emirates]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in the United Arab Emirates|*Commission for Academic Accreditation]]\n[[Category:Higher education accreditation]]\n[[Category:Government agencies of the United Arab Emirates]]\n[[Category:Quality assurance organizations]]\n\n\n{{UAE-stub}}\n{{gov-agency-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Jehad Al-SAdi", "label": "safe", "comment": "due to the change in the structure of CAA and due to that Dr. Bader is no longer with CAA. I made these changes. By the way, Dr. Bader  died last December  2019.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Commission_for_Academic_Accreditation"}
{"title_page": "Bassas da India", "text_new": "{{Coord|21|28|57|S|39|40|19|E|region:FR-TF_type:isle|display=title}}\n\n{{Expand French|Bassas da India|date=February 2017|topic=geo}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n\n{{Infobox country\n|conventional_long_name = Bassas da India\n|native_name = ''Bassas da India''\n|image_flag = Flag of the French Southern and Antarctic Lands.svg\n|image_coat = \n|symbol_type = Coat of arms\n|national_motto = \"[[Libert\u00e9, \u00e9galit\u00e9, fraternit\u00e9]]\"\n|national_anthem = ''[[La Marseillaise]]''\n|image_map = Iles eparses de l'ocean Indien.svg\n|map_caption = Location of the [[Scattered Islands in the Indian Ocean]]. <div style=\"text-align:left;margin-left:8.0em;\">{{vunblist |1. Bassas da India |2. [[Europa Island]] |3. [[Glorioso Islands]] |4. [[Juan de Nova Island]] |5. [[Tromelin Island]]}}</div>\n}}\n\n'''Bassas da India''' ({{IPA-fr|basa da \u025b\u0303dja}}) is an uninhabited, roughly circular French [[atoll]] that is part of the [[French Southern and Antarctic Lands]]. Located in the southern [[Mozambique Channel]], about halfway between [[Mozambique]] and [[Madagascar]] (about {{convert|385|km|abbr=on|disp=sqbr}} further east) and around {{convert|110|km|abbr=on}} northwest of [[Europa Island]], the rim of the atoll averages around {{convert|100|m}} in width and encloses a shallow lagoon of depth no greater than {{convert|15|m|abbr=on}}. Overall, the atoll is about {{convert|10|km|abbr=on}} in diameter, rising steeply from the [[seabed]] {{convert|3000|m}} below to encircle an area (including lagoon) of {{convert|80|km2|abbr=on}}. Its [[exclusive economic zone]] (EEZ), {{convert|123700|km\u00b2|abbr=on}} in size, is [[Contiguous zone|contiguous]] with that of Europa Island.\n\nThe atoll consists of ten barren rocky islets, with no vegetation, totalling {{convert|20|ha}} in area. Those on the north and east sides are {{convert|7|to|10|ft|order=flip}} high, while those on the west and south sides are {{convert|4|ft|order=flip}} high. The reef, whose coastline measures {{convert|35.2|km|abbr=on}}, is completely covered by the sea from three hours before [[Tide|high tide]] to three hours afterward. The region is also subject to [[cyclone]]s, making the atoll a long-time maritime hazard and the site of numerous shipwrecks.\n\n[[Jaguar Seamount]] and [[Hall Tablemount]] lie, respectively, about {{convert|40|and|70|km}} further southwest.\n\n== History ==\nThe Bassas da India was first recorded by [[Portuguese explorers]] in the early sixteenth century as the \"'''''Baixo da'' Judia'''\" (\"''Jewess'' Shoals\"). The ''Judia'' (\"''Jewess''\", for the ancestry of its owner [[Fern\u00e3o de Loronha]]<ref>{{cite contribution |title=Rela\u00e7am do navfragio da nao Santiago & itenerario da gente que delle se salvou |last=Cardozo |first=Manoel Godinho |orig-year=First published 1602 |editor-first=Bernardo |editor-last=Gomes de Brito |work=[[Hist\u00f3ria tr\u00e1gico-mar\u00edtima]] |page=[https://archive.org/details/historiatragicom02brit/page/n193/ 47] |location=Lisbon |publisher=Off. da Congrega\u00e7ao do Oratorio |volume=Volume II |date=1736}}</ref>) was the Portuguese ship that discovered the feature by running aground on it in 1506.<ref>{{cite journal |first=Brian R. |last=Stuckenberg |title=The location and identity of the Baixos da Judia : Portuguese historical cartography of the Mozambique Channel and its relevance to the wreck of the Santiago in 1585 |work=Natal Museum Journal of Humanities |volume=12 |publisher=Council of the Natal Museum |location=Pietermaritzburg, South Africa |pages=51\u201379 |date=December 2000 |issn=1015-0935}}</ref> The name became \"'''Bassas da India'''\" due to transcription errors by cartographers. The ''Santiago'' broke up on the shoal in 1585.\n\nIt was rediscovered by the ''Europa'' in 1774, whence the name \"Europa Rocks\".<ref>{{cite book |quote=Bassas da India, sometimes named Europa rocks, was discovered by the ship ''Europa'' in 1774. |author-first=Algernon F. R. |author-last=de Horsey |title=The Africa Pilot, Part III : South and east coasts of Africa from the Cape of Good Hope to Cape Guardafui, including the islands in the Mozambique Channel |publisher=[[United Kingdom Hydrographic Office|Hydrographic Office of Great Britain]] |location=London |edition=3rd |date=1878 |page=410 |oclc=36761841}}</ref> The ''Malay'' was lost 27 July 1842 on the Europa Rocks.<ref>{{cite book |first1=Chas. S. |last1=Osgood |first2=H. M. |last2=Batchelder |title=Historical Sketch of Salem, 1626\u20131879 |date=1879 |location=Salem |publisher=Essex Institute |oclc=248257682}}</ref>\n\nIn 1897, the shoal became a [[Third French Republic|French]] possession, later being placed under the administration of a commissioner residing in [[R\u00e9union]] in 1968. [[Madagascar]] became independent in 1960 and claims sovereignty over the shoal since 1972.\n\n== Tourism ==\n[[Mooring (watercraft)|Mooring]] at Bassas da India requires a permit from the French Government.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://taaf.fr/acceder-aux-territoires/demandes-dactivites-et-dacces/acces-et-mouillage-dans-les-eparses/ |title=Acc\u00e8s et mouillage dans les Eparses |trans-title=Access and mooring in the Scattered Islands |language=fr |access-date=2020-02-03 |website=TAAF : Terres australes et antarctiques fran\u00e7aises |publisher=Government of France}}</ref> Fishing without such a permit may result in the boat being expelled or even confiscated.<ref>{{cite act |url=http://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/affichTexte.do?cidTexte=JORFTEXT000000880593&dateTexte=19960708 |index=83-582 |date=5 July 1983 |title=Loi n\u00b0 83-582 du 5 juillet 1983 relative au r\u00e9gime de la saisie et compl\u00e9tant la liste des agents habilit\u00e9s \u00e0 constater les infractions dans le domaine des p\u00eaches maritimes |publisher=Government of France |language=fr}}</ref> Several illegal tourism charters departing from Mozambique or South Africa have been seized since 2013 by the [[French navy]].<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.defense.gouv.fr/operations/prepositionnees/actualites/fazsoi-operation-combinee-de-controle-des-peches-dans-le-canal-du-mozambique |title=FAZSOI : Op\u00e9ration combin\u00e9e de contr\u00f4le des p\u00eaches dans le canal du Mozambique |trans-title=FAZSOI: Combined fisheries control operation in the Mozambique Channel |language=fr |publisher=[[French Ministry of Defense]] |date=2013-11-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.ipreunion.com/evenements/reportage/2014/10/09/iles-parses-peche-non-autorisee-le-floreal-intercepte-un-bateau-au-large-de-bassas-da-india,27539.html |title=P\u00eache non autoris\u00e9e : le ''Flor\u00e9al'' intercepte un bateau au large de Bassas da India |trans-title=Unauthorized fishing : the ''[[French frigate Flor\u00e9al|Flor\u00e9al]]'' intercepts a boat off Bassas da India |language=fr |publisher=Imaz Press R\u00e9union |date=9 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Bassas da India atoll map-fr.png|Detailed map.\nFile:Bassas_da_india.jpg|[[International Space Station|ISS]] photograph.\nFile:Bassas da India.png|[[Landsat program|Landsat 7]] image.\nFile:Bassas da India-CIA WFB Map.png|[[The World Factbook|CIA World Factbook]] map.\nFile:Bassas da india 76.jpg|[[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]] map.\nFile:Bassas da India in Sunglint.jpg|ISS image of Bassas da India with varying degrees of sunglint.\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite magazine|title=A tale of two atolls|magazine=National Geographic|date=April 2014|first=Kennedy|last=Warne|pp=62\u201375}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Bassas da India}}\n\n*{{wikiatlas|Bassas da India}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.oceandots.com/indian/mozambique-channel/bassas-da-india.php |title=Oceandots |accessdate=2009-03-14 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101223043232/http://www.oceandots.com/indian/mozambique-channel/bassas-da-india.php |archivedate=23 December 2010 |df=dmy }}\n*[http://permanent.access.gpo.gov/websites/pollux/pollux.nss.nima.mil/NAV_PUBS/SD/pub171/171sec09.pdf Sailing Directions: East Africa and the South Indian Ocean]\n*{{CIA World Factbook link|fs|French Southern and Antarctic Lands}}.\n\n{{French overseas departments and territories |Uninhabited}}\n{{Outlying territories of European countries}}\n{{Scattered islands in the Indian Ocean}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bassas da India}}\n\n[[Category:Indian Ocean atolls of France]]\n[[Category:Atolls of Madagascar]]\n[[Category:Uninhabited islands of France]]\n[[Category:Islands of the French Southern and Antarctic Lands]]\n[[Category:Territorial disputes of France]]\n[[Category:Territorial disputes of Madagascar]]\n[[Category:France\u2013Madagascar relations]]\n", "text_old": "{{Expand French|Bassas da India|date=February 2017|topic=geo}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{coord|21|28|57|S|39|40|19|E|region:FR-TF_type:isle|display=title}}\n{{Infobox country\n|conventional_long_name = Bassas da India\n|native_name = ''Bassas da India''\n|image_flag = Flag of the French Southern and Antarctic Lands.svg\n|image_coat =\n|symbol_type = Coat of arms\n|national_motto=\"[[Libert\u00e9, \u00e9galit\u00e9, fraternit\u00e9]]\"\n|national_anthem = ''[[La Marseillaise]]''\n|image_map = Iles eparses de l'ocean Indien.svg\n|map_caption = Location of the [[Scattered islands in the Indian Ocean]]. <div style=\"text-align:left;margin-left:8.0em;\">{{vunblist |1. Bassas da India |2. [[Europa Island]] |3. [[Glorioso Islands]] |4. [[Juan de Nova Island]] |5. [[Tromelin Island]]}}</div>\n}}\n\n'''Bassas da India''' ({{IPA-fr|basa da \u025b\u0303dja}}) is an uninhabited, roughly circular French [[atoll]] that is part of the [[French Southern and Antarctic Lands]]. Located in the southern [[Mozambique Channel]], about halfway between [[Mozambique]] and [[Madagascar]] (about {{convert|385|km|abbr=on|disp=sqbr}} further east) and around {{convert|110|km|abbr=on}} northwest of [[Europa Island]], the rim of the atoll averages around {{convert|100|m}} in width and encloses a shallow lagoon of depth no greater than {{convert|15|m|abbr=on}}. Overall, the atoll is about {{convert|10|km|abbr=on}} in diameter, rising steeply from the [[seabed]] {{convert|3000|m}} below to encircle an area (including lagoon) of {{convert|80|km2|abbr=on}}. Its [[exclusive economic zone]] (EEZ), {{convert|123700|km\u00b2|abbr=on}} in size, is [[Contiguous zone|contiguous]] with that of Europa Island.\n\nThe atoll consists of ten barren rocky islets, with no vegetation, totalling {{convert|20|ha}} in area. Those on the north and east sides are {{convert|7|to|10|ft|order=flip}} high, while those on the west and south sides are {{convert|4|ft|order=flip}} high. The reef, whose coastline measures {{convert|35.2|km|abbr=on}}, is completely covered by the sea from three hours before [[Tide|high tide]] to three hours afterward. The region is also subject to [[cyclone]]s, making the atoll a long-time maritime hazard and the site of numerous shipwrecks.\n\n[[Jaguar Seamount]] and [[Hall Tablemount]] lie, respectively, about {{convert|40|and|70|km}} further southwest.\n\n== History ==\n\nThe Bassas da India was first recorded by [[Portuguese explorers]] in the early sixteenth century as the \"'''''Baixo da'' Judia'''\" (\"''Jewess'' Shoals\"). The ''Judia'' (\"''Jewess''\", for the ancestry of its owner [[Fern\u00e3o de Loronha]]<ref>{{cite contribution |title=Rela\u00e7am do navfragio da nao Santiago & itenerario da gente que delle se salvou |last=Cardozo |first=Manoel Godinho |orig-year=First published 1602 |editor-first=Bernardo |editor-last=Gomes de Brito |work=[[Hist\u00f3ria tr\u00e1gico-mar\u00edtima]] |page=[https://archive.org/details/historiatragicom02brit/page/n193/ 47] |location=Lisbon |publisher=Off. da Congrega\u00e7ao do Oratorio |volume=Volume II |date=1736}}</ref>) was the Portuguese ship that discovered the feature by running aground on it in 1506.<ref>{{cite journal |first=Brian R. |last=Stuckenberg |title=The location and identity of the Baixos da Judia : Portuguese historical cartography of the Mozambique Channel and its relevance to the wreck of the Santiago in 1585 |work=Natal Museum Journal of Humanities |volume=12 |publisher=Council of the Natal Museum |location=Pietermaritzburg, South Africa |pages=51\u201379 |date=December 2000 |issn=1015-0935}}</ref> The name became \"'''Bassas da India'''\" due to transcription errors by cartographers. The ''Santiago'' broke up on the shoal in 1585.\n\nIt was rediscovered by the ''Europa'' in 1774, whence the name \"Europa Rocks\".<ref>{{cite book |quote=Bassas da India, sometimes named Europa rocks, was discovered by the ship ''Europa'' in 1774. |author-first=Algernon F. R. |author-last=de Horsey |title=The Africa Pilot, Part III : South and east coasts of Africa from the Cape of Good Hope to Cape Guardafui, including the islands in the Mozambique Channel |publisher=[[United Kingdom Hydrographic Office|Hydrographic Office of Great Britain]] |location=London |edition=3rd |date=1878 |page=410 |oclc=36761841}}</ref> The ''Malay'' was lost 27 July 1842 on the Europa Rocks.<ref>{{cite book |first1=Chas. S. |last1=Osgood |first2=H. M. |last2=Batchelder |title=Historical Sketch of Salem, 1626\u20131879 |date=1879 |location=Salem |publisher=Essex Institute |oclc=248257682}}</ref>\n\nIn 1897, the shoal became a [[Third French Republic|French]] possession, later being placed under the administration of a commissioner residing in [[R\u00e9union]] in 1968. [[Madagascar]] became independent in 1960 and claims sovereignty over the shoal since 1972.\n\n== Tourism ==\n\n[[Mooring (watercraft)|Mooring]] at Bassas da India requires a permit from the French Government.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://taaf.fr/acceder-aux-territoires/demandes-dactivites-et-dacces/acces-et-mouillage-dans-les-eparses/ |title=Acc\u00e8s et mouillage dans les Eparses |trans-title=Access and mooring in the Scattered Islands |language=fr |access-date=2020-02-03 |website=TAAF : Terres australes et antarctiques fran\u00e7aises |publisher=Government of France}}</ref> Fishing without such a permit may result in the boat being expelled or even confiscated.<ref>{{cite act |url=http://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/affichTexte.do?cidTexte=JORFTEXT000000880593&dateTexte=19960708 |index=83-582 |date=5 July 1983 |title=Loi n\u00b0 83-582 du 5 juillet 1983 relative au r\u00e9gime de la saisie et compl\u00e9tant la liste des agents habilit\u00e9s \u00e0 constater les infractions dans le domaine des p\u00eaches maritimes |publisher=Government of France |language=fr}}</ref> Several illegal tourism charters departing from Mozambique or South Africa have been seized since 2013 by the [[French navy]].<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.defense.gouv.fr/operations/prepositionnees/actualites/fazsoi-operation-combinee-de-controle-des-peches-dans-le-canal-du-mozambique |title=FAZSOI : Op\u00e9ration combin\u00e9e de contr\u00f4le des p\u00eaches dans le canal du Mozambique |trans-title=FAZSOI: Combined fisheries control operation in the Mozambique Channel |language=fr |publisher=[[French Ministry of Defense]] |date=2013-11-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.ipreunion.com/evenements/reportage/2014/10/09/iles-parses-peche-non-autorisee-le-floreal-intercepte-un-bateau-au-large-de-bassas-da-india,27539.html |title=P\u00eache non autoris\u00e9e : le ''Flor\u00e9al'' intercepte un bateau au large de Bassas da India |trans-title=Unauthorized fishing : the ''[[French frigate Flor\u00e9al|Flor\u00e9al]]'' intercepts a boat off Bassas da India |language=fr |publisher=Imaz Press R\u00e9union |date=9 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Bassas da India atoll map-fr.png|Detailed map.\nFile:Bassas_da_india.jpg|[[International Space Station|ISS]] photograph.\nFile:Bassas da India.png|[[Landsat program|Landsat 7]] image.\nFile:Bassas da India-CIA WFB Map.png|[[The World Factbook|CIA World Factbook]] map.\nFile:Bassas da india 76.jpg|[[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]] map.\nFile:Bassas da India in Sunglint.jpg|ISS image of Bassas da India with varying degrees of sunglint.\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite magazine|title=A tale of two atolls|magazine=National Geographic|date=April 2014|first=Kennedy|last=Warne|pp=62\u201375}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Bassas da India}}\n*{{wikiatlas|Bassas da India}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.oceandots.com/indian/mozambique-channel/bassas-da-india.php |title=Oceandots |accessdate=2009-03-14 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101223043232/http://www.oceandots.com/indian/mozambique-channel/bassas-da-india.php |archivedate=23 December 2010 |df=dmy }}\n*[http://permanent.access.gpo.gov/websites/pollux/pollux.nss.nima.mil/NAV_PUBS/SD/pub171/171sec09.pdf Sailing Directions: East Africa and the South Indian Ocean]\n*{{CIA World Factbook link|fs|French Southern and Antarctic Lands}}.\n\n{{Scattered islands in the Indian Ocean}}\n{{French overseas departments and territories |Uninhabited}}\n{{Outlying territories of European countries}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bassas da India}}\n[[Category:Indian Ocean atolls of France]]\n[[Category:Atolls of Madagascar]]\n[[Category:Uninhabited islands of France]]\n[[Category:Islands of the French Southern and Antarctic Lands]]\n[[Category:Territorial disputes of France]]\n[[Category:Territorial disputes of Madagascar]]\n[[Category:France\u2013Madagascar relations]]\n", "name_user": "Kenwick", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bassas_da_India"}
